<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Broadly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell broadly against major European  
currencies Tuesday as data showed Germany's economy stronger than 
expected, signaling that surrounding stagnant economies could be 
expanding. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also fell against the yen as rumors surfaced that a  
major upcoming economic report will show Japan may be finally 
recovering from its devastating recession. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0458, up  
from $1.0286 late Monday and its most recent record low of $1.0260, 
set in the opening of trading in London Monday. In other late 
trading Tuesday, the dollar was quoted at 118.88 Japanese yen, down 
from 120.80 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders liked several pieces of news Tuesday, including a report  
showing that Germany's gross domestic product rose 0.7 percent on 
an annual basis, against an expected growth rate of 0.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro has been sliding since its inception in January as  
Europe's economies have lagged. The German economy is the world's 
third largest and the largest in Europe, and has not been able to 
help the flagging economies in the 11 countries the euro 
represents. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the president-designate of Germany's central bank,  
Ernst Welteke, said there was cause for concern regarding the 
euro's slide, allowing traders to speculate about possible 
intervention. That counters the majority of comments made by 
European monetary officials, who have seemed calm in the face of 
the euro's double-digit percentage fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also lost support Tuesday as the Dow Jones industrial  
average fell 143.74 to 10,765.64. Bond prices also fell. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market's been looking for an excuse to rally after weeks  
and months of (euro) lows,'' said Ben Strauss, a vice president of 
foreign exchange at Bank Julius Baer &AMP; Co. There was enough going 
on ``to get people to come out and take profit on the dollar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, there were rumors in Japan that a report due Thursday  
would show that country's GDP growing, perhaps indicating that 
Japan has turned the corner in the country's fight against its 
worst recession since World War II. The data are consistent with 
recent reports showing strength in other areas, said Jay Bryson, an 
international economist at First Union Capital Markets in 
Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is all starting to sound pretty convincing,'' Bryson said  
of Japan's possible recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In other late trading, the dollar also was quoted at 1.5224  
Swiss francs, down from 1.5436, and 1.4753 Canadian dollars, up 
from 1.4685. The British pound rose to $1.6049 from $1.6005. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth: 
1.8702 German marks, down from 1.9015; 6.2735 French francs, down 
from 6.3776; and 1,851.85 Italian lire, down from 1,883.24. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
