<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 143.74  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The fear of higher interest rates returned to  
Wall Street today after a three-session hiatus, sending blue-chip 
stocks and bond prices sharply lower. The Dow Jones industrial 
average fell 143.74 to close at 10,765.64. Broader stock indicators 
also fell. The Nasdaq composite index was down 48.98 to 2,475.23. 
Major market averages had rallied in recent days as new economic 
data suggested the nation's unprecedented growth may be continuing 
without rising inflation. Analysts said many investors had 
abandoned a belief that the Federal Reserve would raise interest 
rates to stifle inflation when its Open Market Committee meets June 
29. But today, William Poole, president of the Federal Reserve Bank 
of St. Louis suggested that he believed inflation has returned to 
the economy. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,765.64 - 143.74
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1135  Declines 1794  Unchgd  620
NYSE Volume:         647,633,910
Most Active NYSE issue:         Compaq Computer22 15/16 -   15/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1317.33 - 17.19
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          772.92  -  5.23
Nasdaq Composite Index:       2,475.23  - 48.98
Gold(final) -    $262.80    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Off-Peak Summer Flights Discounted  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Major airlines cut ticket prices today by as much  
as 25 percent for off-peak summer travel. United Airlines set off 
the fare war and others including Delta Air Lines, Continental 
Airlines and Northwest Airlines joined the matched the United 
promotion on domestic and international travel. Under the 
promotion, consumers who purchase tickets for advance travel only 
on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Saturdays could see as much as a 25 
percent discount over regularly priced tickets. The promotion, in 
which tickets must be purchased by June 18, applies to travel 
through the end of September. The airline also capped advanced 
round-trip ticket purchases for peak travel days at $498. 

</P>
<P>
	Productivity Rises in 1st Quarter  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- American workers' productivity increased at an  
annual rate of 3.5 percent in the first three months of the year 
while wage pressures remained well contained, the government said 
today. The 3.5 percent increase in output per hour worked 
represented a slight downward adjustment of the earlier estimate. A 
key measurement of inflationary pressures was revised up slightly 
in today's report. Unit labor costs, the amount of compensation per 
unit of output, edged up 0.7 percent at an annual rate in the first 
quarter, compared to an original estimate of a 0.3 percent 
increase. 

</P>
<P>
	Businesses Urge Passage of Y2K Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The heads of the nation's major business and  
high-tech groups urged Congress and the White House today to enact 
legislation protecting them from being battered by Y2K-related 
lawsuits. The Y2K litigation bill, which could return to the Senate 
floor this week, is the number one priority of the high-tech 
industry, Harris Miller, president of the Information Technology 
Association of America, said at a news conference on Capitol Hill. 
President Jerry Jasinowski of the National Association of 
Manufacturers also pushed for the bill sponsored by Sens. John 
McCain, R-Ariz., Ron Wyden, D-Ore., and Christopher Dodd, D-Conn. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Exec Testifies on Microsoft  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a second day of testimony damaging to  
Microsoft, an IBM manager accused the software giant today of 
dangling valuable discounts for Windows if IBM agreed not to 
distribute rival software on its line of personal computers. IBM 
manager Garry Norris testified at the federal anti-trust trial that 
Microsoft executive Bengt Ackerlind told him clearly in a March 
1997 meeting: ``No Netscape.'' The government showed U.S. District 
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson the notes handwritten by Norris 
regarding that meeting, when Microsoft Corp. allegedly offered to 
increase rebates available under its so-called Market Development 
Agreements if IBM promised not to include Internet software from 
Netscape Communications Corp. in the personal computers it sold. 

</P>
<P>
	Saturn Extends an Engine Warranty  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Saturn Corp. has extended the warranty on 363,000  
engines to cover costly cylinder head cracks that have occurred in 
a small percentage of its 1994-96 model-year cars. The small-car 
subsidiary of General Motors Corp. said the warranty extension is 
for its single-overhead-cam, 4-cylinder engines only. The cracks 
are estimated to affect only about 5 percent of the engines 
produced during the three model years, spokeswoman Julie Hamp said 
Tuesday. The warranty is extended to six years or 100,000 miles, 
whichever comes first, from the regular powertrain warranty of 
three years or 36,000 miles. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. May Ease Computer Export Rules  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Clinton administration is making plans to  
ease government restrictions on the sale of high-powered computers 
to more than 100 countries, the Los Angeles Times reported today. 
The Commerce Department has proposed changes in export rules on 
sales to most countries in Asia, Africa, Latin America and Central 
and Eastern Europe, unidentified administration sources told the 
Times. The administration, however, will not loosen restrictions on 
China and some 50 other countries, the newspaper reported. 
Administration officials who spoke to the Times on condition of 
anonymity said the White House has not yet determined how much to 
ease controls 

</P>
<P>
	Report: China Internet Cafes Close  
</P>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- Police have closed some 300 cafes in  
Shanghai for offering Internet services without required licenses, 
the Shanghai Star newspaper reported today. The closures, which 
came during a crackdown last week, appeared to be part of efforts 
to silence potential sources of dissent around last Friday's 
anniversary of the bloody 1989 crackdown on pro-democracy protests 
centered on Beijing's Tiananmen Square. Cafes with computer 
terminals that sell Internet access by the hour are common in 
China, but they operate under increasingly strict rules. Operators 
must pass a police check, and users are required to register. 

</P>
<P>
	Nortel To Combine Voice, Data, Video  
</P>
<P>
	BRAMPTON, Ontario (AP) -- Nortel Networks Corp. today unveiled 11  
new products and enhancements to others in an effort to strengthen 
its position in the market for integrated data and voice networks. 
The products range from the basic Inca Telecommuter, which allows a 
computer to be used as both a voice and data terminal over a single 
analog line, to the more sophisticated i3220 Internet Phone, which 
will provide the front end for intelligent networks. The company 
said the items will be available within a year. 

</P>
<P>
	Australia Nixes Coke-Cadbury Deal  
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australian regulators have rejected for  
the second time Coca-Cola Co.'s plan to buy soft drink brands in 
Australia from Cadbury Schweppes PLC on the grounds it would reduce 
competition. The Australian Competition &AMP; Consumer Commission 
announced today the decision against the revised proposal. It 
rejected the initial plan in March. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Productivity: up 3.5 percent at annual rate  
</P>
<P>
	Thursday: Jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Producer prices  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
