<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 00:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Researchers Looking at Web's Effects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Internet's impact on society, from its  
effect on families to how it's changing the world economy, will be 
tracked in an unprecedented study funded in part by rivals America 
Online Inc. and Microsoft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The project announced Tuesday by the University of California,  
Los Angeles, will follow not only computer and Internet use but 
also nonusage in the United States and other countries for at least 
a generation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet is transforming how we work, how we play and how  
we learn,'' said Jeffrey Cole, the study's principal investigator 
and director of the UCLA Center for Communication Policy. ``There 
isn't anything that's not going to be affected by this 
technology.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's the sort of research scientists should have conducted on  
television when it first became available in the late 1940s and 
early 1950s, said Cole, whose center conducts studies on network TV 
violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem with television was that nobody was in the  
households to watch what happened,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 50 percent of U.S. households have computers and  
about a third of those use the Internet. Usage varies widely in 
other parts of the world, from a high percentage of residents in 
Singapore to very few households in parts of Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers will examine how family time, political leanings and  
social life are affected by a new computer purchase. Do people 
spend less time watching television or talking to their families? 
Do they become more liberal? More politically active? 
</P>
<P>
	The study also will track online banking, shopping and buying  
habits, comfort with using credit cards and how e-mail affects 
other forms of communication. Do they shop online and buy at a 
store or shop at a store and buy online? How does it change the way 
people work? 
</P>
<P>
	The average participant will probably answer about 100  
questions, Cole said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is to do it year by year, stay with the same families  
and watch the migration and the change in attitudes,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft and America Online both said the study will be used to  
better serve their customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of those times where an industrywide effort helps  
everyone,'' said Brad Chase, vice president of Microsoft Corp.'s 
Consumer and Commerce Group. ``We're taking the Internet in its 
infancy and helping it grow so we can do the right thing so 
everyone can get the most out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cole said the sponsors, which also include The Walt Disney Co.  
and Sony, will not influence the questions or analysis. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, 2,000 randomly selected people mirroring  
the nation's ethnic, economic and geographic makeup will be 
followed during the study, with people added as others drop out. 
Most will be surveyed by telephone. He estimates the study's margin 
of error will be about 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore and Italy will also be studied in the first year;  
another dozen countries will be added in the next three to five 
years. Results will be presented annually, starting next year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
