<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 16:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers Rice Philosophical of Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Jerry Rice spent the offseason  
confronting his football mortality and he insisted Tuesday he's 
learning to deal with it. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, guys, basically it's coming to an end and I don't  
want to go out on a sour note,'' said the 36-year-old Rice, who 
joined the San Francisco 49ers for the opening of a four-day, 
full-squad minicamp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to go out feeling good about my career, enjoying the  
game of football,'' he said. Asked if this would be his last 
season, Rice laughed and said, ``No, no, no, no, no, no. I'm not 
saying that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL's leading career receiver earned his 12th Pro Bowl  
invitation last season. 
</P>
<P>
	But he conceded his comeback season from two devastating knee  
injuries was marred by his grousing over a diminished role as 
Terrell Owens and J.J. Stokes became the focus on more and more 
plays. Both Owens and Stokes have been re-signed by the 49ers, 
preserving the team's triple threat at wide receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was not happy about what was going on with me, how I was  
dealing with the situation,'' Rice said. ``I said to myself that 
I've got to completely turn this thing around. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to be able to carry this team like I used to. I  
just want to go in there and try to be a factor, just try to help 
the young guys as much as possible and just enjoy. I'm not going to 
say I'm going to get too relaxed. When my number is called, I want 
to make the play and get it done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After so many years as the offensive focal point, Rice said it's  
tough accepting a reduced role. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's time for me to just kick back and enjoy this game,''  
Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also came to the realization that he had little choice.  
Owens, who led the team with 14 touchdown catches in 1998, and 
Stokes have developed into important playmakers in their own right 
and with running back Garrison Hearst also in the mix, San 
Francisco's offense operates best when quarterback Steve Young 
spreads the ball around. 
</P>
<P>
	That point was driven home even more when the 49ers kept both  
potential free agents, re-signing Stokes in March and designating 
Owens as a franchise player, effectively limiting his free agency 
movement. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, Owens signed his $3.5 million tender offer for this  
season with the expectation the two sides will work out a longterm 
deal in the coming weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think for Terrell, to have that behind him, it's a relief,''  
coach Steve Mariucci said. ``The talks on a longterm deal are still 
going and that should get done. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to see not just Terrell, but the Three Amigos,  
Jerry, J.J. and Terrell. You line up with those three guys across 
the board, that's exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That image also helped foster the new philosophical approach by  
Rice, who also drew from watching David Robinson accept a change in 
his role with the emergence of Tim Duncan as the San Antonio Spurs' 
chief playmaker. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to step away but I've just got to let go,'' Rice  
said. ``I look at it just like David Robinson, the role he has 
taken now. I think he's dealing with that situation very, very well 
and for him to be able to step back like that, it really showed me 
a lot. Well, that's my role now and that's exactly how I'm going to 
approach it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Owens, meanwhile, said he's glad to have his future stabilized  
and looks forward to another season playing beside Stokes and Rice. 
</P>
<P>
	He added he believes San Francisco's offense can duplicate or  
exceed last year's performance, when it finished at the top of the 
NFL rankings in passing and rushing yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think keeping us together is just going to make us that more  
special,'' Owens said. ``You don't get three receivers with the 
talent that we have on a team very often. You've got those guys 
over in Minnesota. They've got their thing going but we've got to 
keep the Bay together. We've got a great group of young guys making 
some plays.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
