<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Inhofe To Protest Hormel Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Conservative Republican Sen. James Inhofe  
threatened Tuesday to hold up ``every single presidential 
nomination'' to protest President Clinton's appointment of a gay 
philanthropist to be ambassador to Luxembourg. 
</P>
<P>
	Inhofe, R-Okla., criticized Clinton for invoking a provision of  
the Constitution allowing him to bypass the Senate confirmation 
process by making a temporary appointment while Congress is in 
recess. Congress returned from a week-long Memorial Day break on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., joined Inhofe in  
criticizing Clinton, saying the president's move to appoint James 
Hormel on Friday was ``a subversion of the confirmation process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Lott indicated he was unlikely to go along with Inhofe's  
blanket objection to presidential nominations. Several high-profile 
nominations are currently before the Senate, including that of 
Lawrence Summers to be treasury secretary and Richard Holbrooke to 
be ambassador to the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Hormel, the former dean of the University of Chicago law school  
and a well-known San Francisco fund-raiser, is the nation's first 
openly gay U.S. ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	By custom, any senator can block a presidential nomination by  
placing a parliamentary ``hold'' on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Inhofe said he was acting on a precedent set by Sen. Robert  
Byrd, D-W.Va., who in 1985 placed holds on President Reagan's 
appointments until Reagan agreed to refrain from making recess 
appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	However, there is no formal rule on such ``holds,'' and they do  
not have to be honored by the Senate majority leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, despite his own opposition to Hormel's nomination, told  
reporters it ``would not be my inclination'' to allow any single 
senator to manage to single-handedly block every nomination. ``I 
wouldn't honor a hold indefinitely,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he conceded that Inhofe still had the right to use  
delaying tactics to slow down nominations on a case-by-case basis -- 
tactics that require a 60-vote majority in the 100-member Senate to 
overcome. 
</P>
<P>
	``President Clinton has shown contempt for the Congress and the  
Constitution,'' Inhofe, R-Okla., said in a statement Monday. He 
called the appointment ``highly inappropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The president has forfeited the presumption of cooperation on  
any remaining appointments he wants to make while in office,'' 
Inhofe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton announced the ``recess appointment'' of Hormel last  
Friday. He made the appointment after a small group of conservative 
senators, led by Inhofe, was able to block the nomination for a 
year and a half -- and after Lott refused to bring it to the floor 
for a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Inhofe at first listed seven nominations to which he was  
objecting. But Tuesday, in a Senate floor speech, Inhofe expanded 
his list, telling colleagues: ``I am putting holds on every single 
presidential nomination that comes from the White House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he wasn't opposed to Hormel just because he was gay.  
``It is the fact that he is a gay activist that puts his agenda 
ahead of the agenda of America,'' Inhofe said. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven original nominees to which Inhofe has objected are:  
</P>
<P>
	--Gary S. Guzy of Washington, D.C., to be assistant administrator  
of the Environmental Protection Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	--Diane Edith Watson of California, to be ambassador to  
Micronesia. 
</P>
<P>
	--Kenneth M. Bresnahan of Virginia, to be chief financial officer  
of the Labor Department. 
</P>
<P>
	--Carolyn L. Huntoon of Virginia to be assistant secretary of  
energy for environmental management. 
</P>
<P>
	--George T. Frampton, Jr., of Washington, D.C., to be a member of  
the Council on Environmental Quality. 
</P>
<P>
	--John T. Spotila of New Jersey, to be administrator of the  
Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs for the Office of 
Management and Budget. 
</P>
<P>
	--Thomas J. Erickson of Washington, D.C., to be a commissioner of  
the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
