<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $13M Crisis Center Opens in NYC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A $13 million high-tech emergency center here  
has opened to criticism from some city officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50,000-square-foot complex was designed to serve as the  
command post during emergencies, but some city council members say 
the $1.4 million annual rent makes it little more than an expensive 
bunker for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and his aides. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an incredible amount of money to enhance somebody else's  
property,'' Councilwoman Kathryn Freed said. ``We had a 
state-of-the-art emergency center in police headquarters, and I 
still don't understand why we needed this one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Housed on the 23rd floor of a building near the twin towers of  
the World Trade Center, the center was built to withstand 
hurricane-force winds, bombs and power failures, and features walls 
reinforced with steel and Kevlar. It also has some of the world's 
most high-tech telecommunications and computer equipment, on which 
city officials can analyze digitized photos of sensitive subway, 
sewage and water lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Three generators guarantee continuous power, and there's enough  
food and water to sustain 100 city, state and federal officials for 
a few days. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the threats confronting the city of New York for at least  
the next 50 years or so, this facility is probably as secure as it 
needs to be,'' said Jerry Hauer, head of the city's Office of 
Emergency Management. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, city officials gave opening day tours to the media  
and participated in a simulated terrorist drill. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is really state of the art -- the best I've seen,'' said  
Col. Robert Fitton of the Pentagon, one of the federal officials in 
the drill. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
