<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Release Cornerback Canty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- The New England Patriots gave up on former  
first-round draft pick Chris Canty, releasing the cornerback 
Tuesday after two years with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Canty started the first nine games last season at right  
cornerback before being replaced by Steve Israel for the last seven 
games. Canty started one game as a rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	By releasing Canty, the 29th pick in the 1997 draft out of  
Kansas State, the Patriots gain salary cap room to sign their 1999 
draft choices. 
</P>
<P>
	Canty also struggled for most of the two years.  
</P>
<P>
	``Chris did not take full advantage of his opportunity with the  
Patriots,'' coach Pete Carroll said. ``I'm encouraged by the work 
and commitment shown by many of our players and expect great 
competition at that position in camp this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the veterans at right cornerback are Israel, 1998  
first-round pick Tebucky Jones and Kato Serwanga. All-Pro Ty Law 
plays the other cornerback position. 
</P>
<P>
	Canty, 23, had 79 tackles, one interception and three sacks in  
his two seasons. The interception came against Peyton Manning, the 
top pick in last year's NFL draft, in the Patriots' home opener 
against Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Canty also played last season on special teams, returning 11  
kickoffs for 198 yards and 16 punts for 170 yards. He had eight 
special teams tackles. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
