<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues New commodities Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- China completed an overhaul of its  
commodities exchanges Tuesday by announcing new rules that strip 
local authorities of the power to regulate trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The reforms, begun last year, reduced the number of exchanges  
from 14 to three and standardized regulation that had been in the 
hands of local officials who sometimes manipulated markets for 
their own benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules ban trading outside the markets and give the main  
government regulator, the China Securities Regulatory Commission, 
power to decide who runs the exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	That mirrors changes imposed last year on securities markets  
after years of haphazard, locally run regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules, announced by the official Xinhua News Agency, impose  
guidelines for traders and brokerages. Violators can be fined up to 
$60,000 or imprisoned. 
</P>
<P>
	Exchanges in Shanghai, the central city of Zhengzhou and the  
northeastern city of Dalian trade rubber, cotton, copper, aluminum, 
grain and other farm products. 
</P>
<P>
	Xinhua said the new rules were temporary, but would remain in  
place until China's legislature passes national regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Since last year, regulators have tried to tighten oversight of  
China's commodities exchanges, raising margin requirements and 
auditing brokerages. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of brokerages have been closed for irregularities.  
</P>
<P>
	Traders say as many as half of China's 300 futures-trading firms  
could close because of stricter regulation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
