<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Show Adds Sound to Mime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shane Dundas says he wanted to drag pantomime  
into the 1990s and decided the answer was sound. 
</P>
<P>
	So, on stage at off-Broadway's Minetta Lane Theater, Dundas,  
with a microphone, and David Collins, generally silent as the mime 
or ``action guy,'' are performing a zany show named ``Thwak.'' They 
bill themselves as the Umbilical Brothers. 
</P>
<P>
	It's whimsical, inventive and clever but, because it's basically  
vaudevillian comedy, without a plot or even a real thread, it can 
wear out its welcome even though it lasts only 80 minutes. While 
some in the audience were finding it hilarious, we found the 
whimsy's appeal evaporating quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	With his mouth, Dundas makes more noises than Bobby McFerrin.  
The evening starts with Collins miming fighting a big animal and 
bees while Dundas makes their noises. An imaginary dog is thrown 
and heard to splatter, a tank is driven and a grenade explodes -- 
all from Dundas' mouth. ``No dogs were harmed during that last 
sequence,'' he intones. 
</P>
<P>
	As the show progresses, Collins becomes the nice guy and Dundas  
the meanie. A short wall emerges and they go behind it and lift up 
hand puppets. Dundas is cruel to a cute bunny puppet, which makes 
Collins cry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Umbilical Brothers work hard to present variety. There are a  
couple of rather tame skits in which the two play stiff German 
comics. At different times each declares, ``All the imaginary 
props, I made them. I'm the creative force behind this show.'' 
During a musical interlude, Collins promises five hours of ballads 
and Dundas rattles marbles in a bucket. Horses are heard to gallop 
on, jump into water and get shot. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thwak'' moved off-Broadway from the off-off-Broadway Westbeth  
Theater. Philip WM. McKinley, whose credits include the circus, 
directed. Collins and Dundas, who created the show they perform, 
met as drama students in Sydney, Australia. Since 1991, they have 
toured widely. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
