<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Cup Goalies Set for Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Dominik Hasek put two frustrating seasons playing  
behind Ed Belfour to good use. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest, I watched him every game, even during practice,  
looking at him to see what he was doing,'' Hasek said Monday, a day 
before his Buffalo Sabres meet Belfour's Dallas Stars in Game 1 of 
the Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour was the starter and Hasek the backup for Chicago in  
1990-91 and '91-92. The Blackhawks had hockey's best record the 
first season, and they reached the Stanley Cup finals the next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour played 145 regular-season and playoff games in that  
span. Hasek was used in 31, then was traded to Buffalo the next 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	With plenty of time on the bench in Chicago, Hasek studied every  
aspect of Belfour's game. One of the things Hasek noticed most was 
Belfour's feet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's a very good skater,'' Hasek said. ``He always  
tries to be in the right position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When either is caught away from the net, both get back by using  
a skating style akin to pedaling. Hasek said it's not a 
coincidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he started to pedal on the ice before I started to do  
it,'' Hasek said. ``I don't know who started to do it first. Many 
people say I was the first, but I think he was the first to pedal 
on the ice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour said he remembers Hasek forcing him to always play his  
best, even in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were always competitive in the drills,'' Belfour said.  
``He'd always compete hard and so would I. It made us both 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither goalie has been in the finals since the Blackhawks were  
swept by Pittsburgh seven seasons ago. Whoever wins this series 
will bring his franchise its first title. 
</P>
<P>
	Every hockey player works his entire life for the chance to put  
his name on the Cup. It's especially significant to be the starting 
goalie on a championship team. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek already has earned a reputation as the world's best  
goalie, even without a title. Belfour, however, is often considered 
a second-tier player because he hasn't been a winner when it 
matters most. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are going to say whatever they dream up,'' Belfour  
said. ``I know what I've done and what I can do. My teammates 
always support me and back me and that's all that matters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek also says the label is unfair.  
</P>
<P>
	``Eddie is a great goaltender and a very competitive person,''  
Hasek said. ``I don't think he gets enough credit because he never 
won the Stanley Cup. I don't think he has any weaknesses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The goalies insist they are friendly rivals. Hasek added that  
their wives are close and that their kids played together for 
several hours at this year's All-Star Game. 
</P>
<P>
	If there was any tension during their Chicago days, both say it  
was nothing more than a healthy dose of competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a tough relationship because he felt I was the person  
who could take his job and I felt he took my job,'' Hasek said. 
``When we see each other off the ice now, we always say hello. I 
respect him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour smiled and laughed when asked if there was a problem  
with their 1-2 status in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't see anything wrong with it,'' he said. ``Maybe he had  
a problem with it because I was the No. 1 guy. But I didn't ever 
have a problem with Dominik. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always enjoyed the challenge of competing against  
Dominik, even when it was in practice. He's a competitor and I love 
competition. I think it's going to be a great opportunity to play 
against him again.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
