<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Ganga To Resign Olympic Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Jean-Claude Ganga, expelled  
from the International Olympic Committee for corruption, plans to 
resign in September as president of the Association of National 
Olympic Committees of Africa, a South African official said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has no choice,'' Dan Moyo, secretary general of the  
National Olympic Committee of South Africa, said in a telephone 
interview. ``His own Olympic committee in Congo excluded him in May 
elections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moyo said ANOCA bylaws bar the organization from expelling  
Ganga, who participates in the organization as an individual. He 
was elected president by the ANOCA general assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Ganga announced his intention to resign at a Paris meeting in  
May of the worldwide Association of National Olympics Committees, 
Moyo said. He said Ganga would resign at a special ANOCA meeting in 
September in Johannesburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Moyo did not know why Ganga was waiting to resign.  
</P>
<P>
	``That question you can ask him,'' Moyo said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ganga could not be reached for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Ganga and five other IOC members were expelled in March and four  
others resigned for taking over $1 million in bribes and 
inducements from Salt Lake City's successful bidders for the 2002 
Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Ganga was singled out by the committee for receiving nearly  
$270,000 in improper inducements -- by far the most of any member. 
</P>
<P>
	Ganga denied the charges and called the investigation a ``plot  
against the Third World.'' The other five who were expelled were 
from Ecuador, Sudan, Mali, Chile and Samoa. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a U.S. congressional investigation, the 1996  
Atlanta Olympics bid committee also gave scholarship money to Ganga 
for two Congolese girls to attend a tennis camp in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Young, the former Atlanta mayor who was one of the  
leaders of Atlanta's bid, defended Ganga, saying he was looking out 
for his country and for other African countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
