<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Office Rents Most Expensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Forget about New York and San Francisco: the city  
with the most expensive office space in the nation is Boston, 
according to a new survey. 
</P>
<P>
	Average rents for Boston's Class A office buildings were $47.93  
per square foot during the first quarter of 1999, according to the 
nationwide commercial real estate company Cushman &AMP; Wakefield. 
</P>
<P>
	That's 15 cents more than the $47.78 price per square foot in  
midtown Manhattan. San Francisco has the third-most expensive 
office space in the country, at $46.08 per square foot. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington, D.C., came next at $38.19 a square foot, followed by  
Chicago at $31.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston's vacancy rate was also significantly lower than the  
other top cities, at 4.1 percent. New York was 6.5 percent, San 
Francisco 6.1, Washington 6.6 and Chicago 10.8. 
</P>
<P>
	Since last year, Boston's average rent has jumped $10, more than  
28 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	At International Place in the city's Financial District, office  
space is pushing $70 per square foot. Last year, the cost topped 
$60. 
</P>
<P>
	``For us, a change in the rent by 50 cents or $1 a square foot  
is a big deal, because it goes right to the bottom line,'' said 
Donald Chiofaro, the developer/owner of International Place, told 
the Boston Herald. ``We have a motivation to get the highest 
rent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even with new office space being built downtown, Boston still  
doesn't have enough to meet demand. The city is absorbing office 
space at a rate of more than 1 million square feet each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Owners of high-end offices in Boston are following Chiofaro's  
lead in deciding what to charge. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chiofaro said he realizes that the buildings must deliver  
great value, or people will stop paying top rents. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good news is that cities are enjoying the greatest  
popularity of my career, and Boston is among the greatest cities,'' 
said Chiofaro, whose twin International Place towers overlook 
Boston Harbor. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
