<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> East Bakes in Pre-Summer Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Temperatures rose toward record highs again  
today in the East, overpowering antiperspirants and straining 
electric utilities. 
</P>
<P>
	With the official start of summer two weeks away, the season  
arrived early from the Mississippi River to the Atlantic Ocean as 
highs climbed into the 90s on Monday. Today, the temperature in New 
York's Central Park was already 88 by 11 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Air conditioners were cranked up to full blast and the biggest  
supplier of electricity in Connecticut, Northeast Utilities, warned 
today that the demand has taxed the New England power grid. 
</P>
<P>
	If the region loses just one generator, utilities will have have  
to cut power in some areas if people don't conserve, said Northeast 
Utilities spokeswoman Deborah Beauchamp. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is very serious,'' Beauchamp said.  
</P>
<P>
	ISO New England, which manages the region's power supply, had  
already issued a power warning on Monday, asking consumers to cut 
their electricity usage and warning that the situation could be 
worse today. 
</P>
<P>
	But how hot is it, really?  
</P>
<P>
	Delivery man Luis Justiniano had to stop Monday and stick his  
head in the refrigerated cargo section of his truck. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real bad,'' he said, mopping the sweat from his brow. ``I  
started work at 6 a.m. and it was bad already.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the New York State Thruway, it wasn't just the heat, it was  
the Hondas. 
</P>
<P>
	Albany's record 94-degree heat got toll collector Jack Rice in  
every direction -- from above, reflected by the asphalt below and 
blasting from the side by the 500 vehicles per hour that revved 
through his toll plaza on the thruway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I try not to pay attention to the weather,'' said Rice, a  
veteran of 12 summers in tiny thruway booths. ``It would be 
unbearable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Portland, Maine, topped out at 95, a full 10 degrees over the  
date's record and the hottest day there since July 1995. 
Harrisburg, Pa., peaked at 96, tying a June 7 record on the books 
since 1925. 
</P>
<P>
	The mercury climbed to 99 degrees at Newark International  
Airport in New Jersey, breaking the day's old record high of 95 set 
in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 172,000 people heading to New York City's seven public  
beaches, which normally see about 20,000 visitors on a weekday at 
this time of year. 
</P>
<P>
	Employees at Brookline Ice and Coal in Brookline, Mass.,  
shuttled from the freezer's frigid air to the sweltering outdoors 
as they tried to meet the demand from hotels, grocery stores, and 
ice cream and coffee shops. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very hectic, but there are worse places to be today than  
the icehouse,'' said worker Donna Bell. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
