<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Futures Drop; Energy, Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coffee futures tumbled today on the Board of Trade of the City  
of New York amid forecasts of warm winter weather in Brazil that 
call for little chance of bean-damaging frosts. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, energy, soybean and grain futures settled  
higher -- also due to factors related to the warm weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say coffee traders are keeping an eye on South American  
weather, where winter temperatures never fell below the mid-40s 
over the weekend. Forecasters also say there is little chance of 
temperatures falling below the freezing mark in the next week to 10 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	That news -- coupled with a bearish Commitments of Traders report  
Friday -- caused July arabica coffee to fall 8 cents to $1.12 a 
pound. 
</P>
<P>
	One coffee analyst said Monday's results represented typical  
post-weekend behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market tends to firm up as the weekend approaches in case  
of any surprises,'' said Judy Ganes, first president at Merrill 
Lynch &AMP; Co. in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Those surprises might include a frost, which didn't happen,  
causing traders to give back gains posted late last week, Ganes 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, natural gas futures continued their climb on the New  
York Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	With summer reserves below normal and domestic production weaker  
than usual, analysts say traders were reacting to forecasts of 
continued hot weather through much of the country -- a factor that 
is likely to force utilities to use more fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil futures also finished higher -- in part in response to  
a statement from Nigerian President Olusegun Abasanjo that his 
country's state-run oil company will honor to its agreement with 
the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries to produce 
1.885 million barrels per day. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas for July delivery rose 4 cents to $2.437 for each  
1,000 cubic feet; July unleaded gasoline rose 1.51 cents to 50.11 
cents a gallon; July heating oil rose 1.56 cents to 41.29 cents a 
gallon; and July crude rose 58 cents to $17.32 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, soybean and grain futures prices finished higher on  
the Chicago Board of Trade though they retreated from a Monday 
morning rally that saw July soybeans up more than 8 cents a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Again forecasts for above-normal temperatures in the next week  
played a role -- the thought being that hot, dry weather could 
damage early planted crops and result in smaller crops and, thus, 
higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts say traders backed off from some of those concerns  
by midday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thoughts that dry weather will aid in the harvest of winter  
wheat also kept wheat futures in check, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 cent to $2.57 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn was up 1 3/4 cent to $2.22 1/2 a bushel; July oats rose 3 cents to 
$1.26 1/2 a bushel; and July soybeans were up 3 3/4 cents to $4.68 1/4 a 
bushel. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
