<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pretrial Rulings Made in Intel Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- A federal judge has ruled that Intel  
Corp. had no license to use Intergraph patented technology in its 
Pentium family of processors, rejecting Intel's argument that the 
patents were included in an old agreement with National 
Semiconductor Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The pretrial ruling by U.S. District Judge Edwin Nelson was an  
early blow for Intel in its defense against a lawsuit brought by 
Intergraph of Huntsville, a workstation manufacturer, in November 
1997. Intergraph contends Intel, which makes computer chips, 
infringed on its patents, used coercive business practices and 
violated antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson's ruling addressed only Intel's claim of a licensing  
agreement governing the Intergraph patents. The allegations of 
patent infringement, antitrust violations and illegal practices 
will be addressed at a trial in February 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for Intergraph, Bill Baxley of Birmingham, did not  
immediately return a call seeking comment Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the news release, Intergraph Chairman and Chief Executive Jim  
Meadlock said Intel repeatedly has claimed they have a license to 
the ``Clipper'' chip patents. 
</P>
<P>
	``The court affirms they don't have such a license,'' Meadlock  
said. ``We believe the entire Pentium family infringes on our 
patents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Intel, Chuck Mulloy, said Monday an appeal of  
Nelson's order was being considered. But the license claim was only 
one of several defenses Intel planned to raise in the lawsuit, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are disappointed and we respectfully disagree with the  
judge,'' Mulloy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Intergraph makes computer workstations mated to its software,  
with the core of its business involving elaborate computer graphics 
for technical design, mapping and animation. For a time, Intergraph 
used its own high-end microprocessor, the ``Clipper,'' in its 
workstations but later moved to an Intel-based system and abandoned 
the Clipper. 
</P>
<P>
	Intergraph claims when it tried to enforce the Clipper patent,  
Intel denied the company technical information and advance copies 
of new microchips -- both crucial to developing new products. 
Intergraph also contends Intel chips were made using Intergraph 
technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel claims it did nothing illegal. In the motion denied by  
Nelson, the chipmaker claimed the Clipper technology fell under a 
long-standing cross-license agreement with NSC. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Intergraph news release, Intergraph and NSC  
each bought parts of Fairchild Semiconductor Corp. in concurrent 
transactions in 1987. Intergraph bought Fairchild's Advanced 
Processor Division, the original developer of the Clipper chip, it 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The undisputed facts establish that NSC had no legal authority  
to grant a license, as the patents at issue belonged not to NSC but 
to a legally distinct corporation -- Fairchild,'' Nelson wrote in 
his order. ``Intel thus never received a license from any entity 
with the power to grant one. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fundamental flaw in Intel's license defense is that the  
alleged license would have originated from NSC, while the Clipper 
patents quite clearly belonged not to NSC but to Fairchild, a 
separate corporation,'' Nelson wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Mulloy said the judge's ruling had ``very broad and  
unprecedented implications'' for the high-tech industry. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 02:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly Warned About Phone Scams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The American Association of Retired Persons  
wants to get the drop on fraudulent telemarketers who prey on the 
elderly by dropping a dime first. 
</P>
<P>
	State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer on Monday joined a group of  
AARP ``fraud fighters'' Monday, phoning senior citizens around the 
state to warn them they may be targeted by scam artists. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Spitzer admitted some seniors may not appreciate  
getting cold calls from a stranger -- even New York's attorney 
general -- he said it's important to warn them that they may be on 
so-called ``mooch lists'' circulated, sold and traded among illicit 
solicitors. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI provided lists of seniors to call based on scam artists'  
call sheets. Three years ago the FBI found a mooch list in a 
fraudulent telemarketer operation that had the telephone numbers of 
6,500 elderly New Yorkers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we are here to turn the tables on the fraudulent  
telemarketers,'' AARP state President Charles Leaven said. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Office for the Aging says 85 percent of those targeted  
by fraudulent telemarketers are older than age 65. Officials claim 
about one in every 10 telemarketers are dishonest. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Bureau of Investigation says telemarketing fraud has  
grown to an industry that draws between $40 billion and $60 billion 
a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The most likely ways that telemarketers strike are by saying  
that a person has won a big prize, asking for contributions to a 
charity or promising to get back money from an earlier scam. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton County District Attorney Penelope Clute has a special  
stake in the programs. She said a con man bilked her mother out of 
$76,000 over several years through a phony telephone sweepstakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Her mother was promised big prizes if she bought the caller's  
products, but the prizes never came, Clute said. She even got taken 
in by someone calling to tell her that they would help get her 
money back if she sent them some more, Clute said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was tricked, lied to and had her money stolen,'' Clute  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, a 2 1/2-year undercover investigation by federal and  
state law enforcers in 38 states tape-recorded telephone scams and 
brought criminal charges against nearly 1,000 telemarketers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
