<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Launch Failure Under Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The Ikonos 1 Earth-imaging satellite launched in  
April failed to reach orbit because of an electrical problem, 
according to preliminary findings released Tuesday by a Lockheed 
Martin investigation team. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lockheed Martin Anomaly Investigation Team suggested that  
the aerodynamic covering over the payload failed to come off 
properly because of a problem with an electrical signal. The 
problem with the electrical signal may have been caused by open 
circuits in redundant connectors, according to the findings. 
</P>
<P>
	The satellite, being launched for the private Space Imaging,  
Inc., and the fourth stage of the Athena II rocket, disappeared 
shortly after liftoff on April 27 from Vandenberg Air Force Base in 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	The fairing was supposed to separate and fall away from the  
rocket after it passed through the atmosphere. It weighs 1,143 
pounds and the extra weight prevented the rocket from achieving 
enough velocity to reach orbit, the Denver-based rocket builder 
said after the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	An investigation by Lockheed Martin into what went wrong is  
ongoing. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
