<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Off-Peak Summer Flights Discounted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Major airlines cut ticket prices today by as much  
as 25 percent for off-peak summer travel, with United Airlines 
setting off the fare war just a day after that carrier warned of 
weak quarterly profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta Air Lines, Continental Airlines and Northwest Airlines  
were among ther first to match the United promotion on domestic and 
international travel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will be competitive with United,'' Delta spokeswoman Kay  
Horner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the promotion, consumers who purchase tickets for advance  
travel only on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Saturdays could see as much 
as a 25 percent discount over regularly priced tickets. The airline 
also capped advanced round-trip ticket purchases for peak travel 
days at $498. 
</P>
<P>
	The promotion, in which tickets must be purchased by June 18,  
applies to travel through the end of September. On domestic 
flights, the sale allows two companions of any age to buy tickets 
at even sharper discounts. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, a ticket for round-trip travel from Chicago to New  
York would cost $238, while companions could purchase tickets for 
$138 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline stocks fell after the fare cuts were announced. In  
midday trading on the New York Stock Exchange, United parent UAL 
was down $2.37 1/2 a share, or 3.6 percent, at $64; American Airlines 
parent AMR was down $2.75, or 4 percent, at $66.93 3/4; and Delta was 
down $1.62 1/2, or 2.7 percent, at $59.37 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale is similar to a more restricted promotion launched last  
week by Northwest Airlines that was due to expire in a few days. 
The sale introduced by United, and now matched by Northwest and the 
other carriers, allows for travel on Saturdays and sets no age 
limit on companion travel. 
</P>
<P>
	United spokesman Joe Hopkins said consumers who previously  
purchased tickets under the old fares can get a travel credit for 
the difference or can get a cash refund after paying a $75 
ticket-change fee. 
</P>
<P>
	The fare sales undercut a 4 percent boost in ticket prices  
instituted last week by major airlines and comes as the carriers 
are finding an unexpectedly large number of empty seats despite 
strong summer bookings. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen percent of Americans are expected to fly this summer,  
up 3 percent from a year ago, according to the Travel Industry 
Association of America. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, United warned Monday that second-quarter earnings would  
fall far short of Wall Street forecasts of $3.10 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the major carriers are taking delivery of new planes at  
a rate faster than retirement of old ones. That increases their 
seating capacity and causes the percentage of seats filled, or load 
factor, to drop. 
</P>
<P>
	Several airline analysts have warned in the past year that  
carriers were putting themselves in such a precarious position as 
they went on a plane-buying spree in the face of three years of 
record profits. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
