<HEADLINE> Getronics Completes Wang Global Buy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Dutch communications technology  
company Getronics NV said Tuesday it has completed its $2 billion 
acquisition of U.S.-based Wang Global. 
</P>
<P>
	Getronics said it has received stocks and stock warrants  
representing 90.7 percent of the outstanding common shares of Wang. 
Getronics said the remaining shares would be exchanged for the 
right to receive cash. 
</P>
<P>
	With the deal, Getronics becomes one of the five largest  
computer-services companies in the world, with annual sales of 
around $4.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Getronics said it will rename the existing Wang Global companies  
Getronics in most of Europe, Latin America and Asia, and 
GetronicsWang in North America. 
</P>
<P>
	Wang was founded in 1951 by An Wang, a Chinese immigrant who  
came to the United States to earn a Ph.D. at Harvard University. 
Then known as Wang Laboratories, the firm began with Wang's $600 in 
savings. 
</P>
<P>
	The company peaked in the mid 1980s when it manufactured word  
processors and closet-sized ``minicomputers,'' but it stumbled 
badly later in the decade when it failed to negotiate the computing 
world's transition to modern networked and desktop computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Until this deal, Amsterdam-based Getronics had no presence in  
the United States. It has about 11,000 employees and provides 
information and computer services in Europe. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
