<HEADLINE> Jitney Jungle's Leaders Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Mike Julian, the longtime chairman and CEO  
of Jackson-based Jitney Jungle Stores of America Inc., resigned 
Tuesday as head of the supermarket chain. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the company announced that Rick Coleman, who  
had been chief financial officer since January, also had resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	Jitney president and chief operating officer Ronald E. Johnson  
has assumed duties as chairman and CEO. David R. Black, the current 
senior vice president, will succeed Coleman. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced that Roger P. Friou, a former Jitney  
president, has been hired as a consultant. 
</P>
<P>
	Julian said in a statement that he was leaving for personal  
reasons. Coleman said he was departing to spend more time with his 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel confident that I have left (the company) in competent  
and capable hands,'' Julian said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said that Jitney was fortunate to have an experienced  
management team on hand to reduce the impact when a company changes 
its leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes come about three weeks after Julian said a $545  
million debt is keeping Jitney Jungle from aggressively competing 
with other grocery stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said Tuesday that the company is still reviewing its  
options. There was no mention of a sale in the company's 
announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Julian said if the company was debt free, it would  
be able to fight off competition from Albertson's, Kroger, Winn 
Dixie and Wal-Mart. Lingering debt is also preventing the company 
from renovating 40 existing stores, Julian said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jitney had earnings of $117 million on about $2 billion in sales  
last year. Jitney operates 197 supermarkets, 10 liquor stores and 
55 gasoline stations in Mississippi, Alabama, Louisiana, Tennessee, 
Florida and Arkansas. 


  	   	
</P>
