<HEADLINE> Columbine Victims' Funds Near $5M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Nearly $5 million has been raised to  
help victims of the Columbine High School shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the 30 funds established to help the victims say the  
outpouring of support has created the problem of how to distribute 
the money, with some families disagreeing on how the money should 
be divided. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities and victim advocates are hoping answers on  
questionnaires handed in Monday by victims' families will help them 
decide how to dole out the donations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It might have been easier to have decided the way to allocate  
the money at the beginning, but it wouldn't have been right,'' said 
Aura Leigh Ferguson, the district attorney's community programs 
director. ``We are just now learning what people's needs and the 
victims' needs are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Relief funds were established soon after the April 20 rampage at  
Columbine. Students Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold killed 12 
classmates and a teacher before committing suicide. Twenty-three 
others were wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	The $3.2 million Healing Fund is the largest. In addition to  
fund, 29 scholarship, memorial and other funds have raised at least 
$1.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The questionnaires asked the families whether victims should all  
receive an equal lump sum, a lump sum based on established 
priorities or whether the money should be distributed as requested 
based on financial needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Survey results won't be tallied for a couple of weeks.  
  	   	
</P>
