<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Charges Attorney and Consultant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators on Tuesday charged an  
attorney and a consultant who worked at his firm with defrauding 
investors of $6.2 million in a sham securities offering known as a 
``prime bank'' scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims included an Ecuadorian charity for underprivileged  
girls, the Securities and Exchange Commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a civil lawsuit filed in federal court in Washington, the SEC  
charged attorney Lewis Allen Rivlin and consultant Edwin Earl 
Huling III with securities fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC also charged Alfred Huascar Velarde, a former law  
partner of Rivlin, with aiding the fraudulent investment scheme. 
Velarde agreed to settle the charges by paying a $20,000 fine and 
promising to refrain from future violations of federal securities 
laws. He neither admitted to nor denied the allegation. 
</P>
<P>
	Huling's attorney described his client as an unwitting investor  
in the scheme and said he would contest the charges in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Huling ``invested his own money with Mr. Rivlin,'' said the  
attorney, Frank Razzano. ``He certainly had no knowledge of this'' 
being fraudulent. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin's attorney, Craig Christensen of Sacramento, didn't  
immediately return telephone calls seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin is the former husband of Federal Reserve Vice Chairman  
Alice Rivlin, who announced last Thursday she was leaving the 
central bank to devote more time to her second job as head of the 
District of Columbia's financial control board. They divorced in 
1977 after 22 years of marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC alleged that Lewis Rivlin and Huling, with Velarde's  
help, sold some $6.2 million worth of sham securities to groups of 
investors, including the Ecuadorian charity. They allegedly 
portrayed their investment program as a pooling of investors' money 
to buy and resell at a profit the so-called ``prime bank'' notes. 
</P>
<P>
	Such ``prime bank'' schemes are a growing area of fraud in which  
ordinary investors -- especially seniors -- have lost millions of 
dollars, according to securities regulators. The schemes promise 
high, risk-free returns on debt notes said to be guaranteed by the 
world's biggest banks. Promoters often claim that only big 
corporations, foreign banks and super-rich individuals know about 
``prime bank'' notes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prime bank offerings are a total scam; they do not exist,''  
SEC Enforcement Director Richard Walker said Tuesday. ``Investors 
should contact the SEC immediately if they are asked to invest in a 
prime bank offering.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In its suit against Rivlin and Huling, the SEC is seeking  
unspecified fines, an accounting of the money trail and 
compensation to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC's Web site contains a discussion of ``prime bank'' fraud  
at www.sec.gov/enforce/prime.txt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Moneyline' Host Quits CNN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lou Dobbs, one of television's most prominent  
financial journalists, resigned from CNN on Tuesday after reports 
he had been clashing with CNN's top executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Dobbs has been host of CNN's nightly financial wrapup show,  
``Moneyline,'' and is also president of the spinoff financial 
network, CNNfn. 
</P>
<P>
	Dobbs will leave his position on Friday to launch a new Internet  
venture, Space.com, a Web site for news, entertainment and 
educational content on space, CNN said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dobbs did not return a telephone call seeking comment. He was  
replaced on ``Moneyline'' on Tuesday by Tony Guida. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement released by CNN, Dobbs said he was looking  
forward to the opportunity to build ``the world's leading Web site 
on space.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I leave with the utmost respect for the organization, and for  
the news professionals it has been my pleasure to work alongside,'' 
Dobbs said. 
</P>
<P>
	Just two weeks ago, Dobbs was involved in an unusually public  
tiff with CNN president Rick Kaplan. A visibly unhappy Dobbs 
interrupted ``Moneyline'' to cover a president news conference from 
Colorado, telling viewers it was under Kaplan's orders. 
</P>
<P>
	It prompted a Kaplan deputy to issue memos stating that CNN's  
executive producers have the authority to break into ``Moneyline'' 
to cover news when warranted. 
</P>
<P>
	There reportedly has been ongoing tension between Dobbs and  
Kaplan, with the Wall Street Journal saying that Dobbs had 
complained internally about money being spent on ``NewsStand,'' the 
newsmagazine series that Kaplan has championed. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaplan did not immediately return a telephone call seeking  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	CNNfn has run a distant second in influence to CNBC, the cable  
leader in business news. CNBC is seen in 69 million homes, while 
CNNfn is available in less than 10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Dobbs' ``Moneyline,'' shown weeknights for an hour at 6:30  
p.m., draws more than twice as many viewers as CNBC's competing 
``Business Center.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He is one of the people who helped put business news on the  
map in television,'' said George Jamison, a CNBC spokesman. ``He 
was a strong competitor and a respected journalist. This is a big 
loss for CNN and CNNfn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dobbs joined CNN in its inception in 1980 as chief economics  
correspondent and anchor of ``Moneyline.'' Over the past two 
decades, he has served in numerous roles and was responsible for 
CNNfn's launch in December 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the second resignation of a prominent on-air CNN  
personality this spring. International correspondent Peter Arnett, 
who was out of favor at the network following last year's 
``NewsStand'' report about Vietnam veterans that was later 
retracted, also resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	David Bohrman, executive vice president of CNNfn, will oversee  
the financial network. Jeff Gralnick, executive vice president, CNN 
financial news, will be in charge of ``Moneyline'' and other 
financial news programming. 
</P>
<P>
	Willow Bay, who is host of two ``NewsStand'' editions, and  
others will serve as interim anchors for ``Moneyline,'' CNN said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
