<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China, Russia Demand Bombing Halt  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- China and Russia demanded today that NATO  
stop bombing Yugoslavia before the U.N. Security Council formally 
adopts a resolution ending the Kosovo conflict and paving the way 
for 850,000 refugees to return home. The 15-member Security Council 
met informally to discuss the proposed text hours after foreign 
ministers from the seven major industrialized nations and Russia -- 
the so-called Group of Eight -- agreed on the text of a resolution 
in Germany. Despite China's hesitancy, diplomats were hopeful that 
a resolution would be adopted tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO, Yugoslav Generals Meet  
</P>
<P>
	KUMANOVO, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO warplanes attacked targets  
across Serbia in a thunderous warning to President Slobodan 
Milosevic to implement a Kosovo peace plan, as Western and Yugoslav 
generals met to finalize the details for withdrawing troops. The 
meeting came after the United States, Russia and six leading 
democracies authorized a text calling for a peacekeeping force for 
Kosovo with ``substantial'' NATO participation and agreed on a NATO 
bombing pause -- once Serb forces began a verifiable withdrawal. 
U.S. B-52 bombers pummeled the area near Junik for a third-straight 
day. There were unconfirmed reports of a large number of Yugoslav 
army casualties. 

</P>
<P>
	India, Pakistan To Hold Peace Talks  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- India and Pakistan agreed today to hold  
weekend peace talks aimed at ending fighting that has left scores 
dead along their disputed Kashmir border. The agreement, even as 
artillery fire thundered on in the Himalayan region, could be the 
first major breakthrough in two weeks of rising tensions between 
the world's newest nuclear powers. The Indian Foreign Ministry said 
in a statement that Pakistan's foreign minister, Sartaj Aziz, would 
be welcome for talks Saturday. Aziz later agreed to go to New 
Delhi. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate To Ask Berger To Testify  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of the Senate Intelligence  
Committee said today he will ask National Security Adviser Sandy 
Berger to appear to discuss what many Republicans say was the slow 
response to China's alleged theft of secrets from nuclear weapons 
labs. Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., said he would ask Berger to 
appear at a closed hearing of his panel as early as next week. 
Berger, along with Attorney General Janet Reno, have been targets 
of Republicans who say someone should be held responsible for not 
moving more quickly to stop the alleged espionage at the Energy 
Department's Los Alamos lab in New Mexico. 

</P>
<P>
	'Choose Life' License Plates in Fla.  
</P>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- ``Choose Life,'' two words carrying an  
emotionally charged message about abortion, will be on some Florida 
license plates under a bill signed today by Gov. Jeb Bush. Money 
raised by sales of the $20 specialty plate, which bears a crayon 
drawing of children, will go to support organizations that serve 
pregnant women who plan to put their babies up for adoption. The 
idea had been vetoed last year by the late Gov. Lawton Chiles, a 
Democrat, but Bush had promised to sign it into law. 

</P>
<P>
	Firms Create Trading System  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., Goldman Sachs Group and  
Madoff Securities announced they have formed an electronic trading 
system that will compete with traditional stock markets. Their 
venture is called Primex Trading, and is the latest in a string of 
electronic communications networks that offer investors another way 
to trade stocks. Primex's gimmick is that it displays all stock 
orders to an electronic ``crowd'' of participants who then compete, 
via computer, for the best price. The New York Stock Exchange 
relies on a brokers who gather on the floor and call out competing 
offers for shares. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Slip  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped Wednesday following a drop in  
the Dow Jones industrial average and a stronger yen. The Nikkei 
Stock Average fell 40.02 points to 16,522.90 in early trading. The 
Dow ended down 143.74 points at 10,765.64. 

</P>
<P>
	Marlins Beat Orioles 2-1 in 1st Game  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Jesse Orosco walked Luis Castillo on a 3-2 pitch  
with two out and the bases loaded in the bottom of the ninth today, 
and the Florida Marlins won their sixth game in a row by beating 
the Baltimore Orioles 2-1. The Marlins' winning streak is the 
longest in the major leagues. The game, delayed twice by rain, was 
the opener of a doubleheader. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
