<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ausstralia Nixes Coke-Cadbury Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australian regulators have rejected for  
the second time Coca-Cola Co.'s plan to buy soft drink brands in 
Australia from Cadbury Schweppes PLC because it would reduce 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian Competition &AMP; Consumer Commission announced  
Tuesday it opposed the revised plan to sell the brands to Coca-Cola 
on the grounds, saying it would substantially lessen market 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	It turned down the initial plan in March.  
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola said the company is considering its options following  
the commission's action and hasn't decided whether to abandon all 
attempts at a deal, a spokesman said. Cadbury Schweppes officials 
declined to comment until the company's British officials had seen 
the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian deal was originally part of a $1.85 billion plan  
for Atlanta-based Coca-Cola to buy all beverage brands owned by 
Cadbury Schweppes outside the U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	The soft drink companies scaled back the deal to about $1.1  
billion after regulatory obstacles arose in several countries. Most 
European Union member states have been dropped from the worldwide 
deal, along with Norway and Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	The Australian regulators said in a statement that the revised  
proposal didn't address the concerns the commission expressed with 
the first plan. ``The core concern is that the premium Schweppes 
branded drinks remain part of the transaction,'' said commission 
chairman Alan Fels. 
</P>
<P>
	``The merger would result in a market structure where the  
leading carbonated drinks in almost every category will be 
controlled by Coke.'' That, in turn, would increase the likelihood 
of an increase in prices, Fels said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the revised plan, Coca-Cola was to buy the major brands of  
Schweppes -- Dr Pepper and Canada Dry -- with the intention of 
licensing the production, sale and distribution rights to Coca-Cola 
Amatil Ltd., its 43 percent-owned local unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Amatil was to sell its carbonated soft drink brands  
not licensed from its parent to Cadbury Schweppes Australia. Those 
brands, including Kirks, Halls and Deep Spring, would have 
supplemented brands to be retained by Cadbury Schweppes, leaving 
the size of its business ``essentially unchanged,'' according to 
Coca-Cola. 
</P>
<P>
	But with Schweppes in its portfolio, Coca-Cola's share of the  
Australian carbonated soft drink market through Coca-Cola Amatil 
would have immediately increased several percentage points from the 
current 65 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission said the second-tier brands like those Coca-Cola  
Amatil was to sell to Cadbury Schweppes Australia have limited 
sales in outlets like convenience stores, and wouldn't likely get 
the display space that Cadbury enjoys. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
