<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Lower; Dow Down 76.93 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices fell on Wall Street today as blue-chip  
stocks gave up ground after their strong gains Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 76.93 at 10,832.45. The Dow climbed Monday for the third 
straight session amid enthusiasm over merger activity, adding 
109.54 to close at 10,909.38. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed, with the Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 composite down 5.71 at 1,328.81 and the Nasdaq composite up 
0.62 at 2,524.83. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow industrials were led lower by Procter &AMP; Gamble, down 2 3/8  
at 95 3/16; IBM, down 2 1/4 at 118 1/4; and Sears, down 15/16 at 48 
13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said there was little news to influence trading.  
Investors are still concerned that the Federal Reserve might raise 
interest rates in an attempt to cool the economy at its next policy 
meeting on June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Those fears appeared to weigh most heavily on major computer  
companies today, analysts said. Those stocks are often perceived as 
too pricey during times of higher interest rates, when corporate 
profits can be sliced by the higher costs of borrowing. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq fell 15/16 to 22 15/16 after a US Bancorp Piper Jaffray  
analyst said the computer maker is losing market share to Hewlett 
Packard. 
</P>
<P>
	But while some of the high-tech leaders faltered, the  
notoriously volatile Internet stocks held up fairly well. Infoseek 
rose 7 9/16 to 50 9/16 after Walt Disney Co. said it is negotiating 
to buy the 57 percent of the Web search company it does not already 
own. 
</P>
<P>
	Some market players have come to believe traders are already  
betting on a rate increase of 0.25 percentage point, and that 
they're not likely to do much more selling. They point to a report 
last Friday of moderate May employment gains, which helped ease 
fears of a larger rate hike. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, most are willing to stay on the sidelines until this  
Friday, when the government will report on productivity. Scott 
Brown, chief economist at Raymond James &AMP; Associates in St. 
Petersburg, Fla., said traders will use that data to firm up their 
bets on whether the Fed will indeed raise rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Productivity data have never been a major market-mover, but  
the figures tell a story of how wage pressures are being met, and 
whether we may be approaching a breaking point,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 299.2 million 
shares, above Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 2.17 to 634.77, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 2.32 at 775.83. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
