<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dozen Former Senators Endorse Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A dozen former Democratic senators endorsed  
Vice President Al Gore's presidential candidacy today and said the 
public's perception of him will improve as they learn more about 
the man they admired when they worked with him in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The former senators who worked alongside the vice president when  
he was in the House and Senate came to Washington on their own for 
an event organized by former Sens. Howard Metzenbaum of Ohio and 
Bennett Johnston of Louisiana and backed by the Gore campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no person better trained to be president than Al  
Gore,'' Metzenbaum said. 
</P>
<P>
	The former senators praised Gore as an effective and competent  
leader with the experience to be an effective president. But 
several acknowledged he has to overcome perceptions among the 
public and the media that he is dull. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican front-runner George W. Bush, the governor of Texas,  
has a double-digit lead in head-to-head matchups with Gore, who is 
seen by a majority in several polls as uninspiring. 
</P>
<P>
	``The elitist media has referred to him as wooden,'' said former  
Sen. Howell Heflin of Alabama. ``Wooden to me is a very proud, 
descriptive term. Wooden in my state is seen as being solid, being 
sturdy and being representative of a builder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Sen. Mike Gravel of Alaska said that when a candidate is  
described as ``wooden,'' it's another word for ``boring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When you stop and consider that the substance of government is  
boring,'' he said, a leader characterized as boring could also be 
``a competent person who can properly govern. Al Gore is extremely 
competent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other former senators joining in the endorsement were Wendell  
Anderson of Minnesota, John Culver of Iowa, Harlan Mathews of 
Tennessee, John Melcher of Montana, Vance Hartke of Indiana, Don 
Riegle of Indiana, Wendell Ford of Kentucky and Donald Stewart of 
Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Metzenbaum listed these former senators as endorsing Gore but  
not attending: Dennis DeConcini of Arizona; Gaylord Nelson of 
Wisconsin; Claiborne Pell of Rhode Island; James Abourezk of South 
Dakota; Russell Long of Louisiana; James Exon of Nebraska and 
Harrison ``Pete'' Williams of New Jersey. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
