<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smith To Republicans: Keep Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Bob Smith, a New Hampshire Republican who  
wants to be his party's presidential nominee next year, warned his 
party today that it is heading for defeat if it chooses a moderate 
candidate for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``How many times do we have to lose with a Dole or a Bush,''  
Smith said at a National Press Club luncheon. ``Let's try someone 
new.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith hopes to be that new face but is vying for the same  
conservative voter pool as former Vice President Dan Quayle; Gary 
Bauer, former head of the Family Research Council; and former White 
House aide and television commentator Patrick Buchanan. Smith 
raised less money through March 31 than any of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Targets of Smith's attack were the generally acknowledged  
front-runner for the 2000 GOP nomination, Gov. George W. Bush of 
Texas, and the former head of the American Red Cross, Elizabeth 
Dole. Bush's father lost his bid for a second presidential term to 
Bill Clinton in 1992, and Dole's husband Bob Dole lost to Clinton 
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Smith's criticisms, Republican National Committee  
spokesman Mike Collins said a conservative defection would send 
Vice President Al Gore to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, Smith accused GOP leaders of being too eager to  
seek the middle ground and compromise with the Democrats rather 
than stick with conservative principles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Electing Republicans is not enough,'' he said. ``You have to  
stand for something, or you stand for nothing. And it's not good 
enough to only talk tough on issues that the pollsters tell you are 
popular.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Smith criticized his party for refusing to pass  
anti-abortion legislation, for supporting gun control measures in 
the recent Senate-passed juvenile crime bill and for supporting 
normal trade relations with China. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
