<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC To Vote on Status of Australian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Australian International Olympic  
Committee member Phil Coles should not be expelled from the Olympic 
movement for preparing secret dossiers on other members, IOC vice 
president Dick Pound said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound told Sydney's Daily Telegraph newspaper that ``there  
wouldn't be too many IOC members around'' if they faced dismissal 
for gathering information on fellow delegates to help Games bid 
committees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have thought the amount of attention gathered (on  
Coles) is far in excess of anything he's done,'' the Canadian said. 
``My understanding is candidate cities share information all the 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC meets in Seoul on Monday to vote on whether to expel  
Coles for his role in preparing dossiers of private information 
about his colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Pound said dossiers were common as was sharing information.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is a camaraderie built up by the candidate cities,''  
Pound said. ``Every single bid city does this. It's part of your 
strategy; where are you going to get your support?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has already been censured by the IOC for accepting lavish  
gifts from officials with Salt Lake City's successful bid for the 
2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	His expulsion would require the approval of two-thirds of the  
IOC's 103 members. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
