<DOCNO> APW19990608.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 10:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Investigators Hear American Air Tape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A voice tape shows the pilots of  
American Airlines Flight 1420 made no mention of deploying 
plane-slowing spoilers while landing their jet in a thunderstorm at 
Little Rock last week, an investigator said today. 
</P>
<P>
	It is still possible that Capt. Richard Buschmann and First  
Officer Michael Origel communicated non-verbally about the 
spoilers, panels that pop up on landing to break the plane's lift 
and help slow it, said George W. Black Jr. of the National 
Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Flight 1420 landed June 1 as a violent thunderstorm approached  
Little Rock National Airport. Nine people were killed and more than 
80 were injured as the plane crashed, broke up and caught fire. Two 
people remained in critical condition today. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane slowed little after landing and roared off the runway  
at 92 mph. It clipped lights at the end of the runway and wrapped 
around steel stanchions on a catwalk to an airport guidance system. 
</P>
<P>
	Buschmann died in the crash, and Origel broke a leg. Black,  
speaking in Washington, said investigators want Origel to listen to 
the cockpit voice recording with them in an effort to refresh his 
memory about preparations made for landing. 
</P>
<P>
	Origel said last week that he believes the spoilers were  
deployed to help slow the plane, but data recorders indicate that 
they did not open at touchdown. In that first interview, though, 
Origel was in pain and on pain medication. 
</P>
<P>
	Black said the voice recording indicates that the pilots went  
over some items on the pre-landing checklist, but there was no word 
pertaining to the spoilers. He would not say if any other elements 
of the checklist were not heard on the tape. It is possible, he 
said, for the pilots to have used pointing or nods of the head to 
acknowledge the proper setting of switches. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I'm really interested in is the communication between the  
two officers,'' NTSB lead investigator Greg Feith said in Little 
Rock, shortly before boarding a plane for Washington. ``Was there a 
miscommunication? Did they not do something because someone did not 
understand?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Feith said that in a hospital interview, Origel said he had  
completed the checklist for landing. 
</P>
<P>
	``He got through the mechanical part, completed some items like  
talking on the radio, and then went back and completed the rest of 
the mechanical checklist,'' Feith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Origel also told investigators last week that he never lost site  
of the runway as the airplane approached in a ``bowling alley'' 
type gap in the storm clouds. Black said today that the cockpit 
voice recorder indicated otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	Crews on Monday moved the plane from the north end of Runway 4R  
to an airport hangar. The runway reopened at 10:35 a.m. today, 
although repairs were not complete to the lighting approach system. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots' console containing many of the jet's important  
controls was removed Monday from the smashed nose of the plane 
after it was taken in pieces from its crash site to a private 
hangar. 
</P>
<P>
	Flight 1420's spoiler system -- along with its anti-skid, thrust  
reverser and braking systems -- will be removed and sent to labs run 
by the NTSB. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are examining whether mechanical problems, pilot  
error or severe weather -- or a combination of those factors -- 
played a role in the crash. The plane's engines were removed 
earlier and shipped to an American Airlines hangar in Tulsa, Okla., 
for tests and possible dismantling. 
</P>
<P>
	Testing is expected to take two to three weeks, Feith said.  
Scrutiny of the jet's other parts is expected to take months. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
