<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> France Declines in European Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- How far can France fall?  
</P>
<P>
	Of Wednesday's 17 Euro 2000 qualifiers, the game in Barcelona  
between the World Cup champions and the semi-pros from Andorra 
normally wouldn't count for much. But these aren't normal times. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fall from Grace,'' was how Tuesday's France Football magazine  
put it, referring to a 3-2 loss Saturday to Russia, the first at 
the Stade de France and France's first defeat since the 1996 
European Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	France is third (11 points) in Group 4 behind leaders Ukraine  
(14) and Iceland (12). Only the group winner qualifies 
automatically. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've taken a knock, a big smack in the face,'' captain Didier  
Deschamps said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't play like world champions,'' added captain Laurent  
Blanc. 
</P>
<P>
	France, which struggled in a 2-0 home victory earlier against  
Andorra, will again be without injured playmaker Zinedine Zidane, 
with forward Youri Djorkaeff also most likely absent. 
</P>
<P>
	England is also in trouble going into its game in Bulgaria. In  
third place (8 points) behind leaders Sweden (13) and Poland (9), 
England now hopes to finish second in the group and qualify for the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The honeymoon ended Saturday for new coach Kevin Keegan in a 0-0  
tie with Sweden at Wembley Stadium. Keegan is now gambling with six 
changes from that team. 
</P>
<P>
	There are no such problems for Italy and the Czech Republic,  
which can be the first two countries to qualify with victories. 
</P>
<P>
	The Czechs, the 1996 runners-up, are the only team with six  
victories and can advance at home against Scotland, which was 
embarrassed in a 1-1 weekend tie at the Faeroe Islands. 
</P>
<P>
	The Czechs have no injuries and coach Jozef Chovanec plans no  
changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Scots are playing for their lives here,'' forward Vladimir  
Smicer said. ``If they lose, they'll have trouble finishing 
second.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Czechs lead Group 9 (18 points) followed by Scotland (8),  
Estonia (7) and Bosnia (7). 
</P>
<P>
	Italy will also advance with a win over Switzerland in Lausanne.  
Coach Dino Zoff most likely will stick with the same lineup that 
beat Wales 4-0 last weekend, prompting the resignation of coach 
Bobby Gould. 
</P>
<P>
	Striker Christian Vieri and captain Paolo Maldini have minor  
injuries but should play. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
