<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Falls on Brazil Weather News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Coffee futures tumbled nearly 6 percent Tuesday on the Board of  
Trade of the City of New York as forecasts for warm weather in 
Brazil dimmed chances for crop damage. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, gold continued its sharp descent, while cocoa  
futures raced to two-month highs. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures extended their slide after Brazilian  
meteorologists called for above-average temperatures this week in 
the nation's main coffee-growing areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculators have been confounded as the world's largest grower  
flirts with the chance for a damaging frost, only to have such 
weather fail to materialize. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil in the past two years has seen bumper production as young  
trees yield more beans and after escaping sustained temperatures 
below freezing. While Brazil produces mostly robusta beans -- the 
type not favored by gourmet coffee drinkers -- its product often is 
blended with the better-tasting arabica produced by Latin American 
and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Arabica coffee for July delivery fell 6.30 cents, or 5.6  
percent, to $1.057 a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures continued to post new 20-year lows on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange as traders failed to shake off bearish 
sentiment about the metal's fortunes. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold prices went into a tailspin after the British government  
announced it would sell more than half the country's reserves to 
raise cash for buying higher-yielding investments. 
</P>
<P>
	That announcement reinforced sentiment that world governments  
will move to sell their holdings because of gold's relative expense 
to store. Many public officials also believe they no longer need to 
back the economies with physical supplies in an era where consumers 
are drifting toward paperless currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	June gold fell $3.30 to $262.80 a troy ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures raced to their highest levels in nearly two months  
on the New York Board of Trade as market participants continued to 
bet new sales would be long in coming. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices have gained for five of the past six trading sessions  
amid the perception that Ivory Coast and Ghana, the world's largest 
growers, have virtually run out of product to sell from the midyear 
crop. 
</P>
<P>
	The two countries contribute more than half the world's cocoa  
supply, which is used mainly in making chocolate. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are betting price that earlier this year reached  
six-year lows are on the rebound. They also note chocolatiers soon 
will need to begin buying after sitting on the sidelines for 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	July cocoa rose $90 to $1,139 a ton.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
