<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 13:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alexander Recruits Iowa Supporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- With a sharp new focus on grass-roots  
organizing, Lamar Alexander said today that he has recruited 
leaders for his Republican presidential campaign in each of Iowa's 
99 counties, the first candidate to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	``We intend to turn out more than 35,000 Alexander supporters''  
with an organizational structure that eventually will reach into 
each of the state's more than 2,100 precincts, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Short of campaign funds, Alexander is focusing his efforts on  
the Iowa caucuses, which launch the 2000 presidential nominating 
season. A former Tennessee governor, Alexander finished third in 
Iowa's caucuses in the last election cycle, and hopes to build on 
that showing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Republicans want a winner, but a winner ... is a candidate who  
is well prepared for the presidency,'' Alexander said at a news 
conference. ``This nomination is too important to be bought, it 
shouldn't be inherited, it ought to be earned. I'm here today to 
earn it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He showed some signs of frustration as he talked about the GOP  
front-runner Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not want to let the political elite pick a nominee six  
or eight months before the people have a say and then find out in 
the middle of a debate with Albert Gore that we've nominated 
someone who is not ready to be president,'' said Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if that meant Bush was unprepared to assume the office,  
Alexander said: ``We don't have any idea if he's ready to be 
president. He's a popular one-term governor and the woods are full 
of popular one-term governors. We don't know a thing about him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander continued campaigning virtually nonstop after dropping  
from the race in the last election cycle, and he's campaigned more 
frequently in Iowa this year than almost any other GOP contender. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that, early polling has shown Bush atop the field, with  
Alexander bunched up with other contenders in single digits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Governor Bush looks forward to meeting with the people of Iowa  
and allowing them to make a determination on his candidacy,'' 
spokesman Eric Woolson said in response to Alexander's comments. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush makes his first swing through the state this weekend.  
</P>
<P>
	``Most voters in Iowa couldn't pick him out of a lineup,'' said  
Alexander. ``His whole objective in this campaign is to make sure 
the race never gets to the people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander's strategists say their tactic is rooted in the  
conventional wisdom that it takes a finely honed campaign 
organization to turn out voters for precinct caucuses that are 
basically neighborhood meetings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
