<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up, Japanese Stocks Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen today after an  
influential Japanese finance ministry official warned against a 
hasty rise in the Japanese currency. Tokyo share prices advanced 
moderately. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.32 yen, up 0.48 yen from late Monday in  
Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 120.80 yen 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average added 87.03 points,  
or 0.53 percent, closing at 16,562.92. On Monday, the average 
gained 175.14 points, or 1.07 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's advance came on the heels of comments from Eisuke  
Sakakibara, vice finance minister for international affairs and 
known as ``Mr. Yen'' for his influential remarks on the currency 
market. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a general rule, it's undesirable for the yen to strengthen  
too much before the economy recovers,'' Sakakibara told reporters 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	His remark prompted U.S. funds to buy dollars to cover their  
short, or oversold, positions in the greenback, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since it's still unclear whether Japan will compile an extra  
budget for additional public works, Sakakibara's words invoked 
concerns in U.S. participants,'' said Minoru Shioiri, assistant 
manager of foreign exchange at Nippon Credit Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 120.50 yen and 121.45 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 125.98 yen, up from  
124.47 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo stock market, meanwhile, posted moderate gains on  
select buying of blue chips following an overnight rise on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	But many investors held back to wait for Thursday's release of  
gross domestic product figures for the first quarter, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also keeping investors on the sidelines was a government report  
on industrial competitiveness, expected to be released soon. 
Investors also are awaiting a meeting of finance ministers and 
central bankers from the G-7 industrialized nations over the 
weekend in Cologne, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 10.49 points, or 0.79 percent, to 1,339.14. 
The TOPIX closed up 12.12 points, or 0.92 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government bond fell to  
1.5700 percent from Monday's finish of 1.6650 percent, driving its 
price up to 98.53 yen from 97.72 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
