<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Much of the East was hit with hot and humid weather for a second  
day today, while showers fell in the Gulf Coast region. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures were in the 80s and 90s in most areas east of the  
Mississippi River. 
</P>
<P>
	Some relief was beginning to show over New England. A cold front  
continued to slowly sag across Maine and triggered showers and 
thunderstorms. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms and showers were expected from western New York to  
Maine in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms also hit the Gulf Coast area, with the  
most widespread activity in southern Florida. Heavy rain has fallen 
across southern Florida for the past few days, resulting in rising 
rivers and streams. 
</P>
<P>
	Other thunderstorms were increasing over southeastern Texas.  
</P>
<P>
	Most of the central United States was fair and warm as high  
pressure remained over the region. There were a few light showers 
over parts of the Dakotas and Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Other showers fell in eastern Kansas and Missouri. Warm and  
mostly dry conditions were expected to continue over most of the 
Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	A frontal boundary slipping south and east across the western  
United States brought showers and a few thunderstorms from the 
northern Rockies, west into the Pacific Northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong to severe thunderstorms developed over eastern Montana.  
Showers were expected to persist over the remainder of the 
Northwest and northern Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair and dry weather was forecast for the Southwest and southern  
Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures around the continental United States ranged from an  
early morning 27 in Klamath, Falls, Ore., to an afternoon high of 
99 in Greenville, N.C. The highest heat index was 103 in 
Greenville, N.C., and the lowest wind chill was 19 in Baker, Ore. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
