<DOCNO> APW19990608.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 19:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Dinner Honors Hungary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It was a little too warm in the nation's  
capital today to stir up a serving of goulash for visiting 
Hungarian President Arpad Goncz. 
</P>
<P>
	So the White House brought out the next best things for its  
state dinner affair: sumptuous entrees borrowing flavors from the 
Eastern European nation and performances celebrating the folk 
cultures of Hungary and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marine Band Strolling Strings perfected a selection of  
songs, including the Hungarian Rondo, to perform while circling the 
East Room tables set for 180 dinner guests. The ensemble also 
selected a version of the Beer Barrel Polka, to highlight the 
talents of 12-year-old accordion virtuoso, Cory Pesaturo. 
</P>
<P>
	Singer Judy Collins, the evening's featured entertainer,  
included in her repertoire one particularly timely piece for a 
crowd with the war in Kosovo weighing on many minds. Titled 
``Walls,'' the song came about after her husband, Louis Nelson, 
designed the Korean War Veterans Memorial Mural. 
</P>
<P>
	The song ``kind of says it is all about the transformational  
experience of when the war is over,'' Collins said Tuesday 
afternoon as she rehearsed. She hoped the music would focus her 
audience on looking toward the end of war. 
</P>
<P>
	``My music has been a kind of hope, a unifying force,'' said  
Collins, who has made numerous visits to the former Yugoslavia as 
UNICEF's special representative for the arts. ``Music touches us in 
ways that are bigger than issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, President Clinton and Goncz celebrated the ties between  
their two nations, an alliance that has taken on special meaning 
with Hungary's recent entrance into NATO and its support for the 
action in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Your vision of people living together and nations living  
together, resolving differences peacefully, drawing strength from 
their diversity, treating all people with equal dignity, this will 
form the basis of a better future for Europe and the world,'' 
Clinton said in his toast to Goncz. 
</P>
<P>
	Goncz said his visit reinforced the shared values and ideals of  
their countries, as they discussed the current problems in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was the first time I really felt, genuinely, that the two  
countries are allies. And a real alliance is characterized by 
identical values, and also that you approach the problems to be 
solved from the same angle,'' Goncz said through a translator. 
</P>
<P>
	The dinner drew a host of literary figures -- including authors  
E.L. Doctorow, William Styron and Elie Wiesel -- in a fitting 
tribute to the president who taught himself English while in 
prison. Goncz later went on to translate a host of English works 
into Hungarian and become a writer himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's an exceptionally cultivated man,'' said writer Susan  
Sontag, whose works were translated by Goncz. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the best Hungary has had in generations,'' said Rep. Tom  
Lantos, D-Calif., who was born in Hungary. ``He's a fantastic human 
being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actor Tony Curtis, author Kitty Kelley, Nobel laureate Wiesel  
and fashion designer Adrienne Vittadini peppered an eclectic guest 
list. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House staff, taking their cue from Tuesday's  
record-breaking temperatures in the high 90s, created a cool 
environment to greet their guests. Mauve silk tablecloths 
complemented flower centerpieces featuring shades of violet -- 
lavender roses, blue columbines and purple allium gigantum. 
</P>
<P>
	Dinner included copper river salmon, which came into season last  
week, with portobello mushrooms. Its toasted caraway and tomato 
sauce simulated the flavors of a Hungarian goulash, ``but cooler,'' 
said White House chef Walter Scheib. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting as close to a summer cookout as a state dinner can, the  
White House served up a pecan crusted lamb with barbecued peach 
ragout to headline the evening's menu. 
</P>
<P>
	Dubbed a salute to Hungarian composer Bela Bartok, dessert  
consisted of a bing cherry strudel with cooked filo dough springing 
from the top, along with a chocolate violin surrounded by pastries. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House selected the Woodrow Wilson base plates and the  
Franklin Delano Roosevelt china to top the tables. Kennedy 
Morgantown crystal and gold vermeil flatware rounded out the place 
settings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
