<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:26:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Serbs May Be Set To Leave Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. intelligence has detected signs that Serb  
forces are making preparations to withdraw from Kosovo, although no 
troops are moving or assembling for a pullout, the Pentagon said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a number of indications that the Serbs plan to  
withdraw,'' spokesman Kenneth Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	In remarks to reporters at the Pentagon, Bacon said the signs of  
preparation for a troop withdrawal include the mobilization of Serb 
transport vehicles in Kosovo that would be used to move soldiers 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are just beginning to see signs of preparations for  
withdrawal. We have not yet seen any withdrawal,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The disclosure came shortly after NATO announced that talks with  
Yugoslav military authorities on the conditions for a Serb troop 
withdrawal would resume Tuesday night at a Macedonia border town. 
The talks had collapsed Monday in a dispute over a United Nations 
role and other sticking points. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon also disclosed new details on U.S. planning for its  
contribution to the NATO-led peacekeeping force that would enter 
Kosovo after Serb forces begin leaving. Some 1,900 Marines from the 
26th Marine Expeditionary Unit now aboard ships in the Aegean Sea 
would serve as the vanguard of U.S. peacekeepers for Kosovo. In 
addition, Bacon said, the Army would send 1,700 soldiers from a 
group based in Tirana, Albania, including an aviation unit with 
eight Apache attack helicopters. The soldiers also would be 
equipped with artillery, multiple-launch rockets, tanks and other 
armor. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be a daunting mission,'' Bacon said, because  
of the land mines, booby-trapped bridges and other hazards the 
peacekeepers will face in preparing for the return of hundreds of 
thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO hoped the Serbs would begin their withdrawal even before  
the renewed military talks finished, Bacon said, but he emphasized 
that it was up to Belgrade to decide when it was ready to end the 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO will not suspend its bombing until the Serbs begin a  
verifiable withdrawal, Bacon said. He said B-52 bombers had struck 
Serb army concentrations Sunday and Monday in areas near the 
Albanian border where the Serbs are engaged in heavy combat with 
forces of the Kosovo Liberation Army. 
</P>
<P>
	He could not confirm published reports that several hundred Serb  
troops were killed in the B-52 attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if U.S. intelligence had picked up signs of Serb  
preparations for a withdrawal, Bacon cited a report that a senior 
Serb army officer had spoken Sunday of a peace deal that would let 
soldiers return to their families. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen, also, signs that they are mobilizing vehicles and  
other means to transport people out, but we have not yet seen signs 
that Serb troops or special police forces or paramilitaries are 
moving out, but we have certainly seen preparations for moving 
out,'' Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	There are an estimated 40,000 Serb army, police and paramilitary  
forces in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon said that once Yugoslav military authorities agree to  
NATO's withdrawal terms and NATO verifies that ``a certain amount 
of movement'' has taken place in a pullout from ``certain zones'' 
in Kosovo, then the North Atlantic Council -- NATO's political arm -- 
will vote to suspend the bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman would not be more specific about what NATO will  
require before it suspends the airstrikes. He said that was part of 
the discussions to take place in the military-to-military meeting 
in Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Under NATO's withdrawal plan, the Serb forces would assemble in  
pre-designated areas in Kosovo and then travel on prescribed roads 
to four exit points on the Kosovo-Serbia border, Bacon said. He 
left open the possibility that a full withdrawal would take more 
than the seven days NATO initially demanded. 
</P>
<P>
	Headquarters for the U.S. peacekeeping contingent in Kosovo will  
be in Gnjilane in southeastern Kosovo, Bacon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a plan President Clinton formally sent to Congress on  
Monday, about 7,000 American troops would take up peacekeeping duty 
as part of a 50,000-strong NATO-led force. Another 1,500 would go 
to Macedonia and elsewhere in the Balkans to help with the flow of 
supplies and other support to the peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to congressional leaders, Clinton said it is  
impossible to estimate how long the peacekeepers will need to stay 
in Kosovo. After ``an initial stabilization period,'' the force 
will be progressively reduced as local police forces are 
established, Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marines, meanwhile, remained aboard their ships Tuesday  
awaiting the Greek government's approval to land and begin 
traveling overland to a staging area in northern Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Greece has been NATO's most skeptical member since the allied  
airstrikes began March 24. The government had prevented the Marines 
from landing as scheduled Monday, fearing an escalation of 
anti-NATO protests. On Tuesday, the Foreign Ministry said Greece 
would ``not cause problems in the effort to install and reinforce'' 
the peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon said the Marines could reach Kosovo's border from their  
ships in four days or less. This would not cause any delay in the 
start of U.S. peacekeeping operations, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
