<HEADLINE> Burns Regains Lead in Acropolis Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Britain's Richard Burns held to the lead  
in the Acropolis Rally on Tuesday after a gearbox problem forced 
defending champion Colin McRae out of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Burns, driving a Subaru Impreza WRC 99, led after the second  
day, but deliberately took a 30 second penalty to allow others to 
clear a path on dirt roads through central Greece, sweeping away 
the rocks and other debris. 
</P>
<P>
	That left McRea, also the 1996 winner, ahead at the start  
Tuesday. But his Ford Focus WRC developed gearbox in the 15th 
special stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Burns led the final stages, which descended from the steep  
mountains near ancient Delphi to flat farmland northeast of Athens, 
to finish in a time of 3 hours, 18 minutes, 27 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	He was followed closely by Carlos Sainz of Spain, driving a  
Toyota Corolla, in 3:18.44, and Finnish world champion Tommi 
Makinen, seeking his third consecutive world title, in 3:19.02 in 
his Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 114 cars that started out from the foot of the Acropolis  
on Sunday, 53 remained in the rally by the end the third day. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally, which covers 817 miles through central and southern  
Greece, ends Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
