<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Trust Documents Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite two Cabinet officials being held in  
contempt of court, the government still isn't taking proper care of 
some Indian trust records, a court-appointed investigator says. 
</P>
<P>
	In a report issued Monday, Alan Balaran said trust documents are  
stored in ``patently substandard conditions'' at several Bureau of 
Indian Affairs offices he inspected recently. At Anadarko, Okla., 
records were kept in unmarked boxes in wooden sheds, the report 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Balaran, special master in a lawsuit against the government,  
said the majority of the dozen offices he visited in April were 
``models of efficiency.'' He was appointed after U.S. District 
Judge Royce Lamberth found Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and 
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin in contempt in February for their 
delay in turning over trust records. 
</P>
<P>
	Balaran recommended the judge issue an order safeguarding the  
documents. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit alleges the government has been mishandling the  
trust accounts for decades. There are 300,000 accounts held by 
individual Indians, subjects of the lawsuit, and an additional 
1,600 tribal accounts worth $2.5 billion. The money includes lease 
revenue, royalties and court settlements. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit is to be tried in two phases, with the first set to  
start Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	BIA officials say trust records are kept in 108 offices and it  
takes time to ensure that all of them have proper storage. The 
Interior Department released a memorandum dated June 2 that ordered 
all its agencies that might have Indian fund records to ensure they 
are preserved. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, records have been lost or ruined, and ownership  
of reservation property has been divided so often through 
inheritances that only a few cents a year passes through many of 
the accounts, officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the plaintiffs claim the government could be liable  
for billions of dollars in underpayments to account holders. While 
not making estimates, BIA officials have acknowledged that the 
liability could be substantial. 
</P>
<P>
	BIA is to launch a new computer system for handling the accounts  
later this month. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
