<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 17:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dodger Pitcher Suspended For Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A contrite Los Angeles Dodgers pitcher Chan  
Ho Park was suspended for seven games and fined $3,000 on Tuesday 
for hitting and kicking Anaheim Angels pitcher Tim Belcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``I apologize for the bad news for (my) teammates,'' Park said  
three hours before beginning the suspension Tuesday night against 
the Texas Rangers. ``I apologize for trying to hurt him. I expected 
three or five games, seven games is so long. I'll forget about it 
after that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Park will be eligible to return June 17 against Pittsburgh at  
Dodger Stadium, and manager Davey Johnson said the 25-year-old 
right-hander from Korea will pitch that night. 
</P>
<P>
	Belcher refused to comment on the fine and suspension following  
Anaheim's 6-2 loss at San Francisco on Tuesday, but expressed anger 
Monday night in his first public comments on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not happy about what happened,'' Belcher said. ``The guy  
tried to take my head off. I just don't think there's any place for 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently, NL president Leonard Coleman agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	The fight last Saturday began after Belcher fielded Park's  
sacrifice bunt in the fifth inning and tagged him out. After a 
brief exchange of words, Park forearmed Belcher in the face and 
followed with a leaping kick. 
</P>
<P>
	Park later said Belcher tagged him hard, and then cursed him.  
</P>
<P>
	Both benches and bullpens emptied, and Park was ejected. Matt  
Walbeck had hit a grand slam off Park an inning earlier, the fourth 
grand slam allowed by Park this season, equaling a big-league 
record for grand slams allowed in a season. 
</P>
<P>
	Park, 4-3 with a 4.84 ERA in 12 starts this year, will actually  
miss just one start. And because the Dodgers are off Thursday and 
Monday, it will allow them to go with a four-man rotation in his 
absence. 
</P>
<P>
	``All suspensions are stiff to me,'' Johnson said. ``There's  
nothing good about a suspension. We have some off days, we won't 
need an extra pitcher, that helps. Someone was looking out for us 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's had a difficult season so far, for whatever reason.  
There's still plenty of time left for him to have an excellent 
season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Park was 14-8 with a 3.38 ERA in 1997, and 15-9 with a 3.71 ERA  
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he respected Coleman's decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``He did what he had to do,'' Johnson said. ``(But) it takes two  
to rumble. You don't get into a fight for no reason at all, you 
know what I'm saying? I know what it's like getting tagged hard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's severe, seven games, but the schedule makes it  
easier. It's over and done with, let's turn the page and go home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, a big-league player for 13 years and in his 13th season  
as a major league manager, said seldom has he seen two pitchers 
fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe they've got an unwritten rule, `Let's not fight each  
other,''' Johnson said with a smile. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if he'd ever seen a player leave his feet like Park  
did to unload a kick, Johnson smiled again and replied, ``I've seen 
people leave their feet going the other way.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
