<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Considers Kosovo Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council today held its first  
meeting on a draft resolution to end the Kosovo conflict, with the 
United States and its NATO partners pushing for quick adoption but 
China saying it has trouble with key points. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambassadors from the United States, Britain and France went into  
the closed-door meeting saying they hope the council would quickly 
approve the draft agreed on today by the seven major industrialized 
nations and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to have it adopted as soon as possible,'' said Peter  
Burleigh, the deputy U.S. ambassador. 
</P>
<P>
	Shen Guofang, China's deputy U.N. ambassador, told reporters he  
has some difficulties with the new text, however -- ``most 
important'' on China's demand for a bombing halt -- and needed 
instructions from Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	As a permanent member of the Security Council, China has veto  
power over resolutions. 
</P>
<P>
	The difficulties Shen cited were a reference to the mandate of  
the international criminal tribunal for Yugoslavia, and the 
resolution's proposed adoption under Chapter 7 of the U.N. charter, 
which makes the resolution militarily enforceable. 
</P>
<P>
	The Netherlands' U.N. Ambassador Peter van Walsum introduced the  
draft resolution at an informal session of the council. 
</P>
<P>
	China had said it would not allow a formal discussion of a  
resolution on Kosovo while NATO planes were bombing Yugoslavia -- a 
point reiterated today in Beijing and by Chinese diplomats at the 
United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Western diplomats said the scenario they are working toward  
would begin with the signing of a military agreement by NATO and 
Yugoslav military chiefs. This would be followed by the withdrawal 
of Yugoslav troops. The Group of Eight said they would suspend 
bombing once the withdrawal was verified. 
</P>
<P>
	This would set the stage for a formal Security Council meeting  
to adopt the resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	Diplomats said they do not expect any action by the council  
until Wednesday at the earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight of the council's 15 members played no part in negotiating  
the text and were seeing the draft for the first time -- Brazil, 
Gabon, Gambia, Malaysia, Namibia, Slovenia, Argentina and Bahrain. 
Their ambassadors will have to send the draft to their governments 
for approval, diplomats said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the peace plan, the Security Council must authorize an  
international force and civilian administration that would be sent 
to Kosovo under U.N. auspices to ensure the safe return of the 
estimated 860,000 refugees. The Yugoslav government agreed to the 
peace deal Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
