<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Book Retailer Offers Music </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Online retailer Amazon.com launched a new music service Tuesday,  
offering free downloads of songs in the controversial MP3 digital 
format and an industry-preferred format. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle-based leader in online book and video sales hopes to  
use the digital freebies as a teaser to boost CD sales and set the 
stage for a pay-per-song future at www.amazon.com. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial selection of downloadable music doesn't include any  
chart-topping hits, although there are songs from well-known 
artists such as Sarah McLachlan, Lyle Lovett, and Public Enemy. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the songs will be available in both the MP3 files  
popular with Internet music bootleggers and in Liquid Audio, which 
makes downloaded music hard to share with those who haven't paid 
for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com will continue to offer both until industry leaders  
settle on a common standard that will serve the needs of both 
manufacturers and consumers, said Amazon.com spokesman Greg Hart. 
</P>
<P>
	The two formats are not interchangeable, a concern for  
Amazon.com and other would-be Internet music providers looking to 
make a seamless transition from traditional music sales to online 
downloads. 
</P>
<P>
	The MP3 format has bedeviled the music industry for more than a  
year as Internet savvy fans copy and trade the songs on Web sites, 
depriving the recording industry of royalties. 

</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	Software for both MP3 and Liquid Audio music players is  
available through Amazon.com at 
http://www.amazon.com/music-downloads. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
