<DOCNO> APW19990608.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 16:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Businesses Urge Passage of Y2K Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The heads of the nation's major business and  
high-tech groups urged Congress and the White House today to enact 
legislation protecting them from being battered by Y2K-related 
lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Y2K litigation bill, which could return to the Senate floor  
this week, is the number one priority of the high-tech industry, 
Harris Miller, president of the Information Technology Association 
of America, said at a news conference on Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate, he said, should ``unshackle the new economy'' by  
approving a compromise measure sponsored by Sens. John McCain, 
R-Ariz., Ron Wyden, D-Ore., and Christopher Dodd, D-Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	National Association of Manufacturers president Jerry Jasinowski  
said a coalition of more than 100 business groups comprising most 
of the country's economy was pushing hard for the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I urge those in the administration who understand and  
acknowledge that this is a reasonable bill to get on this train 
before it leaves the station,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democrats, upset over unrelated disputes with the  
Republican leadership, have twice before blocked floor action on 
the Y2K litigation bill. But Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, 
R-Miss., said an agreement had been reached with the Democrats to 
resume debate on Wednesday, raising chances for quick approval of 
the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle said Democrats would stop  
their delaying tactics and permit the measure to come up for 
debate. But unless changes are made in the GOP-drafted measure, he 
said, ``it will be vetoed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the urging of Wyden, Dodd and other Democrats, the Senate  
bill is being changed to better protect the rights of those with 
legitimate legal complaints. Caps on punitive damage awards will be 
limited to small businesses and personal liability caps for 
officers of businesses and corporations will be eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has nonetheless threatened to veto the bill.  
It supports the bill's provisions giving defendants a 90-day period 
to fix computer problems before lawsuits are filed and encouraging 
mediation, but says other provisions tip the balance between 
defendant and plaintiff rights. 
</P>
<P>
	There are stronger administration objections to a House version  
which passed last month and is viewed as applying more restraints 
on the right to sue for damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The business community says that without some controls they  
could be swamped by frivolous lawsuits initiated by those trying to 
make money from the disruptions that may occur from computers that 
misread the 2000 date as 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	``One big lawsuit could cause a retail company, especially a  
smaller one, to falter. More than one lawsuit could cause 
catastrophe,'' said Tracy Mullin, president of the National Retail 
Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Chamber of Commerce president and CEO Thomas J. Donohue  
said that while business groups support overall tort reform to rein 
in frivolous lawsuits, they have been careful to make clear that 
this is a one-time measure concerned only with the Y2K issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not using this as a subterfuge or cover to get a lot of  
other tort reform,'' he said. ``This has to be a clean bill.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
