<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Five masked gunmen burst into a small  
concrete house Tuesday and shot dead five youths in what police 
said was an apparent drug dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	The killings took place at dawn in the sugar cane growing region  
of Serrana, 175 miles northwest of Sao Paulo. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were between 16- and 17-years-old and all had  
criminal records for possession and sale of cocaine, said Ricardo 
Dama Cecilio, an officer at the Serrana police department. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing one youth who survived the shooting, Cecilo said the  
killers wore police uniforms and were armed with handguns. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Jailed drug lord Miguel Rodriguez  
Orejuela appeared before a judge on Tuesday to deny charges he 
tried to bribe his way out of a narcotics conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez Orejuela, who along with his brother Gilberto led the  
Cali cocaine cartel, requested the hearing in Bogota's La Picota 
prison, where he is serving a 20-year sentence for drug 
trafficking. 
</P>
<P>
	He is being investigated for allegations that he offered a  
$640,000 bribe to a judge dealing with cases involving violent drug 
traffickers or terrorism. The accusation was filed by the judge who 
received the alleged offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Journalists were not allowed into the session, and prosecutors  
have declined to say when the attempted bribe occurred or offer 
other details on the case. If convicted of the new charges, Miguel 
Rodriguez Orejuela could tack on between two and six years to his 
current sentence, which was shortened after he confessed and agreed 
to cooperate with authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rodriguez Orejuela brothers were arrested and the cartel  
dismantled by Colombian police in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- An Argentine provincial governor  
has abandoned his plans to seek the Peronist party's nomination for 
president, leaving Eduardo Duhalde as the party's flag bearer in 
Argentina's October elections, reports said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Adolfo Rodriguez Saa, governor of the San Luis province, told a  
gathering of supporters on Monday he was relinquishing plans to run 
in the Peronist's July 4 primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodriguez Saa had been given little chance of beating Duhalde,  
the governor of Buenos Aires province and a party stalwart who in 
the past had declared himself the ``natural'' candidate to succeed 
President Carlos Menem. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls have shown Duhalde has pulled even with Buenos  
Aires Mayor Fernando de la Rua, the presidential candidate from an 
opposition alliance of the centrist Radical Civic Union and the 
center-left Frepaso party. 
</P>
<P>
	President Carlos Menem is barred from seeking a third straight  
term under Argentina's constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Thousands of landless farm workers  
marched in southern Brazil on Tuesday to demand land and freedom 
for jailed compatriots in Parana state, a hotbed of agrarian 
unrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Holding banners reading ``No more killing,'' some 4,000  
protesters massed in front of the governor's palace in Curitiba, 
the Parana state capital 420 miles southwest of Rio, organizers 
said. Hundreds set up makeshift tents on the lawn outside in 
preparation for a long protest, as police watched from a distance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're here for as long as it takes to free our 42  
companions,'' Roberto Baggio, a leader of the Landless Rural 
Workers Movement, said by phone from Curitiba. 
</P>
<P>
	Baggio said police had arrested some 200 members of the  
movement, which encourages farm workers to invade idle land to 
pressure the government to speed up agrarian reform. Fifteen 
members were killed in clashes over land. he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Uneven distribution of land is behind the violence in Brazil,  
where one-fifth of the population owns nearly 90 percent of the 
arable land. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
