<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Accuses Microsoft of Misconduct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A manager for IBM today accused Microsoft of  
dangling valuable discounts for Windows if IBM agreed not to 
distribute rival software on its line of personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	The allegation in Microsoft's antitrust trial from Garry Norris,  
supported by his handwritten notes from a March 1997 meeting, was 
characterized by government lawyers as the most flagrant example of 
Microsoft Corp.'s illegal aggression toward competitors.	   However, Norris, a mid-level manager for International Business 
Machines Corp., backed off a central claim in his earlier testimony 
-- that Microsoft proposed an alliance in 1994 if IBM would abandon 
its rival OS/2 operating system and ``primarily promote'' Windows 
on its computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft lawyer Rick Pepperman confronted Norris with later  
drafts of the alliance proposal -- which IBM ultimately rejected -- 
requiring IBM to promote Windows ``but not exclusive to products 
offered by other divisions of IBM, affiliates or ventures of IBM.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said he never saw those later drafts, but acknowledged  
they didn't include restrictions against selling OS/2. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly appears that way,'' Norris said.  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson asked Norris how he  
could be sure the later drafts were genuine, since they weren't 
turned over by IBM but were found in Microsoft's files. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepperman offered to put on the witness stand two Microsoft  
executives to vouch for the drafts. But in a stinging rebuke, the 
judge replied that if they were to testify, ``there's a lot more 
they'll have to testify about than these documents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday, Norris testified about Microsoft's alleged  
efforts to dissuade IBM from supporting software rivals. He said 
said that Microsoft executive Bengt Ackerlind had told him clearly 
during a 1997 meeting: ``No Netscape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The government showed the judge Norris' handwritten notes from  
that meeting, when Microsoft allegedly offered to increase rebates 
available under its Market Development Agreements if IBM promised 
not to include Internet software from Netscape Communications Corp. 
in the personal computers it sold. 
</P>
<P>
	In notes he marked in the margins with three asterisks for  
significance, Norris wrote: ``No Netscape &AMP; receive more MDA $ 
across the PC Co.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Norris, the government's next-to-last witness in the trial,  
recounted the meeting with Ackerlind, who wanted IBM to distribute 
on its computers the fourth version of Microsoft's Internet 
Explorer Web browser software. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would have to agree to load IE 4 without any competitive  
software,'' Norris said, shifting in his seat to face the judge. 
``Bengt was very specific. He said, 'No Netscape.''' 
</P>
<P>
	For a second day, the judge appeared transfixed by parts of the  
testimony. He took notes and alternated glances between Norris and 
Microsoft's lawyers at their defense table. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray said outside the courtroom that  
Ackerlind was referring only to the software to be loaded on a 
prototype ``Broadcast PC,'' an expensive computer with television 
features that IBM and Microsoft considered developing years ago but 
ultimately canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't believe such a proposal was ever made,'' Murray said.  
</P>
<P>
	Murray also noted that IBM continues to this day to distribute  
rival software on its popular line of desktops and portable 
Thinkpad machines. The price IBM pays for Windows remains among the 
lowest in the industry, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But E-mail from Norris about plans for the Broadcast PC  
indicated that Microsoft offered IBM other incentives -- including 
the secret blueprints to Windows -- if it agreed to ``neutralize'' 
its desktops and Thinkpads, and even its business-level servers by 
removing ``objectionable software.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft described a ``neutral'' computer as one that included  
Microsoft's own word processor, spreadsheet, digital encyclopedia, 
Internet software, finance software and several games, Norris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris said Microsoft was angry about IBM's support for  
Netscape's Internet software and its distribution of the Lotus 
Development Corp. ``SmartSuite'' package of business applications. 
IBM bought Lotus in the summer of 1995, and SmartSuite competes 
directly with the lucrative Microsoft Office package. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
