<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Zurich Opera Head Moves to Cleveland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Franz Welser-Moest, head of the Zurich Opera,  
has been named music director of the Cleveland Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	Welser-Moest signed a five-year contract Monday and will take  
over in 2002 when music director Christopher von Dohnanyi retires. 
</P>
<P>
	The 38-year-old Welser-Moest ``is equally at home with classical  
and Central European repertoire as he is with innovative and 
unusual contemporary repertoire,'' said Richard Bogomolny, 
president of the orchestra's board. 
</P>
<P>
	The Austrian conductor was trained as a violinist but turned to  
conducting following a serious car accident in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	His international career began in 1986 when he filled in as a  
substitute conductor for the London Philharmonic. He ultimately 
served as its music director for six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1995, Welser-Moest has been in Zurich, where he has gained  
a reputation for improving the symphony and luring renowned 
conductors as guests, including von Dohnanyi. 
</P>
<P>
	He has a recording contract with EMI/Angel and has twice been  
nominated for Grammy Awards for recordings with the London 
Philharmonic and Philadelphia Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial terms of his contract with the Cleveland Orchestra  
were not disclosed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
