<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars' Belfour Allows 3 Late Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Dallas Stars fans were screaming ``Ed-die!  
Ed-die!'' before Game 1 of the Stanley Cup finals even began. They 
were muttering the same words as they left. 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour, who looked so good for the first two periods, allowed  
two third-period goals and another 15:30 into overtime as the 
Buffalo Sabres beat Dallas 3-2 Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	For the Stars to win this series, Belfour is going to have be  
better than his counterpart, Dominik Hasek. The numbers say he 
wasn't. 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour allowed three goals on 24 shots. He had stopped the  
first 11 before giving up goals to Stu Barnes and Wayne Primeau 
within a 5:04 span of the third period, then was beat by Jason 
Woolley in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew we were going to get our chances,'' Buffalo captain  
Michael Peca said. ``It was just a matter of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek stopped 35 shots, allowing two goals when Dallas had a  
man-advantage. The Stars got a power-play goal from Brett Hull 
midway through the first period and Jere Lehtinen scored with 48 
seconds left in regulation while Dallas went with an empty net. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we shot a lot of pucks right at him,'' Stars captain  
Derian Hatcher said. ``Not to take anything away from him, but I 
don't think we forced him to make too many spectacular saves. We 
have to make it tougher on Dominik.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour made several big saves in overtime. He was all over a  
breakaway chance by Geoff Sanderson with 8:44 left that again had 
fans cheering his name. 
</P>
<P>
	With 6:07 left, fans held their breath when Belfour stopped a  
shot but didn't smother the rebound. The puck was accidentally 
kicked back toward the net by Brian Skrudland as he skated away, 
but Belfour covered it just before it crossed the goal line. 
Officials reviewed the play and upheld the initial no-goal ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Woolley took a pass from the wall and sent a slap shot  
under Belfour, dropping his career record to 14-14 in overtime 
playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a seeing-eye dog; it goes through Eddie's legs,'' Dallas  
coach Ken Hitchcock said. 
</P>
<P>
	Woolley skated into corner with his arms up and leaned against  
the glass as a dejected Belfour skated off the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had just come off the bench, so I think I snuck up on  
them,'' Woolley said. ``I got lucky it went in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour, playing in his second career finals, is still seeking  
his first win. He was in goal for Chicago when Pittsburgh swept 
them in the 1992 finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour looked good early, even though Buffalo tested him just  
five times in the first period and four more in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres finally got to him with 11:27 left in the third  
period when Joe Juneau found Stu Barnes uncovered in front of the 
net and he fired a waist-high slap shot that beat Belfour on his 
glove side, tying the game at 1. 
</P>
<P>
	After two nice saves, Buffalo went ahead 2-1 on Primeau's  
power-play goal that Belfour probably never saw. 
</P>
<P>
	``My main job is just to create traffic and screen the  
goaltender,'' Primeau said. ``The guys were playing the puck really 
well around the outside. A rebound came to me and I was able to pop 
it home.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
