<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Up in Midday Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was sharply lower against the yen  
Wednesday morning amid speculation a Japanese government report 
will indicate the economy is recovering. Tokyo stocks edged higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 119.36 yen in early trading, down 1.96 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo but higher than its level of 118.88 yen 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average rose 18.85 points, or 0.01 percent, to  
finish the morning session at 16,581.77. On Tuesday, the average 
closed up 87.03 points, or 0.53 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar came under selling pressure overseas following rumors  
that a government report due out Thursday would show the country 
may be finally recovering from its worst recession since World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors emerged that the report would show GDP growing, perhaps  
indicating that Japan has turned the corner in its fight against 
its economic slump. 
</P>
<P>
	The currency's relative strength from its New York level came  
after traders bought the greenback to cover short, or oversold, 
positions amid concerns that Japanese financial officials might 
warn against a stronger yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, influential Japanese finance ministry official,  
Eisuke Sakakibara, warned against a strengthening of the yen before 
Japan's economy recovers. Traders said that caution remained 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 124.77 yen, down  
from 125.98 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices edged higher despite a 143-point  
fall in the Dow Jones industrial average Tuesday and a stronger 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 5.46 points, or 0.04 percent, to 1,344.60. The 
TOPIX closed up 10.49 points, or 0.79 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.5600 percent from  
Tuesday's finish of 1.5750 percent, driving its price up to 98.61 
yen from 98.48 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
