<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Dismisses War Powers Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge dismissed a lawsuit brought by  
House members who accused President Clinton of overstepping his 
authority when he ordered the U.S. military to take part in the 
bombing of Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31 lawmakers who filed the lawsuit claimed that Clinton  
violated the 1973 War Powers Act when he authorized U.S. 
involvement in the NATO airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vietnam War-era legislation, which has been ignored by  
presidents of both parties, requires a president to receive 
congressional approval for the ``introduction into hostilities'' of 
U.S. forces for more than 60 days. The NATO air campaign began 
March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Paul Friedman did not addressing the merits  
of the claim in dismissing the case Tuesday but ruled that the 
lawmakers lacked the legal standing to sue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Plaintiffs have failed to establish a sufficiently genuine  
impasse between the legislative and executive branches to give them 
standing,'' Friedman wrote in his opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Tom Campbell, the California Republican who led the  
lawmakers suing the president, said he would appeal the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``The effect of today's ruling is to prevent any member of  
Congress from contesting a war that the president initiates and 
carries forward in the absence of a declaration of Congress,'' 
Campbell said in a statement. ``That is an absurdity if the 
Constitution's war declaration authority is to have any meaning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In their lawsuit, the 31 lawmakers, including four Democrats,  
noted a 213-213 vote on April 28 that fell short of authorizing 
U.S. participation in the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia. Another vote 
that day rejected a resolution declaring a state of war between the 
two countries. The lawmakers claim that Clinton ignored both votes 
by continuing with the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	But Friedman said that ``congressional reaction to the  
airstrikes has sent distinctly mixed messages.'' He noted that 
Congress later defeated a bill that would have removed U.S. troops 
from Yugoslavia. It also passed an emergency spending bill to help 
pay for bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had the four votes been consistent and against the president's  
position, and had he nevertheless persisted with airstrikes in the 
face of such votes, there may well have been a constitutional 
impasse,'' Friedman said. ``But Congress has not sent such a clear, 
consistent message.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
