<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 23:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> For Now, New Hastert Strategy Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Heeding House Speaker Dennis Hastert's call  
for Republican unity, GOP lawmakers have pushed the first spending 
bill of the year through the chamber. But it is unclear how far 
their newfound togetherness will take them. 
</P>
<P>
	On a near party-line 246-183 vote, the House approved a $61  
billion measure Tuesday financing agriculture, food and drug 
programs for fiscal 2000. It was the first of the 13 annual 
spending bills for the next fiscal year, which starts Oct. 1, to 
pass either chamber of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Passage marked a victory for Hastert, R-Ill., because until  
Tuesday the measure had been bogged down by conservatives angry 
that the measure spent too much. It was approved only after the 
House voted 234-195 -- again mostly along party lines -- to cut $102 
million from Agriculture Department construction and other accounts 
in the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	It also came after Hastert used a closed-door morning meeting  
with Republicans to rally them behind his leadership after six 
months in which the House GOP's agenda has slowed markedly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am asking each of you as directly as I can, search your  
heart, search your conscience, and then decide to join us,'' he 
told them, according to excerpts provided by his staff. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending cuts -- which Republicans hope to follow with  
reductions in some other spending bills -- are designed to portray 
the GOP as fiscally conservative. They are also aimed at creating a 
pot of money that can be added to some of the later, bigger 
spending measures for education, environment and other programs so 
they can garner enough votes to pass the House. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall GOP goal is to keep all 13 spending bills below the  
$538 billion cap set by the 1997 budget-balancing pact with 
President Clinton. They will not propose spending beyond that, they 
say, because to do so would require spending Social Security 
surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to show the American people which party is for a  
smaller government, which party wants to strengthen Social 
Security, and which party wants to return the surpluses to the 
taxpayer before it is spent,'' Hastert told his colleagues at their 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, most Republicans concede that some of the biggest, most  
controversial spending bills may never be approved by the House, 
and won't make it into law without autumn negotiations with the 
White House. That is because they will fall billions below 1999 
levels and even further below what Clinton wants. 
</P>
<P>
	Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said it will be a ``long, hot  
summer. It's going to be difficult, we know that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Only in their own mind'' have Republicans solved their problem  
of pushing the spending bills through the House, said Rep. David 
Obey, D-Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	Other bills expected to endure relatively small cuts include  
measures financing the Treasury Department and Congress' own 
operations. A $270 billion measure financing the Pentagon was 
expected to be exempted because of the GOP's strong pro-defense 
stance. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert's larger concern was the November 2000 elections and  
worries that GOP infighting over spending, taxes and other issues 
are undermining their chances of retaining House control. Those 
internal differences are magnified by the GOP's thin majority, in 
which defections by just six Republicans could defeat a GOP 
initiative. 
</P>
<P>
	Praise for Hastert's remarks came from both conservative and  
moderate Republicans, some of whom contrasted them with the more 
fiery style of his predecessor as speaker, Rep. Newt Gingrich, 
R-Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just appealed to everybody to be part of the team,'' said  
conservative Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla. ``We weren't called 
stupid once. ... Nobody was taken to task for questioning the 
genius of the Republican leadership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By honoring spending caps and delivering a promised $19 billion  
increase for defense, domestic spending bills would be more than 
$30 billion short of what Clinton wants to spend. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the extra $7 billion Republicans hope to find from  
trimming some bills and selling part of the broadcast spectrum, at 
least three bills covering health, veterans, commerce and other 
programs are likely to fall well short of what Clinton will demand. 
That is likely to lead to negotiations with Clinton this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Differences remained among Republicans over other complicated  
issues such as which taxes to cut, how strictly to limit access to 
guns, the Kosovo intervention and whether to overhaul campaign 
finance laws. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
