<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Average Joe' Frustrates the Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Law enforcers have come to bank on the elusive  
robber's routine: Smiling in sunglasses, he coolly waits his turn 
to see a teller, then springs a note demanding cash and, sometimes, 
a cordial sendoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten times at different Detroit-area banks he's done it since  
April, each time making off with loot and the note he takes back, 
apparently aware of its evidentiary value. 
</P>
<P>
	The bandit is so casually clad, pleasant and smooth in demeanor,  
investigators have dubbed him ``The Average Joe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We call him that based on the fact that he's totally  
unremarkable in what he does,'' Kevin Kendrick, special agent in 
charge of the FBI's Oakland County office in Troy, said Monday. 
``He's basically your chameleon kind of guy. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not really aggravating. He's more like a thorn. Every so  
often, you're made aware that he's there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities believe the spree began with a holdup of a Warren  
bank on April 22. Two days later, he robbed another one in that 
Detroit suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	Both times, tellers complied with a note's demands for cash, a  
``thank you'' and a ``have a nice day'' -- demands accompanied with 
threats if the courtesies weren't extended, Warren police Detective 
Jeff Pierog said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Oakland County banks were held up in as many days last  
month. The most recent heist came Thursday at a branch in suburban 
Troy. 
</P>
<P>
	In every case, Kendrick said, the suspect ``walks in, waits in  
line like everyone else and isn't rude -- I'll give him that,'' then 
slips the teller a note, snatching it back once it has been read. 
</P>
<P>
	Each time he has demanded cash in small denominations --  
generally $100, $50 and $20 bills. The robber suggests he has a 
weapon but has never shown one, Kendrick said. 
</P>
<P>
	Surveillance cameras have photographed the bandit in various  
disguises and clothes, though without fail he has sported 
sunglasses and a baseball or fishing hat. Several times, he's 
smirked at the camera. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators ``have what we believe to be outstanding photos''  
of the suspect but no sizable leads, Kendrick said. One reason: the 
suspect is, well, average -- a 6-foot, 180-pound man, 25 to 35 years 
old, wearing unremarkable clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hits so many different places it's hard to pinpoint his  
next hit,'' Pierog said. ``There's no rhyme or reason.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kendrick and Comerica Inc. -- targeted in at least six holdups --  
would not divulge the robber's take or security measures banks 
employ. 
</P>
<P>
	A $2,000 reward for his arrest is being offered by the Detroit  
Clearinghouse Association, a banking group. 
</P>
<P>
	Pierog said he thinks success may be a matter of time, and  
believes the suspect is ``getting a little cocky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We just have to wait until the next time he hits. Maybe we'll  
get lucky.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 05:30:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crashed Plane Cleared for Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Investigators prepared to pore over the  
instruments aboard the American Airlines jet that crashed here last 
week, while an airport hangar has become the grim repository for 
its twisted remains. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots' console containing many of the jet's important  
controls was removed Monday from the smashed nose of the plane 
after it was taken in pieces from its crash site to a private 
hangar. 
</P>
<P>
	Preliminary evidence indicates the pilots apparently skipped all  
or part of their regular checklist as they tried to land in a 
powerful storm, USA Today reported in today's editions, citing 
unidentified sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane's co-pilot said last week that he believes the  
spoilers were deployed to help slow the plane, but data recorders 
indicate that they did not open at touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Flight 1420's spoiler system -- along with its anti-skid, thrust  
reverser and braking systems -- will be removed and sent to labs run 
by the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators also are examining whether mechanical problems,  
pilot error or severe weather -- or a combination of those factors -- 
played a role in the crash. The plane's engines were removed 
earlier and shipped to an American Airlines hangar in Tulsa, Okla., 
for tests and possible dismantling. 
</P>
<P>
	Testing is expected to take up to three weeks, said lead NTSB  
investigator Greg Feith. Scrutiny of the jet's other parts is 
expected to take months. 
</P>
<P>
	Examinations could reveal whether the flight's first officer is  
correct in believing Capt. Richard Buschmann properly prepared for 
landing. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight crashed on landing during a thunderstorm June 1 at  
Little Rock National Airport, killing nine, including Buschmann, 
and injuring more than 80. Fourteen survivors remained hospitalized 
on Monday, three in critical condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral services are to be held today and Wednesday in  
Russellville, Ark. for two crash victims. 
</P>
<P>
	The jet, which made its approach as a violent thunderstorm  
overtook the airport, roared off the runway at 92 mph, clipped a 
bank of lights and slammed into the steel supports of a walkway 
near the Arkansas River. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the airport hangar, the piles of parts create a jarring  
tableau: a jumble of twisted wires dangling from the jet's smashed 
nose, blue passenger seats leaning into a crushed left fuselage and 
a plastic magazine rack still attached to the bulkhead, its 
periodicals undisturbed despite a missing sidewall. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials expect to reopen the airport's damaged runway this  
week. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
