<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. Mulls Concert Warning Labels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Seeing Marilyn Manson strapped to a cross  
and wearing a black G-string on stage convinced state Sen. Dale 
Shugars that parents had to be warned. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was like Satan,'' Shugars said of the April concert by the  
shock rocker in Grand Rapids. 
</P>
<P>
	After seeing the concert, accompanied by two body guards,  
Shugars lobbied even harder for a bill he sponsored that would 
require parental advisories on tickets, posters and other 
advertising for certain concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure passed the state Senate last month and is now before  
a House committee. If it passes the full House, it would be the 
first law of its kind in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``We found that a lot of times parents weren't aware of what the  
lyrics are, lyrics about drug abuse, raping and killing,'' Shugars 
said. ``Does this guarantee that parents won't let their kids go to 
these concerts? No. But it does guarantee a red flag.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit entertainment attorney Mike Novak called the bill a  
waste of state time -- and may even backfire. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is naive to suggest that putting some sort of a  
warning on shows will somehow solve problems,'' Novak said Tuesday. 
``Many bands will seek out this kind of labeling to make them more 
appealing to certain audiences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Novak also said the bill is insulting because it suggests  
parents don't know what their kids are listening to. 
</P>
<P>
	But state Rep. Sue Tabor, R-Delta Township, argues that she used  
to be one of those parents. 
</P>
<P>
	After her husband read about Shugars' bill, she said, ``he sort  
of declared war in our household.'' The Tabors and their sons held 
a meeting to look through the boys' compact discs. 
</P>
<P>
	``My husband found one CD that did have the parental advisory  
label on it. He read the lyrics to me and I was absolutely appalled 
and stunned,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to point out that, hey, I think I'm a pretty good  
parent. We try to pay attention, we have a good, loving, Christian 
home. But one of my kids had these CDs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The group that got parental warning labels put on albums, the  
Recording Industry Association of America, opposes the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a draconian measure that we feel could undermine a  
program that's working,'' said Joel Flatow, RIAA vice president of 
government affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, concert promoters or venue operators would have  
to put warning labels on tickets, posters or advertisements for any 
artist who has put out an album with a parental advisory label in 
the past five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would let promoters or venues choose to put the label  
on only one form of advertisement -- for example, only the concert 
posters or only the tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	If they fail to put any warning, they could be fined up to  
$5,000. Record companies voluntarily place the warnings on their 
albums as part of the RIAA program, which began in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathan Wey, a 17-year-old rock fan from East Lansing, said the  
concern over Manson's lyrics is overblown. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of these bands that they're trying to target aren't  
really that violent at all,'' he said. ``Marilyn Manson is opposed 
to violence. I think the whole point of his music is trying to be 
yourself.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
