<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Gore Back From Mental Illness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tipper Gore told of sinking into such a  
depression that she went to a doctor and said, ``I need some 
help.'' A congresswoman talked about severe mood swings in her 
youth and how she couldn't look after her children. 
</P>
<P>
	A college student said that at age 15, she was taking in only 20  
calories a day and doing so many sit-ups she got sores on her back 
and hips, all in an irrational and potentially deadly drive to be 
thin. 
</P>
<P>
	Giving voice to each of these cases, a White House conference  
Monday showed just how close to home mental illness can be. 
</P>
<P>
	Organized by Mrs. Gore, wife of Vice President Al Gore, the  
meeting tried to make people understand mental illness is a 
sickness much like any other -- ``a real disease of a real organ, 
the brain,'' as one professional put it -- and that no one should 
feel shame or suffer discrimination for getting treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, public attitudes don't lump Mrs. Gore's bout with  
clinical depression 10 years ago in the same category as President 
Clinton's recovery from a bum knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Mental illness is ``the last great stigma of the 20th century,''  
Mrs. Gore said, noting how cancer and then AIDS were once 
unmentionable in many families. ``Most people treat someone with a 
mental illness as if it's their fault or as if they can just snap 
out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	People must know ``there is the right diagnosis and the right  
treatment and the right health care professional out there for 
you,'' she said. About 50 million Americans are estimated to suffer 
some form of mental illness during their lives, but only one in 
five seeks treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons and the Gores shared the stage with CBS newsman  
Mike Wallace, whose own depression once laid him ``lower than a 
snake's belly,'' as well as others who believe healing power is 
found in the knowledge that mental problems strike people in all 
walks of life. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Lynn Rivers, D-Mich., wife of an auto worker, said mood  
swings in her late teens were first signs of her manic depression. 
Later, ``I had two babies I could not deal with.'' She said the day 
she was diagnosed was a happy one because ``I was finally dealing 
with something that was not my fault.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, she said it took 10 years to figure out the right mix  
of medication, and the treatment at one point was eating half the 
family's income. She went public with her problem after political 
opponents in the 1994 election that brought her to Congress spread 
word that she had had a breakdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Against a backdrop of such testimony, Clinton asked Congress to  
ensure Americans with mental illness get the same health benefits 
they now have for broken bones or an asthma attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Without proper treatment for mental illness, he said, ``the loss  
of human potential is staggering.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A bill to eliminate distinctions between physical and mental  
health coverage is pending in the Senate but the Republican-led 
Congress has been wary of costly health care measures. The health 
insurance industry also is worried about mandated benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our experience has been that mandates, no matter how well  
intentioned, raise the cost of coverage,'' said Richard Coorsh of 
the Health Insurance Association of America. The National 
Association of Manufacturers also criticized the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gore said she sought professional help and medication for  
clinical depression because ``I was not myself,'' after her son 
Albert was hit by a car in 1989, an accident from which he has 
recovered. So, she said, has she. ``I'm happy to say that it 
worked,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting heard from Jennifer Gates, a sophomore at William  
and Mary who struggled with anorexia nervosa in high school. 
Compliments about her slim figure made her want to be skinnier 
still. One night her mother, in tears, woke her in the middle of 
the night trying to get her to eat some yogurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw how much pain she was in,'' she said. ``I couldn't bring  
myself to eat it. I was just so desperate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Professional help finally paid off, as it has for Robyn  
Kitchell's son, a manic depressive who recently graduated from the 
eighth grade and won a football award, even as the struggle against 
his illness continues. 
</P>
<P>
	``When mental illness hits puberty, boy is that a ride,''  
Kitchell said. She spoke of the imbalance of a health system that 
would cover her son's physical diagnostic tests for manic 
depression but not the $150 psychiatric sessions in Nashville, 
Tenn. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
