<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Hopefuls To Swarm Calif </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- White House hopefuls plan to swarm  
into California in a hunt for a mother lode of campaign cash, 
delegates and news media attention. 
</P>
<P>
	By advancing its primary to March 7, 2000, California has set  
off an early stampede by presidential aspirants: At least seven 
were scheduled to visit the state this month, and two candidates' 
wives will appear separately. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is completely unprecedented,'' Michael Schroeder,  
California's former Republican Party chairman, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gale Kaufman, a consultant for former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley,  
said early summer marks a critical time when presidential hopefuls 
must lay groundwork in this massive, expensive state. 
</P>
<P>
	With ``Labor Day always being a significant point in campaigns,  
you really need to have pushed off by then,'' Kaufman said. ``If 
you're looking at a March primary and trying to build a structure, 
something about June makes sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of this month's visits will not be the sort of political  
``quick hits'' California has previously drawn with its traditional 
June primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, candidates would quietly swoop in, hold a fund-raiser and  
possibly a news conference, and race back to Iowa or New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with the Golden State's primary set a week after New  
Hampshire's primary, ``presidential candidates are all over 
California as if they thought it WAS Iowa or New Hampshire,'' 
Schroeder said. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, Bradley, a Democrat, plans to hopscotch the state  
for about 10 days this month, holding what his aides bill as small 
forums with community leaders. He'll also raise money. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley is the only declared challenger to Vice President Al  
Gore for the Democratic nomination. The two will compete for the 
media spotlight June 18, when both are scheduled to campaign in Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Both men's wives also will campaign in California this month.  
</P>
<P>
	Tipper Gore will appear Saturday with First Lady Hillary Rodham  
Clinton at Democratic National Committee fund-raisers in Los 
Angeles and San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	And Ernestine Bradley was scheduled to campaign today in  
Sacramento. The event is officially a rally to pressure lawmakers 
for more breast cancer research money, but the announcement went 
out under a ``Bill Bradley for President'' letterhead. 
</P>
<P>
	And in the most anticipated campaign swing of the year, Texas  
Gov. George W. Bush has plans to finally appear in California, 
hitting five cities at the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush tops recent California polls, but has sequestered himself  
in Austin, Texas, as the Legislature there worked through its 
business. Meantime, Bush's support grew in California, and so did 
curiosity about him. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Vice President Dan Quayle spoke in Santa Barbara earlier  
this month. Other Republican presidential hopefuls who also plan 
visits include former Sen. John McCain; conservative commentator 
Pat Buchanan; and Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander's team will be smaller when he arrives. On Monday, his  
campaign made more staff cuts, letting go its deputy press 
secretary and a press aide, said a campaign source, speaking on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as California basks in its new role in the nomination  
process, there are signs its clout could decline by March. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, other states hoping to attract more attention  
from candidates also are moving their primaries up. Inspired in 
part by California's move, at least 10 other states now plan to 
hold primaries on or before March 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, one Republican lawmaker wants to scrap the  
``winner-take-all'' system that gives California much of its appeal 
for candidates, especially front-runners. 
</P>
<P>
	In the current system, the candidate who wins the primary takes  
all the delegates to the party convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ray Haynes has proposed that the delegates be awarded by  
congressional district, with varying numbers of delegates going to 
candidates depending upon how many districts they win in the 
primary. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
