<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Judge Acquits 3 of Fund Misuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Three men were cleared of charges they bought  
lingerie, Super Bowl tickets and other goods with $1.3 million 
stolen from the Port of Miami. The judge ruled they couldn't be 
convicted because the money never belonged to the government. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Donald Middlebrooks said prosecutors  
``presented substantial evidence of greed and public corruption, 
the placement of private interests over those of the public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he granted a defense motion Monday and acquitted Carmen  
Lunetta, longtime director of the county-owned port, and two 
co-defendants, saying the money didn't yet belong to the county 
when it was used on items such as vacations and a $120,000 donation 
to the Democratic National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The two other defendants were Calvin Grigsby, the owner of  
Fiscal Operations Inc., which operated cranes at the port; and Neal 
Harrington, a part-owner of a stevedoring company. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said stevedoring companies paid Fiscal Operations  
for use of cranes, and Fiscal Operations turned the money over to 
Miami-Dade County. Fiscal Operations was allowed to deduct $150,000 
a year plus expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	But prosecutors said those expenses were heavily padded with  
such things $6,000 for cleaning Grigsby's yacht, thousands of 
dollars in contributions to the Democratic National Committee, 
Super Bowl tickets, Victoria's Secret lingerie, vacation trips, 
luxury car rentals and bar tabs. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge agreed with defense attorneys' contention that the  
misused money was owed to the county, but since it had not been 
paid, was not owned by the county. 
</P>
<P>
	Grigsby faces trial next month on charges of arranging $350,000  
in kickbacks to two Miami-Dade executives in return for county bond 
business. He owned Grigsby Brandford &AMP; Co., the nation's largest 
minority-owned municipal bond underwriter until it closed in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors expressed disappointment, but U.S. Attorney Thomas  
E. Scott said the case ``brought to light the abuse of public trust 
that was rampant at the Port of Miami, and exposed the lack of 
financial controls and oversight that made this type of corruption 
possible.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
