<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Eight Nations Agree on Kosovo Force  
</P>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- The United States, Russia and six other  
nations agree on a U.N. resolution to settle the conflict with 
Yugoslavia and send international troops under NATO command to 
Kosovo. ``We got what we came for,'' Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright proclaimed. British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said 
bombing could be suspended in the next few days if Serb troops 
begin withdrawing from the province. The bombing halt is a 
significant concession to Russia, long a vocal opponent to the 
attacks. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge Dismisses War Powers Lawsuit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge today dismissed a lawsuit  
filed by a group of House members who wanted the bombing of 
Yugoslavia by U.S. forces to be declared illegal. The lawsuit by 26 
lawmakers alleged that President Clinton violated the War Powers 
Act of 1973 by authorizing military air strikes against Yugoslavia. 
The Vietnam War-era legislation requires a president to get 
congressional approval for the ``introduction into hostilities'' of 
U.S. forces for more than 60 days. The NATO air campaign began 
March 24. 

</P>
<P>
	Teens May Need IDs for R Movies  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Teen-agers will be carded to see R-rated films  
under a tougher enforcement policy adopted by thousands of movie 
theaters across America. The theater owners were responding to a 
challenge by President Clinton. The National Association of Theater 
Owners represents about 65 percent of the screens in the United 
States. ``R'' in the movie rating system is for restricted, meaning 
anyone under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian. 

</P>
<P>
	Texas OKs Abortion Notification Bill  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Likely Republican presidential candidate George W.  
Bush signed into law in Texas a bill requiring that parents be 
notified when their minor daughters seek abortions. Under the law, 
effective Sept. 1, an unmarried girl under age 18 cannot get an 
abortion until one of her parents is notified or she gets a judge's 
permission. One Right to Life committee member said abortion 
opponents have been pushing for a notification law for 25 years. 
Bush has been criticized by some in the anti-abortion movement as 
being soft on abortion. 

</P>
<P>
	High Temps Hit Eastern US  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Temperatures rose toward record highs again  
today in the East, coaxing thousands to the beach and straining 
electric utilities. Although the official start of summer is two 
weeks away, temps climbed into the 90s. Air conditioners were 
cranked up to full blast and the biggest supplier of electricity in 
Connecticut, Northeast Utilities, warned today that the demand has 
taxed the New England power grid. School districts in parts of New 
Jersey, Maryland, Virginia and Washington, D.C. are opting to close 
early. 

</P>
<P>
	Western Nations Create Anti-Drug Plan  
</P>
<P>
	GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Western Hemisphere nations are developing  
their own system to evaluate efforts to stop drug abuse in an 
effort to soothe one of the sorest points in U.S.-Latin American 
relations. The evaluation system developed by the 34-nation 
Organization of American States is not related to the U.S. policy 
of ``certifying'' other nations' drug-fighting efforts. But OAS 
members hope that even if the evaluation system doesn't end U.S. 
drug certification, it could at least influence the criteria used 
in the process. 

</P>
<P>
	Off-Peak Summer Flights Discounted  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- United Airlines today slashed ticket prices as  
much as 25 percent for off-peak summer travel, a day after warning 
too many empty seats would cause quarterly profits to fall. Delta 
Air Lines, Continental Airlines and Northwest Airlines were among 
ther first to match the United promotion on domestic and 
international travel. Consumers who purchase tickets for advance 
travel only on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Saturdays could see as much 
as a 25 percent discount over regularly priced tickets. But tickets 
must be purchased by June 18. The move undercuts a 4 percent boost 
in ticket prices instituted last week by major airlines. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 96  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 96.88 to 10,812.50. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,548-1,285. The Nasdaq was down 6.96 to 
2,517.25. 

</P>
<P>
	Malone Breaks All-NBA Record  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Karl Malone, who won the NBA's MVP award last  
week for the second time in three years, today became the first 
player ever to make 11 All-NBA teams. Six players had been on 10 
all-star teams -- Michael Jordan, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, Elgin Baylor, 
Bob Cousy, Bob Pettit and Jerry West. Joining the Utah Jazz power 
forward on the first team were San Antonio's Tim Duncan, Miami's 
Alonzo Mourning, Philadelphia's Allen Iverson and Jason Kidd of 
Phoenix. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
