<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 13:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Becker Opens With Win at Queens Club </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Boris Becker, returning to the site of his first  
pro tennis title 14 years ago, began tuning up for Wimbledon with a 
6-4, 6-4 victory over Petr Korda in the first round of the Queens 
Club tournament on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Becker, who won this event when he was 17, still showed the deft  
touch and quick movement that helped him to three Wimbledon titles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt very comfortable,'' said Becker, who says he'll be  
playing his final Wimbledon and will retire this summer. ``I was a 
bit surprised by my rhythm and my timing. Petr is a good player, 
and good on his returns especially, and I was able to play a very 
solid game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Becker's next match is against defending champion and  
15th-seeded Scott Draper of Australia, who beat qualifier Oren 
Motovassel of Israel 7-6 (7-3), 7-6 (9-7). 
</P>
<P>
	In other matches, Australia's Todd Woodbridge beat Rogier Wassen  
of the Netherlands 6-2, 6-1; Cecil Mamiit of the United States beat 
Germany's Axel Pretzsch 6-3, 6-4; fourth-seeded Mark Philippoussis 
defeated fellow American Michael Sell 6-4, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Jim Courier beat Denmark's Kenneth Carlsen 6-2, 4-6, 6-1;  
11th-seeded Cedric Pioline beat Italy's Mose Navarra 7-6 (7-2), 
3-6, 6-1; Germany's Michael Kohlmann beat ninth-seeded Swede Thomas 
Enqvist 6-4, 6-4; and Peter Tramacchi of Australia topped 
16th-seeded Fabrice Santoro 6-3, 7-6 (8-6). 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Becker said he would be playing his last  
Wimbledon, but changed his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two or three years ago I considered myself one of the few who  
had a chance at Wimbledon,'' the 31-year-old German said. ``I know 
I can play well on grass and I'm going to give a difficult match to 
anybody who's going to play me on it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 16:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Movie Rating System Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Last year's raunchy satire ``Orgazmo'' was  
slapped with an NC-17 rating for its constant stream of sex jokes 
and crude sight gags. 
</P>
<P>
	A few months later, the action-packed ``Payback'' showed Mel  
Gibson killing a variety of people in a variety of ways before he 
was tortured, but the ratings board gave the film an R rating. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, producers have complained the ratings board has more  
tolerance for violence than for sex. That raises questions about 
whether checking IDs at the theater door -- as President Clinton 
said Tuesday that theater owners have agreed to do -- will shield 
youngsters from violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The president may have complicated the issue further by getting  
the government involved, contends lawyer Alan Dershowitz, who 
helped push through the NC-17 rating in 1990 to take the X-rated 
stigma off non-pornographic films with adult themes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The system itself is skewed against sex and in favor of  
violence,'' he said. ``But once the president puts the heavy thumb 
of government on the scale, it begins to smack of governmental 
intrusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Valenti, head of the Motion Picture Association of America,  
which sets the ratings, said he applauded the agreement, calling it 
``a big step forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valenti developed the system more than 30 years ago. He admits  
it is subjective and imperfect, but said it consistently receives 
favorable reviews from parents. Over the years, the system has been 
altered only slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	Initially, the ratings were G, M, R and X, but the M -- for  
mature audiences -- was changed to PG, for parental guidance 
suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, following concerns about violence in the PG-rated  
``Gremlins'' and ``Indiana Jones'' movies, the PG rating was split 
to include a tougher PG-13 for a higher level of intensity. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, when 10 mainstream movies, including ``Henry &AMP; June,''  
received X ratings, the MPAA created the NC-17 category to separate 
films with strong adult content from sleazy porno films. 
</P>
<P>
	Many newspapers won't advertise NC-17 films and many theaters  
won't show them. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the MPA, board members place themselves in the role  
of ``most American parents'' and try to apply a rating that ``most 
parents would find suitable and helpful in aiding their decisions 
about their childrens' moviegoing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After watching the entire film, each member comes his or her own  
conclusion, then a discussion is held. The final rating is 
determined by majority vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The process is conducted in private and the MPA doesn't  
generally comment in detail on why a particular rating is assigned. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the secrecy and vagueness of the process that most  
frustrates filmmakers, who often complain they're never entirely 
sure what the ratings board found objectionable. 
</P>
<P>
	Often, it is a matter of degree.  
</P>
<P>
	Paul Thomas Anderson, who directed the sex-filled movie ``Boogie  
Nights,'' said he only had to remove about 40 seconds from the 
three-hour movie to get it from an NC-17 to an R. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the guidelines, a G film ``contains nothing in theme,  
language, nudity, sex or violence ... which would be offensive to 
parents whose younger children view the film.'' 
</P>
<P>
	PG films are those that parents should examine before they let  
their children attend, the MPA said. There may be some profanity, 
violence and brief nudity, but none of these would be considered 
too intense. 
</P>
<P>
	PG-13 films carry a more stern warning for parents to see the  
film for themselves first. This kind of film ``leaps beyond the 
boundaries of the PG rating'' for violence, nudity and language. It 
does allow drug content, but usually no nudity in a sexual sense. 
</P>
<P>
	R-rated films may include ``hard language, or tough violence, or  
nudity within sensual scenes, or drug abuse.'' The MPA says that 
parents ``must find out more about an R-rated movie before they let 
their teen-agers view it.'' Anyone under 17 needs to be accompanied 
by a parent or adult guardian. 
</P>
<P>
	The MPA says that NC-17 films are those that ``most parents will  
consider patently too adult for their youngsters 17 and under.'' 
This rating can be due to violence, sex, ``aberrational behavior'' 
or drug abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	At Universal Studios Cineplex Odeon in Universal City,  
15-year-old Hunter Pechin said enforcement of the ratings system is 
spotty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some places know you're not 17, but they'll let you in, no  
questions asked,'' he said. ``Other places won't let you buy 
tickets.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Sets Sights on New Hampshire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush said today that  
he would not campaign or file as a Republican presidential 
candidate in any state that encroaches on New Hampshire's 
first-in-the-nation primary. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who makes his first campaign trip to New Hampshire next  
Monday, said he knows he's late getting to the state, but he's 
ready to convince New Hampshire voters he knows how to lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I have a lot of work do to and I'm looking forward to  
doing it,'' he said in a telephone conference call with New 
Hampshire reporters. ``I'll honor the pledge and I intend to put 
together a great grass-roots organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush made his primary commitment in a letter to the secretary of  
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Rival Elizabeth Dole said she would sign the New Hampshire  
primary pledge Wednesday. ``New Hampshire first by seven days,'' 
she said, referring to state law requiring the primary to be held 
at least a week before any other. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush also said he had sent a letter accepting the Americans for  
Tax Reform pledge to veto any income tax increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor said he plans to spend his time in New  
Hampshire talking about tax cuts, free trade, education and 
strengthening the military. 
</P>
<P>
	He offered few specifics, saying voters should be patient. ``I  
think it's important for those who are watching the campaign to 
understand I will have a timetable,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic National Committee Chairman Joe Andrew, who met with  
Gov. Jeanne Shaheen and other officials Tuesday, predicted Bush 
would clash with voters who expect specific answers to specific 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like the Titanic,'' he said. ``Great theme music, great  
boat, everyone wants to get on.... New Hampshire has a long history 
of debunking candidates who won't take a stand. I think that will 
be the iceberg he'll run into.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush acknowledged the pressure to impress during his first trip  
to New Hampshire. He leads in the polls even though he hasn't yet 
started campaigning. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first problem I have is expectations are out of sight for  
me,'' he said. ``It means I'll have to go up there and shake as 
many hands as I can. My first hurdle is to tell people what's in my 
heart.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
