<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 05:40:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Buying Bank of New York Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp.'s financing subsidiary has  
agreed to pay $1.8 billion for a commercial lending unit of The 
Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Acceptance Corp. will acquire BNY Financial  
Corp., which has about 3,000 clients worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, disclosed Tuesday, is subject to regulatory approval.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is an outstanding opportunity for GMAC to acquire an  
established asset-based lending and factoring company with an 
experienced management team that has achieved 17 consecutive years 
of increased profits,'' GMAC Chairman John D. Finnegan said in a 
news release. 
</P>
<P>
	BNY Financial is based in New York City and has 15 offices and  
about 900 employees worldwide. It reported $26.7 billion in sales 
and $3.9 billion in assets in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The new GMAC subsidiary will be called GMAC Commercial Credit  
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	BNY Financial Chairman and chief executive Joseph A. Grimaldi  
said customers will see few changes, and employees will keep their 
titles and duties. He will become president and chief executive of 
the new subsidiary. 
</P>
<P>
	GMAC had more than $140 billion in assets on March 31, 1999.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
