<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 09:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Stock Market Up 12 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's stock market soared 12  
percent Tuesday, lifting indexes in neighboring Singapore and 
Malaysia, as a remarkably smooth election process raised hopes for 
political stability in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia's currency, which was battered at the height of the  
Asian financial crisis, also benefited from the enthusiasm among 
investors, strengthening to 7,648 rupiah to the dollar. Last week 
it took more than 8,000 rupiah to get one dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta stock exchange's Composite Index closed with a  
stunning gain of 12.2 percent, slightly off its high for the day. 
Only two stocks fell, 189 gained and 24 were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Yohanna Iskandar, an analyst with Panin Securities, told Dow  
Jones Newswires that the main factor behind the ``frenzy buying'' 
was the smooth elections Monday. A strong showing on Wall Street 
also added to the positive sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	The elections, hailed as the most free in decades, came more  
than a year after pro-democracy protests ended President Suharto's 
32-year authoritarian rule. The balloting in this ethnically 
diverse archipelago of 210 million people was held in remarkable 
peace. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the rally Tuesday, there were concerns that Indonesia's  
stock market might be deflated by any negative political 
developments before a new president is chosen in November. 
</P>
<P>
	The euphoria in Indonesia's markets spilled over into exchanges  
in neighboring countries, which could also benefit from greater 
investment if Indonesian politics remain calm. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore's Straits Times Index jumped 2.1 percent, reaching a  
two-year high, and Malaysia's Composite Index of 100 quality stocks 
surged 3.3 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 10:41:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Soccer's Vieri Sold in $43M Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- In what would be a record soccer deal worth $43  
million, Italian striker Christian Vieri was set Tuesday to be sent 
from Lazio to Internazionale of Milan. 
</P>
<P>
	Vieri, the biggest star on Italy's national team, would be  
paired up front at Inter with Ronaldo, the two-time FIFA World 
Player of the Year. This would be Vieri's ninth club in eight 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vieri is Inter's,'' Inter owner Massimo Moratti said. ``He  
will play alongside Ronaldo next season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Lazio said negotiations are at an ``advanced stage''  
but the deal is not yet signed. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale would give Inter soccer's most expensive attack.  
Ronaldo went to Inter for a then-record $28 million two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Moratti said Argentine midfielder Diego Simeone will be sent to  
Lazio, offsetting some of the cash cost. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal would be a record for a soccer transfer. However,  
Brazilian star Denilson's move from Sao Paolo to Real Betis -- 
completed in 1997 and worth $35 million -- remains the most 
expensive cash-only transfer. 
</P>
<P>
	Vieri led Italy with five goals at the 1998 World Cup. He had a  
goal and an assist Saturday as Italy moved within one victory of 
clinching a berth at the 2000 European Championships by routing 
Wales 4-0. 
</P>
<P>
	He scored 13 goals in 22 league games in his first and only  
season with Lazio, which won the Cup Winners Cup but lost the Serie 
A title by one point to AC Milan. 
</P>
<P>
	The other chief bidder for Vieri had been Juventus, one of the  
forward's former teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Vieri can muscle many defenders off the ball. While at times he  
appears clumsy, he can score with both feet and is dangerous on 
headers. 
</P>
<P>
	His power should be a perfect complement to Ronaldo's pace and  
precision. 
</P>
<P>
	Vieri came to Lazio from Spain's Atletico Madrid last August for  
a $30 million transfer fee. He was thought to be the final piece of 
the puzzle that would bring Lazio its first league title since 
1974. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
