<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 08:00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Limits Use of N.J. Ballfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Baseball may be as American as apple pie,  
but a man who built a professional ball field in his back yard is 
breaking the law by bringing in too many crowds, a judge says. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Ingraham broke zoning laws in Tewksbury Township with  
round-the-clock games on his regulation-size diamond, Superior 
Court Judge Victor Ashrafi said Monday. The ruling came in a 
2-year-old lawsuit filed by township officials and neighbors who 
said the 12-hour days of games, traffic and pinging of bats 
shattered their privacy and peace of mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingraham, a label company owner who moved to western New Jersey  
horse country to build his field of dreams, has said that Tewksbury 
just doesn't like baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	While agreeing with township officials that the field violated  
zoning laws, the judge rejected arguments that the field was a 
public nuisance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Children playing baseball cannot easily be branded a  
nuisance,'' Ashrafi wrote in a 55-page opinion. ``One might as well 
say that apple pie is poison.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But the fact that baseball for kids is wholesome and patriotic  
does not mean that full-scale games, practices and training can be 
held anywhere,'' Ashrafi added. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingraham spent nearly $300,000 to build the field and an indoor  
pool house in 1996, and sent out fliers advertising a ``Field of 
Dreams Academy,'' with classes for youngsters and a 35-and-over 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	He abandoned his plan to turn the field into a business after  
the township -- Gov. Christie Whitman's hometown -- told him it was 
illegal. But he said he still wanted to play ball with his 
11-year-old son and his friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Neighbors and the township sued in 1997, saying Ingraham's use  
of the field, with back-to-back games, spectators and professional 
umpires, was out of hand. Ingraham has been limited by a court 
order to playing four days a week in small groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingraham's attorney said he would ask his client whether he  
wanted to appeal. Terence Scott had argued that Ingraham used his 
field the way that other neighbors use tennis courts or swimming 
pools. But Scott said Ingraham would live with the ruling, for now. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashrafi ruled that Ingraham, his wife and two children can play  
baseball anytime they want with up to eight guests, but they can 
have larger groups just once a month. The ruling also bans 
uniforms, aluminum bats, night games, loudspeakers and outdoor 
lighting. Ingraham also can't bring organized, league teams or paid 
officials onto the field, Ashrafi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tewksbury's deputy mayor, Tres Arnett, called the lawsuit's end  
``a reasonable result.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't looking to have him plow the field under,'' Arnett  
said. ``It was up to the judge to draw a line.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 16:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
