<DOCNO> APW19990608.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 23:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Dole Departs From Script </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Super Mom or Super Executive. Women must  
choose, said Republican Elizabeth Dole, casting her own path -- all 
career, no children -- as a reality accepted but not chosen. ``I've 
just lived this life,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole, the only woman in the 2000 presidential field, spoke  
for the first time in the campaign about her family life in a 
wide-ranging interview Tuesday with The Associated Press. After a 
calculated decision to ``go solo'' in the early months and 
establish her own credentials, she said her husband, Bob, the 1996 
GOP presidential nominee, would take a higher profile in her 
campaign and help raise some badly needed money. 
</P>
<P>
	``He never did it for himself. He just doesn't want to ask  
anybody for money. But you want to know something? He's doing it 
for me,'' said Mrs. Dole, who plans to announce her candidacy 
formally in late summer or early fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's on the phone asking for money and he's also going to be  
doing some fund-raisers between now and the end of the month,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Kansas senator and Republican leader would bring  
stature and experience to her White House, Mrs. Dole said, and he 
would be particularly suited to handle agriculture issues. But 
there would be no Cabinet post, no ``two for the price of one'' 
that supporters of Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton promised in 
1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to be a co-presidency,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole, 62, is trying to become the first American woman to  
win a major party nomination. She ranks second in GOP polls, well 
behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush (``I believe he's a fine 
candidate,'' she said) but ahead of Democratic Vice President Al 
Gore in polls on a two-party race. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of her support comes from women eager to see one of their  
own make history in the White House or who think Mrs. Dole can 
relate to their hectic lives inside and outside the home. 
</P>
<P>
	In one recent poll, Dole's female supporters outnumbered men  
3-to-2. 
</P>
<P>
	The former American Red Cross president and two-time Cabinet  
secretary, who is often criticized for hewing too tightly to 
prepared texts and exposing little of her personal side, spoke 
expansively in the hourlong interview about the choices forced upon 
women. 
</P>
<P>
	Feminism was wrong in promising women they could have it all,  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most of the women who are involved today in trying to  
be the Super Mom or the Super Executive and all the rest would 
acknowledge that `Yeah, I have had to make some sacrifices. I don't 
have the time I need for all these areas,''' Mrs. Dole said. 
``That's just realism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government dictates -- such as the Family and Medical Leave Act  
or mandatory flextime employment policies -- are not the solution, 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The employee and the employer need to determine what are the  
best interests of that group,'' she said. ``I don't think one size 
fits all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Saying ``my path was a different one,'' Mrs. Dole commended  
women who choose not to work and said society often denies them the 
credit they deserve for raising families. 
</P>
<P>
	As for her own path, Mrs. Dole said she and Bob Dole married  
``late in life,'' when she was 39 and he was 52. ``We felt, 'Great, 
if it happens.' But if it doesn't, there really is a great 
opportunity through the positions that we're in to help a lot of 
children which is very satisfying -- to be able to give back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if she would be where she is today if she'd had children,  
Mrs. Dole replied: 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't speculate on what might have happened had it been a  
different set of circumstance because I've just lived this life and 
it's hard to really put yourself into another situation. But I 
think women are doing a great job today of trying to juggle a lot 
of different areas and I'm very supportive of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said she was blessed to have two nephews and a daughter,  
Robin, from the former senator's first marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole also:  
</P>
<P>
	--Held to her hawkish views amid signs of peace in Yugoslavia and  
said NATO should arrest Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic under 
a war crimes indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you just label him and do nothing about it, it doesn't mean  
anything,'' she said. ``I think he needs to be apprehended and NATO 
is the right force to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Announced that pollster Tony Fabrizio, a veteran of her  
husband's failed campaign, would be her top strategist. 
</P>
<P>
	--Supported a move to raise the maximum individual presidential  
donation from $1,000, saying it takes too much time to raise money 
in such small increments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to say whether she supported limiting the purchase of  
hand guns to one per month and requiring registration of weapons, 
as President Clinton has proposed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
