<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rain Mars Bratislava Track Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRATISLAVA, Slovakia (AP) -- Kenya's Bernhard Barmasai, world  
record-holder in the 3,000-meter steeplechase, led a 1-2-3 Kenyan 
finish at a Grand Prix track and field meet Tuesday marred by 
horrible weather conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Barmasai was timed in 8 minutes, 28.36 seconds. His world record  
is 7:55.72. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenyans also went 1-2 in the 5,000, with Benjamin Limo beating  
Thomas Nyariki in 13:38.15. 
</P>
<P>
	Stormy winds, rain and cold prevented any chances of world-class  
performances. Many athletes withdrew rather than risk injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Gabor Dobos of Hungary won the men's 100 in 10.52 in light rain,  
while Britain's Tony Jarrett ended the meet with a victory in the 
110 hurdles in 13.49 in sleeting rain that forced spectators to 
clear the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	Roland Nemeth gave Hungary a second victory, taking the 200 in  
20.60. 
</P>
<P>
	Denisa Krejcova of the Czech Republic took the women's 200 in  
24.37, and compatriot Helena Fuchsova won the 400 in 52.61. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Redolat of Spain was the only non-Kenyan to win a distance  
race, taking the 1,500 in 3:47.34. 
</P>
<P>
	Praskevi Tsiamita of Greece won the women's triple jump at 48  
feet, 1 1/4 inches. Milan Haborak of Slovakia took the shot put at 
69-7 1/4 and Svetlana Krivelyova of Russia threw 63-9 1/2 to win the 
women's shot put. 
</P>
<P>
	Tatyana Grigoryeva of Russia cleared 13-10 to win the women's  
pole vault. 
</P>
<P>
	Yelena Gulyayva of Russia won the women's high jump at 6-2, her  
concentration broken in her final attempt as the wind kept blowing 
down the bar. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
