<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cop Found Guilty in Torture Case  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A police officer accused of holding down a  
Haitian immigrant while another officer tortured him in a 
stationhouse bathroom was found guilty today while three other 
officers were acquitted of all charges. The anonymous jury of seven 
men and five women reached the verdict after 18 hours of 
deliberations over three days. They heard four weeks of often lurid 
testimony in Brooklyn federal court in the case of Abner Louima. 

</P>
<P>
	Eight Nations Agree on Kosovo Force  
</P>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- The United States, Russia and six other  
nations agree on a U.N. resolution to settle the conflict with 
Yugoslavia and send international troops under NATO command to 
Kosovo. ``We got what we came for,'' Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright proclaimed. British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said 
bombing could be suspended in the next few days if Serb troops 
begin withdrawing from the province. The bombing halt is a 
significant concession to Russia, long a vocal opponent to the 
attacks. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Considers Kosovo Resolution  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Security Council today discussed  
the draft resolution to end the Kosovo conflict, with the United 
States and its NATO partners pushing for quick adoption but China 
saying it has trouble with key points, including the mandate of an 
international criminal tribunal for Yugoslavia. As a permanent 
member of the Security Council, China has veto power over 
resolutions. China had said it would not allow a formal discussion 
of a resolution on Kosovo while NATO planes were bombing 
Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Schumer Traces Guns Used in Crimes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One percent of gun dealers are the source of  
weapons used in nearly half of all crimes, according to a report 
released by Sen. Charles Schumer. The report from the New York 
Democrat found that only a tiny fraction of the nation's 100,000 
federally licensed gun dealers supplied guns used in 45 percent of 
the crimes where the weapon was successfully traced by federal 
officials. Schumer said the report shows that the Bureau of 
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms needs to do more inspections at 
dealerships with track records of providing guns to criminals. 

</P>
<P>
	Group Seeks Ban on Jail Stun Belts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A human rights group that wants electric stun  
belts banned says federal and state prisons are increasingly 
relying on the devices that can deliver 50,000 volts of electricity 
to subdue prisoners. Amnesty International says the U.S. Marshals 
Service, the federal Bureau of Prisons and at least 20 state prison 
systems have authorized use of stun belts, although the extent of 
their use in some of those states isn't clear. The security devices 
are typically strapped onto prisoners for court appearances or 
while they are being transported. The battery-powered belts, 
triggered by a remote control, temporarily incapacitate inmates 
with a painful, eight-second jolt above the left kidney. 

</P>
<P>
	Belgium Defies Food Scandal Demands  
</P>
<P>
	LUXEMBOURG (AP) -- The Belgian government said today most foods  
it banned in a dioxin contamination crisis were safe and would be 
allowed back on store shelves within two days. Belgium claims it 
has proof the contamination was limited to 175,000 pounds of animal 
feed and that many of the tests on suspect farms proved negative. 
The European Union has insisted on the destruction of food products 
from suspect farms, and Belgium has banned sales of domestic 
butter, poultry, eggs, fatty beef and pork, and all byproducts. The 
Belgian food industry association says the crisis has cost the 
country $500 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Mich. Mulls Concert Warning Labels  
</P>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- A Michigan state senator is lobbying for a  
bill that would require parental advisories on tickets, posters and 
other advertising for certain concerts. ``We found that a lot of 
times parents weren't aware of what the lyrics are, lyrics about 
drug abuse, raping and killing,'' State Sen. Dale Shugars said. 
Shugars sponsored the bill after attending a concert given by 
rocker Marilyn Manson. ``He was like Satan,'' the 46-year-old 
Republican said. 

</P>
<P>
	Off-Peak Summer Flights Discounted  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- United Airlines today slashed ticket prices as  
much as 25 percent for off-peak summer travel, a day after warning 
too many empty seats would cause quarterly profits to fall. Delta 
Air Lines, Continental Airlines and Northwest Airlines were among 
the first to match the United promotion on domestic and 
international travel. Consumers who purchase tickets for advance 
travel only on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Saturdays could see as much 
as a 25 percent discount over regularly priced tickets. But tickets 
must be purchased by June 18. 

</P>
<P>
