<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polls: Strong Gun Control Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the House on the verge of a debate over  
gun control, confidential Republican polling suggests overwhelming 
public support for fresh restrictions, including an increase in the 
minimum age for handgun purchases from 18 to 21. 
</P>
<P>
	The polling, conducted last month for the GOP House campaign  
committee, found rock-solid support of roughly 80 percent for 
expanded background checks for handgun purchases, safety locks for 
guns, mandatory prison terms for felons who commit crimes with guns 
and the 21-year age limit for handgun purchasers. 
</P>
<P>
	A copy of the survey was made available to The Associated Press.  
</P>
<P>
	The poll underscores the political crosscurrents at work as the  
GOP leadership prepares for next week's expected debate on the 
House floor. While the public -- and most House Democrats -- favor 
new gun control measures, many Republicans and their traditional 
allies at the National Rifle Association oppose them. 
</P>
<P>
	A Senate-passed measure to require background checks for all  
sales at gun shows would ``impose a cradle-to-grave massive federal 
regulatory scheme on gun owners throughout America -- and that's no 
exaggeration,'' the NRA said in a recent mailing to its membership. 
</P>
<P>
	It called the looming House vote on the issue ``the most  
critical gun vote in over five years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Within the House, jockeying continued. Republicans decided to  
bring the gun control issue directly to the House floor rather than 
to convene the Judiciary Committee next week for a preliminary 
airing. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people don't want to vote repeatedly on guns,'' said  
Rep. Henry Hyde, the chairman of the committee, in a reference to 
the political volatility of the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats countered that Republicans had refused to allow  
immediate votes on the subject two weeks ago, saying at the time 
they wanted the committee to first consider it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It indicates to me once again that the delay ... was to allow  
the NRA to lobby,'' said Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the 
Democratic House leader. He later added that Democrats would 
scrutinize any GOP proposal ``to see if it's a loophole-ridden 
measure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it was  
possible the House would be given the chance to choose among three 
or four competing gun control proposals, and the one that gained 
the most votes would be advanced toward final passage. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to finding strong support for a variety of gun  
control measures, the internal GOP poll also asked whether voters 
would be more likely to support a candidate who is linked to the 
NRA. Fewer than one-third of those who answered said they would be 
more inclined to support such a candidate. More than 45 percent 
said they would be less inclined. 
</P>
<P>
	The outcome of the debate over guns is difficult to predict,  
given the party split within the House. There are 223 Republicans, 
211 Democrats and one independent who customarily votes with 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, two to three dozen Democrats are expected to  
oppose at least some of the proposed new restrictions on guns. Yet 
as many as three or four dozen Republicans may be inclined to 
support amendments that gun control advocates will present. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them, Rep. Marge Roukema of New Jersey, said she believes  
the House should enact ``what the Senate passed, at a minimum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But if the Senate measure is under attack from some quarters,  
the internal GOP polling suggests the public is ready to accept 
even more restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Senate measure requires instant background checks for  
all purchases at gun shows and includes a safety lock provision, it 
does not address the issue of age of eligibility for handgun 
purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	Nor did gun control advocates attempt to win approval for such a  
provision when the measure was in the Senate. Democrats said they 
were undecided about whether to attempt it in the House. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hyde, R-Ill., said he will attempt to win a vote on the  
subject. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue will come to the floor as part of a broader measure  
relating to efforts to combat juvenile crime. In addition, Hyde 
will attempt to force passage of amendments relating to violence 
and youth. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will outlaw the sale to children of extremely explicit  
sexual or violent material and also require record stores to allow 
parents to review on site and on request, prior to purchase, any 
lyrics packaged with CDs,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
