<HEADLINE> Opening of Ali Center Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- The opening of a center honoring Muhammad  
Ali will be pushed back by fund-raising delays, but backers remain 
optimistic that it will be built. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am confident about our ability to raise the money,''  
businessman Larry Townsend said Monday. ``Of course, we are going 
to get it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Townsend, who has worked with Muhammad and Lonnie Ali to build  
the center, declined to say how much has been raised or pledged so 
far. But he acknowledged that fund-raising delays will prevent it 
from opening by January 2001 in the former boxing champion's 
hometown. 
</P>
<P>
	The center will include a museum and an institute promoting good  
sportsmanship. It will also sponsor retreats to help young people 
develop self-esteem. 
  	   	
