<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Torre Switches Yanks' Batting Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- New York Yankees manager Joe Torre dropped  
Chuck Knoblauch from the leadoff spot and moved Paul O'Neill from 
third to fifth on Tuesday in what he hoped was a temporary cure for 
the team's struggling offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Knoblauch, batting .258 and struggling to get on base, was moved  
from first to eighth for the Yankees' game against the Philadelphia 
Phillies. O'Neill, a career .317 hitter as a Yankee who is batting 
.255 this year, was dropped to fifth with Bernie Williams taking 
his place in the third spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wanted to try to change things around,'' Torre said.  
``if we score five, six or seven runs I'm not going to guarantee 
it's going to stay this way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It marked the first time this season after 50 starts that  
Knoblauch was not in the leadoff spot. Tony Tarasco led off against 
Phillies right-hander Curt Schilling. Asked if the changes were 
indefinite, Torre said, ``It's tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The changes came one day after the Yankees suffered a sloppy 6-5  
loss to the Phillies, running their winless streak at Veterans 
Stadium to four. The most glaring error occurred when Knoblauch, 
anticipating a grounds rule double on Derek Jeter's shot down the 
left-field line, slowed down as he approached third and failed to 
score in the sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre said the play had nothing to do with the changes.  
</P>
<P>
	``That would be punishment,'' Torre said, ``and we don't do  
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Torre added, ``Just last night I decided I wanted to do  
something. It was an ugly game, and I figured if I'm ever going to 
do something it's after an ugly game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though the Yankees entered play Tuesday night trailing Boston by  
a half-game in the AL East, they have struggled with the enormous 
pressure of living up to last season's magical 125-win season. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ingredients are here,'' Torre said. ``Nobody loses it  
overnight. I'm confident it will come back. We're a half-game out 
of first place. It's not as ugly or desperate as it may appear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill had batted third in all 53 of his starts this season and  
was a fixture in that spot last season as the Yankees won their 
second World Series championship in three years. He snapped an 
0-for-17 slide Monday night with an RBI single and was 1-for-5. He 
6-for-23 on New York's recent homestand. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we had O'Neill started a few times,'' Torre said.  
``I just sense that he's trying to get too many hits each time 
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre didn't talk with any players about the lineup changes.  
Instead, he simply posted it in the clubhouse. He doesn't 
anticipate any problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope not,'' he said. ``We're not as strong as we should be  
if that's going to be a problem.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
