<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Large Lichtenstein Exhibition Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Roy Lichtenstein, the artist who made comic  
strips into museum-quality paintings, is getting his first big 
sculpture exhibition. And it turns out that a lot of his sculpture 
looks like comic strips, too. 
</P>
<P>
	The Corcoran Gallery of Art is putting on the first  
comprehensive show of about 100 of his carvings, castings, moldings 
and forgings, and 100 of the drawings he made in planning them. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the building stands a 32-foot aluminum ``Brushstroke  
Group'' by Lichtenstein painted black, white blue, yellow and 
green. A similar work, only about 8 feet high, sold for $126,000 at 
a Sotheby's auction in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly half a century ago, Lichtenstein apparently fell in love  
with the tiny, regular dots that can still be seen when looking 
closely at comic strips. They originate in the mechanical process 
used in printing, but Lichtenstein used them as an artistic element 
for the rest of his life. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Corcoran sculptures, the dots appear much enlarged in a  
variety of his work from ``Brushstroke Nude'' that dominates the 
main staircase, to the low-slung BMW 320i sedan that had to be 
dismembered to get through the gallery's entrance. The car won 
first place in its class at Le Mans in 1977 -- for its speed, not 
Lichtenstein's painting on it. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Cowart, curator of the show, told a story that the artist's  
children brought him a bubble gum wrapper and challenged him to do 
a painting as good. The story says the result was his picture of 
Mickey Mouse and Donald Duck now owned by the National Gallery of 
Art, called ``Look Mickey, I've caught a big one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cowart explained that when Lichtenstein and other American  
painters started imitating comics in the early 1960s, they were 
reacting from the fashionable ``abstract expressionism'' that 
produced colorful but unrecognizable images. He ``monumentalized'' 
the new style, Cowart said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roy was the one who was most interested and most successful in  
taking the dot pattern, the line pattern, the design and 
composition pattern and kind of re-engineering (them) into his own 
compositions,'' said Cowart. 
</P>
<P>
	``Roy Lichtenstein, Sculpture and Drawings'' will close Sept.  
30. It comes in part from an exhibit in Mexico that Lichtenstein 
was helping put together when he died in 1997. Admission for adults 
is $6. Students and senior citizens $3. Parts of the exhibit will 
go on to Valencia and La Coruna in Spain. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Remains of Vietnam Vet Coming Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	READING, Mass. (AP) -- Richard Holt was hunkered down in graduate  
school when his older brother took off for Vietnam with Marine 
Fighter Attack Squad 542. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't agree with his brother's decision to enlist, but  
figured they'd have plenty of time to debate it later. He never got 
the chance to say goodbye. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll get that chance this weekend, when the remains of Capt.  
Robert Holt are returned from the jungle where they lay for nearly 
30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Holt was 26 when his fighter plane crashed and exploded during a  
September 1968 bombing mission over the Quang Binh Province of 
Northern Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	Details are incomplete, but the crash was likely caused by enemy  
fire. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash site, now overgrown jungle, was off limits to  
Americans until the early 1990s when Vietnamese officials began 
allowing the recovery of remains. 
</P>
<P>
	Holt's remains were recovered in 1994, and this week the  
Department of Defense said they had been positively identified and 
would be returned to his family. 
</P>
<P>
	He will be laid to rest near his mother's grave in a Reading  
cemetery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was against him being there, which he understood and  
accepted,'' said Richard Holt, 54, of Westchester County, N.Y. ``We 
had gotten closer as we got older, so it was really hard (to lose 
him).'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
