<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Wings Plan To Keep Shanahan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The Detroit Red Wings plan to hold on to forward  
Brendan Shanahan, general manager Ken Holland says. 
</P>
<P>
	Holland said Monday he has no plans to move Shanahan, who is  
entering the final year of his contract, and expects him to be at 
training camp in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had no conversations with any other team or general  
manager and at this point I have no plans to talk to anybody in the 
league regarding Brendan Shanahan,'' Holland told Booth News 
Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings also will offer associate coach Barry Smith a  
one-year contract extension, the Detroit Free Press reported 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shanahan's situation has been questioned after two sub-par  
scoring seasons by his standards. After scoring 47 goals in 
1996-97, he scored 28 during 1997-98 and 31 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	But Shanahan also has high-profile supporters, including Red  
Wings captain Steve Yzerman. Shanahan himself campaigned to remain 
a Red Wing after the season ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Shanahan also could become an unrestricted free agent after next  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings will begin negotiating with Shanahan this summer  
for a possible extension, Holland said. 
</P>
<P>
	With Shanahan staying put, the chances of the Red Wings making a  
major move this summer are slight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like our nucleus, our supporting cast and our depth,''  
Holland said. ``If we can, I'd like to make a move to strengthen 
our team and give our team a different look. I don't know if we can 
make it happen for a number of factors, payroll being one of the 
most important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's offer from Holland is meant to keep him alongside Scotty  
Bowman, who signed on last month for a seventh season as head 
coach. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings' other associate coach, Dave Lewis, interviewed  
last week for the Los Angeles Kings' head coaching position. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
