<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Post-Tony Fallout: 4 Shows Closing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Four Broadway shows that came up mostly  
empty-handed at the 1999 Tony Awards will close this weekend, 
including ``The Civil War,'' an $8 million musical. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Civil War'' ends its run Sunday. The musical by Frank  
Wildhorn, who also wrote the scores for ``Jekyll and Hyde'' and 
``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' will have played 61 performances. A 
national tour is planned, starting in Cincinnati in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Although ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' won two Tonys --  
for performers Kristin Chenoweth and Roger Bart -- it has been 
struggling to find an audience since it opened in February. The 
musical revue based on the Charles Schulz comic strip closes Sunday 
after 150 performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Two also-rans for the best-play prize, ``Not About  
Nightingales'' by Tennessee Williams and ``The Lonesome West'' by 
Martin McDonagh, will fold, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nightingales,'' which won a Tony Award for best set, was  
scheduled to close June 27 after a limited engagement, but its 
producers decided to end the run two weeks early. ``Nightingales'' 
will have played 124 performances. 
</P>
<P>
	The play was written by Williams in 1938 but was never produced  
until last year in London before coming to New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Lonesome West'' was McDonagh's second play on Broadway in  
two years. The first, ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'' was a hit 
last year. ``The Lonesome West,'' the story of two antagonistic 
Irish brothers, ends its run after 55 performances. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other shows will finish their runs at the end of the month.  
``The Sound of Music,'' now starring Richard Chamberlain as Capt. 
Von Trapp, ends its more than year-long run June 27. Chamberlain 
takes the show on the road in August, starting in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Also shutting June 27 is ``Night Must Fall,'' a revival of the  
1930s thriller starring Matthew Broderick. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
