<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Bombs Targets Near Belgrade  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO hit targets near the Yugoslav  
capital of Belgrade for the first time in days today, keeping its 
pledge to intensify attacks until President Slobodan Milosevic 
orders his troops out of Kosovo. Fire and dense smoke could be seen 
rising above Pancevo, 12 miles northeast of Belgrade, and 
explosions could be heard from the direction of nearby Batajnica 
military airfield. In addition, one person was killed and five 
wounded in NATO attacks on Novi Sad, the country's second-largest 
city, Serb media reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Prays for Peace in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	ELK, Poland (AP) -- Bathed in golden light from a setting sun,  
Pope John Paul II issued a powerful plea for world peace and spoke 
of innocent blood being shed in Kosovo. His prayer yesterday 
evening in the northern city of Torun was the first time the 
pontiff has mentioned Kosovo since beginning a 13-day pilgrimage to 
his native Poland on Saturday. It came at the final event of a 
hectic day that saw him consecrate the nation's largest church and 
praise the scientific achievements of Nicholas Copernicus -- praise 
that came nearly four centuries after the Vatican condemned the 
astronomer's discovery that the earth revolved around the sun. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Said Seeks Medicare Change  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- President Clinton plans this month to propose  
changing the Medicare program to offer prescription drug coverage 
to all beneficiaries, The New York Times reported today. Clinton 
will contend that such coverage could save the government money by 
reducing the need for hospital stays and nursing home care, The 
Times said, citing unnamed administration officials. The President 
plans to unveil details of his plan later this month, as an 
alternative to a plan proposed in March by an advisory commission, 
The Times said. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia Takes Part in 'Free' Vote  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A reform party that former President  
Suharto once tried to sideline took an early lead today in 
Indonesia's historic elections. The country basked in praise from 
abroad and more good news about its battered economy. More than a 
year after deadly pro-democracy protests ended Suharto's 32-year 
authoritarian rule, this ethnically diverse archipelago of 210 
million people held its freest election in 44 years in remarkable 
peace yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Death Penalty Sought for Ocalan  
</P>
<P>
	IMRALI ISLAND, Turkey (AP) -- Turkish prosecutors demanded the  
death sentence today for Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan in 
closing arguments at his treason trial. Ignoring a warning by 
Kurdish rebels -- who have threatened to intensify their war for 
autonomy if Ocalan is given a death sentence -- the prosecutors said 
the rebel leader should hang for leading a 15-year war for autonomy 
that has killed 37,000 people. The court then adjourned for 15 days 
to give Ocalan's lawyers time to prepare for his final defense. The 
lawyers had said they would ask for a month-long recess to read 
through the 16,000 pages of evidence against him. 

</P>
<P>
	India Offers To Hold Peace Talks  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- India offered today to hold high-level peace  
talks with Pakistan this weekend, a move that came even as its 
warplanes and troops struck against the hundreds of fighters India 
says Pakistan has sent into the mountains of Kashmir. A Foreign 
Ministry statement said Pakistan's foreign minister would be 
welcome on Saturday, countering a proposal by Islamabad for Sartaj 
Aziz to come to New Delhi yesterday, which India called 
``inconvenient.'' There was no immediate response from Pakistan. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Finish Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks finished higher today in thin  
trading ahead of the release of a key economic indicator later this 
week. The Nikkei gained 87.03 points to close at 16,562.92. 

</P>
<P>
	Mariners 4, Rockies 2  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Rookie John Halama pitched into the eighth inning  
and got his first major league hit as the Seattle Mariners beat the 
Colorado Rockies 4-2 last night. Butch Huskey and Alex Rodriguez 
each had two hits and combined for three RBIs, but Ken Griffey Jr. 
was 0-for-5 with two strikeouts in his first appearance at Coors 
Field since winning the home run derby before last year's All-Star 
game. 

</P>
<P>
	Cardinals 7, Royals 5  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Shawon Dunston, filling in because Mark  
McGwire sat out with a sore back, hit a two-run homer as the St. 
Louis Cardinals beat Kansas City 7-5 last night and sent the Royals 
to their ninth straight loss. Kansas City is on the longest losing 
streak in the major leagues this season and the longest for the 
Royals since a nine-game skid from April 15-25, 1992. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
