<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 14:30:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tony Awards Falter in TV Ratings / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rosie O'Donnell stayed away from the Tony Awards  
this year -- and so did most television viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratings for Broadway's annual awards show plummeted this year  
after a two-year revival attributed to O'Donnell's stint as host, 
Nielsen Media Research said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday night's show, which had no host, drew an estimated 9.15  
million viewers. That was the second smallest audience since the 
show began being telecast in 1974. Only the 1996 show, one year 
before O'Donnell took over, was smaller at 8.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, the Tony Awards drew 12.9 million viewers in 1997.  
O'Donnell stayed away this year, saying she had other obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	The awards tied for 31st place in Nielsen's prime-time ratings,  
even though it was the week broadcast networks began their long 
summer slumber. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC was the week's champ with a 7.2 rating and 13 share, and  
also managed a comfortable victory in the 18-49 demographic it 
chases. CBS was second with a 6.8 rating and 13 share, ABC had a 
5.9 rating and 11 share, and Fox was at 4.8 and 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Those top four networks had 34.3 million people watching during  
an average minute of prime-time broadcasting last week, a sharp 
drop from the season average of 47.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the emerging networks, the WB had a 2.3 rating and 4  
share, UPN had a 1.6 rating and 3 share and Pax TV had a 0.8 rating 
and 1 share. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ``Nightly News'' won the evening news competition with a  
7.0 rating and 17 share. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' had a 6.7 
rating and 16 share, and the ``CBS Evening News was at 5.8 and 14. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 994,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 99.4 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of May 31-June 6, the top 10 shows, their networks  
and ratings were: ``Frasier,'' NBC, 10.2; ``ER,'' NBC, 10.1; 
``Friends,'' NBC, 10.0; ``20/20-Wednesday,'' ABC, 9.9; ``60 
Minutes,'' CBS, 9.9; ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC, 9.8; ``Touched By an 
Angel,'' CBS, 9.6; ``Dateline NBC-Tuesday,'' NBC, 9.4; ``Law &AMP; 
Order,'' NBC, 9.2; ``20/20-Friday,'' ABC, 8.9. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 08:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Likes Idea of Senate Spouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The thought of President Clinton socializing  
with the other Senate spouses at a luncheon affair? 
</P>
<P>
	Another check in the ``plus'' column for the first lady  
pondering a New York Senate run. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are many reasons to do or not do something,'' Mrs.  
Clinton said Monday night at a Democratic fund-raising event. 
``That kind of goes on the list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Imagining the president at events for Senate spouses ``just  
brings an enormous smile to my face,'' she admitted. Mrs. Clinton 
announced last week that she plans to form an exploratory committee 
for the race. 
</P>
<P>
	And the president says he doesn't think it's such a bad deal --  
maybe even better than being in the Senate itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``No offense Senator Daschle, but until you change the numbers  
up there, if I were given the choice I'd rather be in the spouses 
club,'' Clinton quipped to the Senate minority leader, also on hand 
at the event which brought in more than $3 million for the 
Democratic National Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to it,'' the president added.  
</P>
<P>
	The dinner honoring fund-raiser Terence McAuliffe was held at  
the spacious Washington home of party activist Beth Dozoretz. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also got a sampling of what life might be like as the  
spouse rather than the president, when former Texas Gov. Ann 
Richards welcomed her friend Mrs. Clinton ``the next junior senator 
from New York ... and of course, her lovely husband Bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked today if he could settle for being just a political  
spouse, Clinton answered with a hearty ``absolutely!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then, he added: ``That won't be my only role, but I'll be happy  
if she's doing what she wants. I'm gonna run my library.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
