<DOCNO> APW19990608.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Schumer Traces Guns Used in Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A tiny fraction of the nation's gun dealers  
provide the weapons used in almost half of all crimes and have done 
so for years, says a lawmaker who strongly supports gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	A report by the staff of Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., used  
statistics from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms to show 
that 1 percent of the nation's 100,000 federally licensed gun 
dealers supplied weapons used in 45 percent of the crimes in which 
the gun was traced by federal officials. The report listed 137 of 
the ``worst'' dealers, which had each sold more than 50 guns used 
in crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This cries out for an explanation,'' Schumer said. ``Most gun  
dealers are law abiding citizens. But a few bad apples appear to be 
spoiling the bunch and it's them we have to go after.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schumer said he will introduce legislation this week to allow  
unlimited ATF inspections at dealers found to have supplied more 
than 10 guns traced to a crime in any given year. Currently, the 
ATF can inspect gun dealers only once a year unless they have a 
warrant. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited 1998 statistics that found 1,160 gun stores that would  
be subject to increased inspections. Those problem gun dealers 
could have their licenses suspended or revoked if they failed to 
meet enhanced reporting guidelines, under Schumer's bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Rifle Association accused Schumer of juggling the  
numbers to make a political point. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every universe of data is subject to manipulation,'' the NRA's  
chief lobbyist, Jim Baker, said. ``I would believe the staff of 
Senator Schumer would be able to come up with the conclusion they 
wanted in the first place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He called Schumer's proposed legislation unneeded because the  
ATF already has the right to go after rogue dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	The ATF did not dispute or endorse the report.  
</P>
<P>
	ATF spokesman Jeff Roehm said Tuesday it was quite possible that  
in some cases dealers listed in Schumer's ``137 worst'' list sold a 
high volume of guns, skewing the results. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that a gun store sells a gun that is at some point  
later on used in a crime is not a definitive indicator of criminal 
activity,'' Roehm said. ``It's certainly a red flag we need to look 
at. But the sale could be perfectly legal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 percent of guns recovered from crimes scenes can be  
traced by federal officials, Roehm said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumer, who authored the Brady law while in the House,  
predicted the report would be used in lawsuits filed by 20 
municipalities against gun manufacturers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 13:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Education Land Grant Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cash-strapped school districts, particularly  
in the West, could buy small parcels of Forest Service land at 
minimal cost for educational purposes under a bill the House passed 
Tuesday without dissent. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted 420-0 for the measure, which advanced to the  
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration says it favors making such lands  
available but opposes the bill because the land would be sold for 
less than fair market price. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. James Hansen, R-Utah, said he understood the concerns but  
suggested the administration take note of who would benefit under 
the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking about schoolchildren. We're talking about giving  
school districts a little land to build an elementary school or a 
playground for the children,'' Hansen said. ``This is a good cause 
and a very good idea.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, school districts could apply for up to 80 acres  
of land. Before transferring the land, the agriculture secretary 
must determine that it will be used for a public elementary or 
secondary school, will serve the public interest and is not 
otherwise needed for National Forest System. 
</P>
<P>
	Districts would pay $10 per acre. Mineral rights would not be  
included in any transfer, and title to the land would revert to the 
government if a district tries to transfer the land or use it for 
purposes other than education. 
</P>
<P>
	School districts in the West face several problems in purchasing  
land, said Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., the bill's sponsor. Many 
towns are surrounded by federal land, which drives up the price of 
private land. Private land also is in great demand because of rapid 
population growth throughout the region, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, only school districts near land supervised by the  
Bureau of Land Management in the Interior Department can apply for 
such transfers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 150.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 03:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Death in Venice' Is No. 1 Gay Novel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Add another voice to the chorus of literary  
lists. 
</P>
<P>
	An organization of gays and lesbians in publishing has compiled  
its picks for the 100 greatest novels of all time. ``Death in 
Venice,'' Thomas Mann's short novel about a writer's infatuation 
with a teen-age boy, was voted No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an obvious response to the Modern Library's list. That  
list got me thinking about what novels by gays and lesbians were 
overlooked,'' said Charles Flowers, chair of the Publishing 
Triangle, which consists of more than 250 gay and lesbian writers, 
editors, agents and publishers. 
</P>
<P>
	Announced last summer, the Modern Library's choices for the  
century's best English-language novels were widely ridiculed as a 
stodgy compilation of white, male fiction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Publishing Triangle's list is more diverse. It covers the  
best gay novels ever, not just for the century. There are far more 
women and nonwhites and all languages were eligible. 
</P>
<P>
	But if the Modern Library, a division of Random House, could be  
faulted for disregarding alternative voices, the current list could 
be cited for excessive loyalty to those voices. 
</P>
<P>
	Few critics would call James Baldwin's ``Giovanni's Room'' (No.  
2) a better novel than Marcel Proust's ``Remembrance of Things 
Past'' (No. 4) or rank Patricia Highsmith's ``The Price of Salt'' 
(No. 36) above ``The Turn of the Screw'' by Henry James (No. 40) 
and Louisa May Alcott's ``Little Women.'' (No. 43). 
</P>
<P>
	``Many elements went into the voting,'' Flowers said. ``Social  
influence. Cultural influence. Literary quality. I don't believe 
there's a single objective standard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the question of what is a ``gay'' novel. Does the  
writer have to be gay? Should the subject matter be gay? Is it 
enough that the book is open to a gay interpretation? You could 
find all kinds on the Publishing Triangle list. 
</P>
<P>
	Judges disagreed, for instance, over the inclusion of  
``Moby-Dick.'' Some said the book didn't belong because it has no 
gay relationships and that Herman Melville wasn't trying to suggest 
any. Others found the novel inspiring. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each of these books contributes to the understanding of the  
outsider mentality,'' said Dorothy Allison, author of the acclaimed 
novel ``Bastard Out of Carolina'' and other books. ``'Moby-Dick' is 
very much about the survival of the different. And that's pretty 
much the situation for gay and lesbian people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You could say that about a leper colony, too,'' responded  
fellow judge M.E. Kerr, a novelist. ``You have to consider the 
writer's intention. If you're supposed to choose a gay novel, I 
should think that it's not just because it has a group of men or 
women interacting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others on the 14-member judging committee included science  
fiction writer Samuel Delany and Anthony Heilbut, author of a 
prize-winning biography on Mann. 
</P>
<P>
	With both the century and the millennium nearing the end, there  
is competition within the literary world to define its history. 
(And, of course, to sell some books). 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past year, the Modern Library released its choices for  
the century's best fiction and nonfiction and publishing students 
at Radcliffe College, most of them women, also compiled a fiction 
list. 
</P>
<P>
	``Such lists are basically a kind of game people play,'' Delany  
said. ``If people take them too seriously it's not a good thing. 
But they inspire people to think. And they inspire people to make 
their own lists'' 
</P>
<P>
	The list was released in conjunction with National Lesbian and  
Gay Book Month, started eight years ago by the Publishing Triangle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:26:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mexico Outraged at TV Star's Slaying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The death of a television star in a fusillade  
of bullets has galvanized popular outrage over crime in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	The motive for the slaying of Francisco ``Paco'' Stanley  
remained a mystery on Tuesday, and its professional style made it 
untypical of murders in the Mexican capital, where taxicab 
kidnappings, armed robberies and carjackings have long terrorized 
citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	But the fame of the victim and the brazenness of the noontime  
attack shocked many Mexicans, and prompted some to use it to attack 
the city's opposition party mayor, a candidate for president. 
</P>
<P>
	``With so much violence in the city, the government has ignored  
us. Anybody can carry a weapon in his hand just as he'd carry a 
cell phone,'' said Claudia Flores, one of thousands of people who 
lined up outside a funeral home Tuesday to file past Stanley's 
coffin. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody protects us. We are alone,'' she said. Many in line  
sobbed as they talked among themselves about their memories of the 
comedian. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley was a sort of morning-show cross between Rosie O'Donnell  
and Ed Sullivan, a wisecracking host offering musical acts and 
silly skits. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I woke up pessimistic, he would tell one of his jokes,  
which were stupid but graceful,'' said Carmen Dolores Duran, 74, a 
retired school principal, clutching a rose against her gray suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the memorial, thousands more gathered at Mexico City's  
Spanish Cemetery for the burial. Many clambered atop family tomb 
chapels to shower flowers upon the hearse carrying Stanley's body 
as it eased through the chaotic crowd. Some chanted ``Justice! 
Justice!'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 24 hours of developments since Stanley's death were  
covered almost non-stop on Mexico's two main television networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said a gunman with a .40-caliber automatic weapon fired  
26 shots into Stanley's black Lincoln Navigator at noon Monday in 
front of El Charco De Las Ranas, one of the capital's most famous 
restaurants alongside its busiest freeway, the Periferico. 
</P>
<P>
	An insurance agent standing nearby also was killed and three  
people were hospitalized with gunshot wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, whose 1997 election victory came on a  
wave of outrage at soaring crime in the city, quickly came under 
attack -- turning the slaying into a possible political issue ahead 
of Cardenas' likely run for the presidency in July 2000 on the 
opposition Democratic Revolution Party ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although the government of Cardenas camouflages the statistics  
of the fight against crime ... Paco's death is one more example 
against what the authorities say,'' Congressman Jorge Galvan of the 
National Action Party told the daily El Heraldo de Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``The responsibility is that of Cuauhtemoc Cardenas,'' charged  
Jorge Garralda, a newscaster on the TV Azteca network where Stanley 
worked. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody should resign and make way for people who are capable  
of protecting us,'' Mexico's best-known newscaster, Jacobo 
Zabludovsky, said on the rival Televisa network. 
</P>
<P>
	A prominent anti-crime lobbying group, Mexico United Against  
Crime, announced plans for a demonstration on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardenas claims that his administration has reduced the wave of  
armed robberies, carjackings, thefts and kidnappings that have 
soared in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	But figures are untrustworthy. Officials admit that many crimes  
are not reported due to lack of faith in authorities, and those 
victims who do report crimes sometimes find they are not treated 
seriously: an attempted kidnapping, for example, is classified as a 
lost document. 
</P>
<P>
	Cardenas at first seemed to minimize the Stanley killing, saying  
it ``is one more case and it will be investigated as one more case. 
... The city is well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But as public outrage grew -- and more fingers were pointed his  
way -- his tone changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no such thing as a 'common crime,''' Cardenas said in  
a paid statement placed in Tuesday newspapers, vowing ``our most 
urgent priority'' to solve the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	He accused ``some news media'' of ``an act of great  
irresponsibility'' in blaming his government for the crime and 
insisted that the federal government -- run by the Institutional 
Revolutionary Party -- also is responsible for fighting crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley's show was not politically controversial and the motive  
for his slaying remained a mystery Tuesday. But that didn't stop 
the speculation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The style of the execution of Paco Stanley is that of a  
settling of accounts among drug-trafficking mafias,'' the newspaper 
Excelsior noted in a Page 1 editorial. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper Reforma said government intelligence reports  
earlier had linked Stanley to drug traffickers, but the city 
attorney general's office would not comment on the allegation. 
</P>
<P>
	At first officials suggested it might have been a bungled  
kidnapping attempt, but that theory soon disappeared as the 
investigation made clear it was a deliberate assassination. 
</P>
<P>
	Police on Monday detained at least two people whose car matched  
the description of that seen by witnesses. But they said Tuesday 
that none of the witnesses could identify the two and they were 
released. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:26:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
