<P>
	But as public outrage grew -- and more fingers were pointed his  
way -- his tone changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no such thing as a 'common crime,''' Cardenas said in  
a paid statement placed in Tuesday newspapers, vowing ``our most 
urgent priority'' to solve the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	He accused ``some news media'' of ``an act of great  
irresponsibility'' in blaming his government for the crime and 
insisted that the federal government -- run by the Institutional 
Revolutionary Party -- also is responsible for fighting crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanley's show was not politically controversial and the motive  
for his slaying remained a mystery Tuesday. But that didn't stop 
the speculation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The style of the execution of Paco Stanley is that of a  
settling of accounts among drug-trafficking mafias,'' the newspaper 
Excelsior noted in a Page 1 editorial. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper Reforma said government intelligence reports  
earlier had linked Stanley to drug traffickers, but the city 
attorney general's office would not comment on the allegation. 
</P>
<P>
	At first officials suggested it might have been a bungled  
kidnapping attempt, but that theory soon disappeared as the 
investigation made clear it was a deliberate assassination. 
</P>
<P>
	Police on Monday detained at least two people whose car matched  
the description of that seen by witnesses. But they said Tuesday 
that none of the witnesses could identify the two and they were 
released. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
