<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Ottawa GM Goes to Tampa Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Former Ottawa general manager Rick Dudley  
will oversee the rebuilding of the Tampa Bay Lightning -- the NHL's 
worst team the past two seasons -- as Palace Sports and 
Entertainment's vice president of hockey operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a whole new day. We are here to win ... make  
no mistake about it,'' Tom Wilson, Palace Sports and Entertainment 
president, said Tuesday in announcing Dudley's hiring. ``One of the 
key parts to that is to bring in somebody who will provide the 
overall direction for the hockey operation and that is Rick 
Dudley.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palace Sports, whose holdings include the NBA's Detroit Pistons  
and the Palace of Auburn Hills, is expected to complete its 
reported $100 million deal to purchase the struggling franchise 
from Art Williams within the next several weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley spent four years as general manager for the Detroit  
Vipers of the International Hockey League -- owned by Palace Sports 
-- before being named general manager of the Ottawa Senators on June 
30, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Ottawa had 103 points and the NHL's third-best record during  
Dudley's only season as general manager. He was released from the 
final two years of his contract Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There wasn't any reservation,'' Dudley said. ``It was a  
wonderful experience being in Ottawa. It was very difficult (to 
leave) because it was the best group of people that I've ever 
worked with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senators will receive undisclosed compensation from Tampa  
Bay for signing Dudley. The status of current coach-general manager 
Jacques Demers should be determined within the next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley did not completely rule out Demers returning in both  
roles, but said handling the dual responsibility is very difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we're looking to make major changes. The ideal  
situation would be all the people here would remain here,'' Dudley 
said. ``Obviously there's some evaluating to go on. I just want to 
get the right mix of people pointed in the same direction and go 
from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley and Demers met for about 30 minutes Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``We'll sit down and see what's best for the franchise and what  
Rick is going to be comfortable with ... where does he want Jacques 
Demers to be,'' Demers said. ``I've never felt not unwanted by this 
organization. We'll have to wait and see what happens.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
