<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. Mulls Concert Warning Labels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- State Sen. Dale Shugars wasn't satisfied  
simply to hear about the antics of shock rockers like Marilyn 
Manson. He had to see them for himself. 
</P>
<P>
	So in April, Shugars headed off to a Manson concert in Grand  
Rapids, taking along two bodyguards. He was marveling at the light 
show when Manson appeared, strapped to a cross and wearing a black 
G-string. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was like Satan,'' said Shugars, a 46-year-old Republican  
whose own musical tastes run toward the Beach Boys. 
</P>
<P>
	The experience prompted Shugars to lobby even harder for a bill  
he sponsored that would require parental advisories on tickets, 
posters and other advertising for certain concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure passed the state Senate last month and is now before  
a House committee. If it passes the full House, it will be the 
first law of its kind in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``We found that a lot of times parents weren't aware of what the  
lyrics are, lyrics about drug abuse, raping and killing,'' Shugars 
said. ``Does this guarantee that parents won't let their kids go to 
these concerts? No. But it does guarantee a red flag.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those fighting the bill claim that red flag is useless at best  
and unconstitutional at worst. 
</P>
<P>
	The group that got parental warning labels put on albums, the  
Recording Industry Association of America, opposes the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a draconian measure that we feel could undermine a  
program that's working,'' said Joel Flatow, RIAA vice president of 
government affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, concert promoters or venue operators would have  
to put warning labels on tickets, posters or advertisements for any 
artist who has put out an album with a parental advisory label in 
the past five years. Record companies voluntarily place the 
warnings on their albums as part of the RIAA program, which began 
in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would let promoters or venues choose to put the label  
on only one form of advertisement -- for example, only the concert 
posters or only the tickets. If they fail to put the warning on any 
of their promotional materials, they could be fined up to $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Ticketmaster, the ticket-sales giant, opposes the law as  
cumbersome, while Detroit entertainment attorney Mike Novak called 
the bill a waste of time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many bands will seek out this kind of labeling to make them  
more appealing to certain audiences,'' Novak said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathan Wey, a 17-year-old Manson fan from East Lansing, said  
Manson's lyrics are misinterpreted. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of these bands that they're trying to target aren't  
really that violent at all,'' he said. ``Marilyn Manson is opposed 
to violence. I think the whole point of his music is trying to be 
yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shugars said he doesn't buy the argument that music doesn't  
affect behavior: ``If we do know that Frank Sinatra makes you feel 
romantic, then this music will make you feel violent.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
