<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole: Milosevic Should Be Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate Elizabeth  
Dole said today that NATO troops should arrest President Slobodan 
Milosevic to face his international indictment on war crimes. ``The 
next person who talks to him should be the one who arrests him,'' 
she said, taking a hard line on bringing the Yugoslav leader to 
trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The Associated Press, Mrs. Dole said her  
husband, the 1996 GOP presidential nominee, has a growing role in 
her presidential bid. After deciding to ``go solo'' early in the 
campaign, Mrs. Dole is asking the former Senate majority leader to 
help raise badly needed money. 
</P>
<P>
	``He never did it for himself. He just doesn't want to ask  
anybody for money. But you want to know something? He's doing it 
for me,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``He's on the phone asking for money and 
he's also going to be doing some fund-raisers between now and the 
end of the month.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If there were a Dole administration, she said Bob Dole would  
bring respect and experience to the White House and would be 
particularly suited to handle agriculture issues. But there will be 
no Cabinet post, no ``two for the price of one'' that supporters of 
Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton promised in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to be a co-presidency,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole, 62, who plans to formally announce her candidacy in  
the late summer or fall, is trying to become the first American 
woman to win a major party nomination. The former American Red 
Cross president and two-time Cabinet secretary ranks second in GOP 
polls, well behind front-runner George W. Bush but ahead of 
Democratic hopeful Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of her support comes from women eager to see a female  
succeed in politics or who think Mrs. Dole can relate to their 
hectic lives inside and outside the home. 
</P>
<P>
	In one recent poll, Dole's female supporters outnumbered men  
3-to-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most of the women who are involved today in trying to  
be the supermom or the super-executive and all the rest would 
acknowledge that `Yeah, I have had to make some sacrifices. I don't 
have the time I need for all these areas,''' Mrs. Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	But she does does not think the government programs -- such as  
the Family and Medical Leave Act -- are the solution. 
</P>
<P>
	``Women make different choices. There's not one mold for  
everyone,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying ``my path was a different one,'' Mrs. Dole commended  
women who choose not to work. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those who decide to stay at home and raise a family of  
outstanding future citizens ... I want those women to be honored, 
too,'' she said. ``We don't give them credit as a society the way 
we really should. I want them to feel like they've got a choice. 
That that's just fine to do that. '' 
</P>
<P>
	She and her husband didn't have children so they dedicated  
themselves to public service, Mrs. Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also:  
</P>
<P>
	--Announced that pollster Tony Fabrizio would be her top  
strategist, replacing Kieran Mahoney who departed in an early staff 
shakeup. 
</P>
<P>
	--Defended her record at the Red Cross, which has been the  
subject of a critical review by the KPMG Peat Marwick auditing 
firm. ``It is really one of the most far reaching contributions 
that I have had the opportunity to make in 30 plus years of service 
to the public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Supported a move to raise the maximum individual presidential  
donation from $1,000, saying it takes too much time to raise money 
in such small increments. 
</P>
<P>
	--Said her husband was never really ``in the woodshed'' -- a  
phrase she coined after Dole raised questions about her campaign 
and suggested that he might donate money to an old friend from the 
Senate, presidential candidate John McCain of Arizona. ``Humor was 
the best way to handle that because the interpretation was so 
totally different than what he intended.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Refused to expand her gun control positions, declining to say  
whether she supported limiting the purchase of hand guns to one per 
month and requiring registration of the weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Her Yugoslavia remarks came as the United States, Russia and six  
other nations agreed on a draft U.N. resolution that could settle 
the conflict over Kosovo. And the Pentagon announced signs that 
Serb forces were preparing to withdraw from the Yugoslav province. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole, who visited refugee camps early in the crisis, said,  
``I hope this agreement will go through. I hope that the people of 
Serbia would want to honor this agreement if indeed (Milosevic) is 
no longer there but I can't speak to what happens next.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I frankly have found it difficult to consider how you  
negotiate with a war criminal,'' she said. Milosevic was indicted 
by a U.N. tribunal on May 27. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you just label him and do nothing about it, it doesn't mean  
anything. I think he needs to be apprehended and NATO is the right 
force to do it,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole and McCain have been alone in the GOP fold advocating the  
toughest action against Milosevic, giving both their campaigns much 
needed attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole and spokesman Ari Fleischer said later that she wasn't  
implying that a massive NATO force sweep into Belgrade. Fleischer 
said there is historic precedent for a small, specially trained 
commandoes apprehending war criminals and terrorists. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
