<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Sends Workers Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Much of the East baked in a second day of  
August-like heat today, with states sending workers home early and 
utilities warning they might not be able to keep air conditioners 
running. 
</P>
<P>
	The thermometer registered a record-tying 97 by early afternoon  
at Newark, N.J., and a record-breaking 96 at Raleigh-Durham, N.C. 
Washington sizzled at 98, and Philadelphia quickly reached a record 
95. It also was 95 in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hot,'' said Yeshu Woldemichael, who sells drinks and  
snacks at a stand in downtown Washington. ``I drank all of my 
profit today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even in usually temperate New Hampshire, air conditioners were  
sold out. A Sears in Concord, N.H., ran out, and customers stood in 
the aisles waiting for the next truck delivery until they were told 
it was delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	Because this heat wave came so early in June -- two weeks before  
the start of summer -- some time-honored methods of cooling off 
didn't work. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of Philadelphia teen-agers hoped to cool off in a Center  
City fountain, but the city hadn't turned it on yet. They ran 
through a nearby flower bed sprinkler. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went through three times. It was fun. But the last time it  
burned my eyes, because it has plant food in it,'' said Joe Werner, 
15. 
</P>
<P>
	Demand for electricity was so high that the company that  
oversees the New England power grid asked all six of the region's 
governors to send nonessential employees home so their lights, 
computers and air conditioners could be turned off. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the red ``Exit'' signs were left turned on in corridors of  
the New Hampshire Statehouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The request was necessary to avoid two-hour rolling blackouts,  
said Jim Sinclair, spokesman for ISO New England, the corporation 
responsible for bulk power transmission in New England. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools closed early around Virginia because many buildings have  
no air conditioning. The elderly were given free fans. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the city housing authority opened fire hydrants  
to provide gushing street showers at 10 housing projects. 
</P>
<P>
	Relief from the heat, haze and humidity was expected to arrive  
by Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	While antiperspirants failed in the East, people in the West  
reached for their blankets. 
</P>
<P>
	Eureka, Calif., dipped to a low of 40, only the third time it's  
been that chilly there in June since 1887. And Klamath Falls, Ore., 
chilled to a record 25 degrees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wash. Paper Sold to Indiana Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONGVIEW, Wash. (AP) -- The Daily News of Longview, Wash., has  
been sold to a privately held newspaper group based in Indiana, 
ending 76 years of ownership by the McClelland-Natt family. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale to Howard Publications Inc., originally expected to  
close in January, also included three local weekly newspapers owned 
by Westmedia Corp., the parent organization of The Daily News. 
Terms of the sale were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	With the purchase, Howard now owns 16 small- to medium-sized  
dailies, although mostly in the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Daily News publisher Ted Natt other family members had owned 69  
percent of Westmedia, with employees owning the remaining 31 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard may start a Sunday edition of the Daily News and will  
consider switching it to a morning publication, said Bill Howard, 
vice president of newspapers for Howard and publisher of a Howard 
paper in Munster, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard said it was not certain what will happen to the three  
weeklies -- the Columbia County Review, Lewis River News and Kalama 
Bulletin and Cowlitz County Advocate. 
</P>
<P>
	The new publisher of the Daily News will be Peter York, 49, a  
native of Portland, Ore., who has been advertising director for the 
Howard-owned Twin Falls Times-News in Idaho for the past 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, Ted Natt will continue to write Views of the News, a  
front-page commentary, for the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
