<HEADLINE> Cable &AMP; Wireless Set To Win Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC came closer to acquiring a  
controlling stake in a major Japanese telecommunications company 
after Toyota Motor Corp. said Thursday it would sell its shares to 
the London-based firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's Nippon Telegraph &AMP; Telephone Corp., which had also been  
bidding for a stake in Tokyo-based International Digital 
Communications Inc., has reportedly given up hope of outbidding 
Cable &AMP; Wireless. 
</P>
<P>
	NTT said in a press release Tuesday it has told Toyota and  
another major IDC shareholder, Itochu Corp., about its decision to 
stand firm on its offer, citing time constraints. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Toyota indicated its willingness to sell its 17.7  
percent stake in IDC to Cable &AMP; Wireless unless NTT, Japan's 
largest telecommunications company, raised its offer price again. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota decided to accept Cable &AMP; Wireless' offer to pay $929 per  
share for IDC shares owned by Toyota -- valued at roughly $101 
million -- after NTT failed to make a new bid, said Toyota 
spokeswoman Hino Yamada. 
</P>
<P>
	Itochu, which also holds a 17.7 percent stake, said it would  
make a decision on Cable &AMP; Wireless' offer on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless also currently holds a 17.7 percent stake in  
IDC, one of Japan's largest international phone companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese media reports have said IDC executives had viewed Cable  
&AMP; Wireless' unsolicited takeover bid as hostile, raising the 
possibility they might try to resist. 
</P>
<P>
	But headlines in major newspapers Wednesday said the British  
company may now have won out. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
