<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cable &AMP; Wireless Win IDC Bid War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC won a bidding war for a major  
Japanese telecommunications company Wednesday after two leading 
shareholders said they would sell their shares to the London-based 
firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless' acquisition of shares in Tokyo-based  
International Digital Communications Inc. will make it the first 
foreign company to own a controlling stake in a Japanese 
telecommunications firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese telecommunications giant Nippon Telegraph &AMP; Telephone  
Corp., which had also been bidding for a stake in IDC, gave up hope 
of outbidding Cable &AMP; Wireless. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota Motor Corp. and Itochu Corp., which each own 17.7 percent  
of IDC, announced Wednesday they would accept Cable &AMP; Wireless' 
offer to pay $929 per share, or about $101 million, for their stake 
after NTT failed to make a new bid. 
</P>
<P>
	NTT said in a press release Tuesday it had told Toyota and  
Itochu it was going to stand firm on its offer of $916 a share, 
citing time constraints. 
</P>
<P>
	Itochu spokesman Yoshiharu Matsumoto said his company's decision  
was based on economic considerations stemming from the value of 
Cable &AMP; Wireless' offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless' bids places IDC's value at about $580 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Cable &AMP; Wireless, which also holds a 17.7 percent stake in IDC,  
is one of Japan's largest international phone companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese media reports had said IDC executives had viewed Cable  
&AMP; Wireless' unsolicited takeover bid as hostile, raising the 
possibility they might try to resist. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
