<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marino Likely To Sign Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Dan Marino will likely sign a two-year contract  
extension with the Miami Dolphins before the week is out, his agent 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say it's probable,'' Marvin Demoff told The Miami  
Herald on Tuesday. ``I'd like to get it done. ... I'm going on 
vacation for two weeks next week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The long-discussed deal is likely to include a signing bonus of  
about $6.4 million and is meant to create salary cap space for the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino's contract, which is entering its final season, calls for  
a cap value of a little more than $7.14 million. Because of NFL 
rules limiting the amount the Dolphins can decrease Marino's 
contract, the team must give Marino a signing bonus of $6.4 million 
or offer other guarantees that he'll receive that amount when he 
signs the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Wiedmeier, the team's vice president of administration who  
is negotiating the deal, declined to comment Tuesday. Dolphins 
coach Jimmy Johnson and director of football operations Bob Ackles 
are both on vacation and could not be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino, who will turn 38 in September, has said he would like to  
play until he's at least 40. He said in April he expected to sign 
the deal soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been talking about it for months, and everybody knows  
about it,'' Demoff said. ``Dan isn't going anywhere else.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
