<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO, Yugoslav Generals Meet  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes attacked targets  
across Serbia in a warning to President Slobodan Milosevic to 
implement a Kosovo peace plan, as key Western and Yugoslav generals 
gathered to finalize details for withdrawing troops. The meeting 
came after the eight major powers signed off on a text to secure a 
U.N. blessing for the deal. The United States, Russia and six 
leading democracies authorized a text calling for a peacekeeping 
force for Kosovo with ``substantial'' NATO participation and agreed 
on a NATO bombing pause -- once Serb forces began a verifiable 
withdrawal. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs May Be Set To Leave Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. intelligence has detected signs that Serb  
forces are preparing to withdraw from Kosovo, although no troops 
are moving or assembling for a pullout, the Pentagon said today. 
Spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the signs include the mobilization of 
Serb transport vehicles that would be used to move soldiers out. 
Bacon also disclosed details on U.S. planning for the NATO-led 
peacekeeping force. Some 1,900 Marines from the 26th Marine 
Expeditionary Unit now aboard ships in the Aegean Sea would serve 
as the vanguard of U.S. peacekeepers. 

</P>
<P>
	NYC Cop Guilty in Torture Case  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A policeman was convicted today of holding down  
a Haitian immigrant in a stationhouse bathroom while another 
officer sodomized him with a broomstick. Three other officers were 
acquitted. The verdict came two weeks after Officer Justin Volpe -- 
the central figure in the trial -- pleaded guilty to torturing Abner 
Louima with the stick. Officer Charles Schwarz, 33, sat impassively 
as the jury convicted him of violating Louima's civil rights. He 
and Volpe could get life in prison. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Sends Workers Home  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Utilities warned today that they might not be  
able to keep air conditioners running as much of the East baked in 
record-breaking heat for the second day. The thermometer registered 
a record-breaking 96 at Raleigh-Durham, N.C. Washington sizzled at 
98, and Philadelphia quickly reached a record 95. It was 95 in New 
York. The company that oversees the New England power grid asked 
the region's governors to send employees home so electricity could 
be turned off. The request was necessary to avoid rolling 
blackouts, a spokesman said. 

</P>
<P>
	Group Seeks Ban on Jail Stun Belts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal and state prisons are increasingly  
relying on stun belts that can deliver 50,000 volts of electricity 
to subdue prisoners, according to Amnesty International. The U.S. 
Marshals Service, the federal Bureau of Prisons and at least 20 
state prison systems have authorized use of stun belts, although 
the extent of their use in some of those states isn't clear, the 
human rights group said today. Amnesty International plans a 
worldwide print and TV advertising campaign next month calling for 
a ban on the belts. 

</P>
<P>
	Hormone Benefits May Outweigh Risks  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A study of 37,000 women found that taking  
hormones after menopause does not increase the risk of breast 
cancer, except for forms of the disease that are slow-growing and 
very treatable. Researchers said the findings are good news because 
they add to evidence that the benefits of hormones outweigh any 
increased cancer risk. Millions of women take hormones to ease the 
symptoms of menopause. Previous studies have indicated that women 
who take hormones -- specifically estrogen -- after menopause are 
more likely to develop breast cancer. 

</P>
<P>
	Boston Office Rents Most Expensive  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Forget about New York and San Francisco: the U.S.  
city with the most expensive office space is Boston, according to a 
new survey. Average rents for Boston's Class A office buildings 
were $47.93 per square foot during the first quarter of 1999, the 
nationwide commercial real estate company Cushman &AMP; Wakefield 
found. That's 15 cents more than the $47.78 price per square foot 
in midtown Manhattan. San Francisco has the third-most expensive 
office space at $46.08 per square foot. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 143.74  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The fear of higher interest rates returned to  
Wall Street today after a three-session hiatus. The Dow Jones 
industrial average ended down 143.74 points at 10,765.64. On the 
NYSE, losers led gainers 1,826-1,147. The Nasdaq fell 49.71 to 
2,474.50. 

</P>
<P>
	Smith Ends Swimming Career  
</P>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- Olympic champion Michelle Smith de Bruin  
ended her swimming career today, insisting she did not use drugs. 
Her announcement came one day after the Irish swimmer lost her 
appeal of a four-year ban for manipulating a urine sample. Irish 
swim authorities may strip her of her national records. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
  	   	
</P>
