<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pretrial Rulings Made in Intel Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- A federal judge has ruled that Intel  
Corp. had no license to use Intergraph patented technology in its 
Pentium family of processors, rejecting Intel's argument that the 
patents were included in an old agreement with National 
Semiconductor Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The pretrial ruling by U.S. District Judge Edwin Nelson was an  
early blow for Intel in its defense against a lawsuit brought by 
Intergraph of Huntsville, a workstation manufacturer, in November 
1997. Intergraph contends Intel, which makes computer chips, 
infringed on its patents, used coercive business practices and 
violated antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Nelson's ruling addressed only Intel's claim of a licensing  
agreement governing the Intergraph patents. The allegations of 
patent infringement, antitrust violations and illegal practices 
will be addressed at a trial in February 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for Intergraph, Bill Baxley of Birmingham, did not  
immediately return a call seeking comment Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the news release, Intergraph Chairman and Chief Executive Jim  
Meadlock said Intel repeatedly has claimed they have a license to 
the ``Clipper'' chip patents. 
</P>
<P>
	``The court affirms they don't have such a license,'' Meadlock  
said. ``We believe the entire Pentium family infringes on our 
patents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Intel, Chuck Mulloy, said Monday an appeal of  
Nelson's order was being considered. But the license claim was only 
one of several defenses Intel planned to raise in the lawsuit, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are disappointed and we respectfully disagree with the  
judge,'' Mulloy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Intergraph makes computer workstations mated to its software,  
with the core of its business involving elaborate computer graphics 
for technical design, mapping and animation. For a time, Intergraph 
used its own high-end microprocessor, the ``Clipper,'' in its 
workstations but later moved to an Intel-based system and abandoned 
the Clipper. 
</P>
<P>
	Intergraph claims when it tried to enforce the Clipper patent,  
Intel denied the company technical information and advance copies 
of new microchips -- both crucial to developing new products. 
Intergraph also contends Intel chips were made using Intergraph 
technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Intel claims it did nothing illegal. In the motion denied by  
Nelson, the chipmaker claimed the Clipper technology fell under a 
long-standing cross-license agreement with NSC. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Intergraph news release, Intergraph and NSC  
each bought parts of Fairchild Semiconductor Corp. in concurrent 
transactions in 1987. Intergraph bought Fairchild's Advanced 
Processor Division, the original developer of the Clipper chip, it 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The undisputed facts establish that NSC had no legal authority  
to grant a license, as the patents at issue belonged not to NSC but 
to a legally distinct corporation -- Fairchild,'' Nelson wrote in 
his order. ``Intel thus never received a license from any entity 
with the power to grant one. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fundamental flaw in Intel's license defense is that the  
alleged license would have originated from NSC, while the Clipper 
patents quite clearly belonged not to NSC but to Fairchild, a 
separate corporation,'' Nelson wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Mulloy said the judge's ruling had ``very broad and  
unprecedented implications'' for the high-tech industry. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 13:00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> School Buses Found Safer Than Vans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- School districts might save money using vans  
instead of school buses to transport students, but it's ``an 
economical advantage purchased at the safety of children,'' the 
head of a federal safety panel said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wrapping up a special investigation into four crashes involving  
``nonconforming buses,'' Jim Hall, chairman of the National 
Transportation Safety Board, said the standard yellow bus provides 
better crash protection than vans and should be the only type of 
vehicle used to take students to school and school-related 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	The crashes that were the subject of the investigation occurred  
in 1998 and earlier this year in Sweetwater, Fla., Lenoir City, 
Tenn., East Dublin, Ga., and Bennettsville, S.C. They killed nine 
people, including eight students. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said the vehicle damage would have been less and  
the injuries not as severe had the accidents involved school buses, 
not a van or a ``specialty bus'' -- a slightly larger vehicle akin 
to an airport rental car shuttle. 
</P>
<P>
	School buses, unlike standard passenger vans, have special  
rollover protections and encase their occupants in a cocoon of 
padded seats and seatbacks. They also have welds designed to keep 
them from splitting open on impact. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, school buses are painted an eye-catching yellow and  
equipped with emergency exits, special warning lights and movable 
arms that block students from walking directly in front of them. 
Many of the protections date from a 1977 change in federal law, 
which was prompted by earlier recommendations from the safety 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	A ``nonconforming bus'' is any vehicle that can carry 10 or more  
people and is used to take students to school or school-related 
activities, yet does not meet federal school bus standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law prohibits car dealers from selling vehicles that do  
not meet federal school bus regulations to schools that plan to use 
them to transport children. 
</P>
<P>
	However, many states have exemptions in their school bus laws  
for after-school, day care or church programs. Even the federal 
government has lagged in developing rules for transporting children 
involved in such things as Head Start, the early-childhood 
education program. 
</P>
<P>
	The worst accident examined by the safety board occurred on Feb.  
16 in Bennettsville, S.C. Six children were killed -- including 
three who were thrown outside the vehicle -- when the 15-passenger 
van they were riding in was struck by a tow truck. 
</P>
<P>
	On March 26, 1998, a 25-passenger speciality bus taking students  
home after an academic competition was rammed by a tractor-trailer 
in Lenoir City, Tenn., when the van's driver attempted a U-turn on 
a highway. A teacher and a student were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The East Dublin, Ga., accident occurred on Dec. 8, 1998, when a  
15-person van taking children to a Head Start program collided with 
a pickup truck. One child was ejected and killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 15-person van was involved in the Sweetwater, Fla.,  
accident, when it was struck by a transit bus at an intersection on 
March 25, 1998. Three children were ejected and suffered head 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-member board only has the power to make safety  
recommendations, not rules. In a unanimous vote, the board urged 
the nation's governors to ensure that students are transported only 
in vehicles meeting the school bus standards. 
</P>
<P>
	The board also urged the Department of Health and Human Services  
to extend the same protection to children participating in Head 
Start. 
</P>
<P>
	``The federal government needs to practice what it preaches and  
it needs to start with Head Start,'' Hall said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 23:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers Rice Philosophical of Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Jerry Rice took a long, hard look at  
himself during the offseason. He didn't particularly like what he 
saw. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL's leading career receiver came back from two devastating  
knee injuries to earn his 12th Pro Bowl invitation last season. But 
he conceded the comeback campaign with the San Francisco 49ers was 
tainted by complaints over his reduced role and the perception of 
selfishness they generated. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice, who joined the 49ers on Tuesday for the opening of a  
four-day, full-squad minicamp, said he knows he's in the twilight 
of his career. He said his main concern now is getting the most out 
of time he has left rather than spend time worrying about whether 
he can maintain his place in the status quo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically it's coming to an end, and I don't want to go out on  
a sour note,'' the 36-year-old Rice said. ``I want to go out 
feeling good about my career, enjoying the game of football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if this would be his last season, Rice laughed and said,  
``No, no, no, no, no, no. I'm not saying that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rice missed most of the 1997 season with knee injuries. He came  
back strong last year, but had trouble adjusting to the notion he 
was no longer the 49ers' offensive focal point. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice, he complained publicly about his lack of involvement in  
the offense, including a memorable shouting match with coach Steve 
Mariucci that was captured by television cameras. He also had a 
harsh exchange with a reporter who suggested in a column that the 
49ers might be better off by trading him. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice conceded he didn't handle himself well.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was not happy about what was going on with me, how I was  
dealing with the situation,'' Rice said. ``I said to myself that 
I've got to completely turn this thing around. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to be able to carry this team like I used to. I  
just want to go in there and try to be a factor, just try to help 
the young guys as much as possible and just enjoy. I'm not going to 
say I'm going to get too relaxed. When my number is called, I want 
to make the play and get it done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After so many years as the offensive focal point, Rice said it's  
tough accepting a reduced role. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's time for me to just kick back and enjoy this game,''  
Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also came to the realization that he had little choice.  
Owens, who led the team with 14 touchdown catches in 1998, and 
Stokes have developed into important playmakers in their own right 
and with running back Garrison Hearst also in the mix, San 
Francisco's offense operates best when Steve Young spreads the ball 
around. 
</P>
<P>
	That point was driven home even more when the 49ers kept both  
potential free agents, re-signing Stokes in March and designating 
Owens as a franchise player, effectively limiting his free agency 
movement. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, Owens signed his $3.5 million tender offer for this  
season with the expectation the two sides will work out a long-term 
deal in the coming weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think for Terrell, to have that behind him, it's a relief,''  
coach Steve Mariucci said. ``The talks on a long-term deal are 
still going and that should get done. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to see not just Terrell, but the Three Amigos,  
Jerry, J.J. and Terrell. You line up with those three guys across 
the board, that's exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That image also helped foster a new philosophical approach by  
Rice after watching David Robinson accept a change in his role with 
the emergence of Tim Duncan as the San Antonio Spurs' chief 
offensive option. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to step away, but I've just got to let go,'' Rice  
said. ``I look at it just like David Robinson, the role he has 
taken now. I think he's dealing with that situation very, very well 
and for him to be able to step back like that, it really showed me 
a lot. Well, that's my role now and that's exactly how I'm going to 
approach it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
