<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Productivity Rises in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- American workers increased their productivity  
in the first three months of this year at an annual rate of 3.5 
percent, the Labor Department reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	That figure -- in line with analysts' expectations -- was slightly  
lower than the government's initial estimate of 4 percent a month 
ago, and follows a downward revision of the quarter's gross 
domestic product. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the 3.5 percent increase represents a strong advance,  
better than the 2.2 percent advance for all of last year. And even 
the 2.2 percent annual figure represented an improvement from weak 
productivity growth over the last two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``During the last four years, labor productivity has advanced at  
an annual rate of 2.1 percent. This is about twice as fast as 
witnessed in the proceeding twenty years,'' said Stan Shipley, an 
economist with Merrill Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	Productivity, the output per hour of work, is considered the key  
measurement for determining whether Americans' living standards 
will increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher productivity means employers can afford to pay workers  
more without raising the price of their products. That keeps 
inflation under control and means that workers' pay checks will go 
farther. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3.5 percent productivity figure resulted from a downward  
revision of the gross domestic product, the total output of goods 
and services, to 4.1 percent from an initial estimate of 4.5 
percent in the first quarter. With less output for the same amount 
of hours worked, the productivity figure was revised down slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a key measurement of inflationary pressures was  
revised up slightly in Tuesday's report. Unit labor costs, the 
amount of compensation per unit of output, edged up 0.7 percent at 
an annual rate in the first quarter, compared to an original 
estimated increase of 0.3 percent. The 0.7 percent rise in unit 
labor costs followed an actual decline of 0.4 percent in the fourth 
quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the upward revision, an increase of just 0.7 percent in  
unit labor costs is considered a good sign that wage pressures are 
well contained, even as the nation's unemployment rate has returned 
to a 29-year low of just 4.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``This certainly suggests that there is no inflation disaster  
lurking around the corner,'' said Ian Shepherdson, economist for 
High Frequency Economics. ``It also suggests that there is no 
pressing reason for the Fed to raise interest rates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the rise in unit labor cost was driven by a 2.6 percent  
rate of increase in wages for each hour of work. This first-quarter 
hourly compensation figure represented a slight acceleration from 
the 2.2 percent rate of increase for the last three months of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	And some analysts blamed this slight rise in hourly wages on a  
dearth of skilled workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``That indicates there is real labor shortages from sea to  
shining sea in America, and that is a new trend,'' said Wells Fargo 
and Co. economist Sung Won Sohn. ``The bottom line is that labor 
shortages are beginning to slow productivity growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Economists are split on whether the Fed will begin raising  
interest rates when policy makers next meet at the end of this 
month. Many believe that if next week's report on consumer prices 
shows another worrisome jump in price pressures, then the Fed will 
be forced to act. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
