<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Another Clinton Adviser Resigning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Janet Yellen, head of President Clinton's  
Council of Economic Advisers for the past two years, said today she 
is stepping down to return to the University of California, 
Berkeley. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials said Martin Baily, a former council  
member, is likely to succeed her. 
</P>
<P>
	Yellen said she took her decision for ``personal and family''  
reasons. Her husband, George Akerlof, also an economics professor 
at Berkeley, is returning to the school after a two-year leave of 
absence. Yellen said after five years in Washington she does not 
want to subject her family to more cross-country commuting. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, President Clinton said Yellen's ``extraordinary  
intellect and keen grasp of domestic and international economics 
have contributed enormously to the formation of my administration's 
policies in critical areas ranging from Social Security, health 
care and the budget to trade and international financial 
architecture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An administration official speaking on condition of anonymity  
said Baily is the leading candidate to succeed Yellen. He was a 
member of the Council of Economic Advisers in 1995-96 and since 
then has been a partner in the Washington office of McKinsey &AMP; Co., 
a consulting firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The official said that in an effort to persuade Yellen to remain  
in government service, the administration offered her the No. 2 job 
at the Federal Reserve, but Yellen declined. 
</P>
<P>
	Alice Rivlin, the Fed's current vice chairwoman, said last week  
she will leave the central bank next month after three years in 
order to devote more time to her duties as head of the District of 
Columbia financial control board. 
</P>
<P>
	While the administration has taken a year to fill another  
vacancy on the seven-member Federal Reserve board, National 
Economic Council Director Gene Sperling said Tuesday the search for 
Rivlin' replacement is ``well along. We are down to a very short 
list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yellen's and Rivlin's announcements followed the revelation last  
month by Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin that he is leaving, 
effective around July 4. Clinton has nominated Deputy Treasury 
Secretary Lawrence Summers to replace Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	Yellen, who said she did not set a departure date because of her  
desire for a smooth transition, has headed the three-member Council 
of Economic Advisers since 1997. At the time, her appointment was 
seen as an administration effort to foster closer ties with the 
Fed, where Yellen was serving when Clinton chose her for the 
council. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman of the CEA is considered the president's chief  
economist, and the three economists on the council are used as the 
administration's in-house think tank on economic policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Yellen was among Clinton's first two appointees to the Fed.  
Before joining the central bank, she was an economics professor at 
Berkeley, where she plans to rejoin the faculty. 
</P>
<P>
	Yellen was Clinton's third council chief, after Laura Tyson,  
another Berkeley professor, and Joseph Stiglitz. Tyson has returned 
to Berkeley as dean of the business school, and Stiglitz is chief 
economist at the World Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Yellen's departure would leave the Council of Economic Advisers  
with only one member, Rebecca M. Blank. Clinton has nominated 
Harvard professor Robert Lawrence to fill another vacancy, but the 
Senate has not confirmed him. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
