<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dallas Stars Acquire Derek Plante </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Stars acquired Derek Plante at the  
trading deadline to put another potential scorer at the end of the 
bench during the Stanley Cup playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	What they ended up getting was someone with inside information.  
</P>
<P>
	Plante came to Dallas after 5 1/2 seasons in Buffalo. On Tuesday  
night, his new team and his old club played Game 1 of the Stanley 
Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know everybody on both teams,'' Plante said. ``It's pretty  
funny.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coaches and teammates have been picking Plante's brain since  
Dallas clinched the Western Conference title Friday night. The 
Stars only had four days to prepare for the Sabres, so they're 
looking for any edge. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have pretty good scouting reports and they've been  
watching the team, so they know what's going on,'' Plante said. 
``But sometimes they come and ask me a few questions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Game tapes show how players react to certain situations. Watch  
enough tapes and you can log their reactions to dozens of 
situations. 
</P>
<P>
	But to really understand what makes a guy tick and to know how  
to play with his mind takes knowledge that can only come from being 
with him regularly -- places Plante was just three months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabres coach Lindy Ruff dismisses that idea  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it's much of a factor,'' Ruff said. ``I think  
he's going to have as much input as he possibly can, but if they 
look at tapes, they're going to see all our tendencies and all the 
things we do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo drafted Plante in the seventh round in 1989, and he made  
the team in 1993-94. A former winner of the NHL's fastest-shot and 
fastest-skater contests, he scored 50 points in three of his first 
four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Back spasms limited him last year and his playing time was down  
this season, too. He finally was sent to the Stars for a 
second-round pick in this year's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of figured something was going to happen,'' Plante  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Plante went from a team fighting for the last playoff spot to a  
team cruising to the NHL's best regular-season record for the 
second straight year. He thought going to Dallas was his best way 
of playing for the Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	But as of last Monday, the seventh-seeded Sabres were in the  
finals for the first time since 1975 and the top-seeded Stars were 
down 3-2 to Colorado in the Western Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Plante was happy for his former teammates. But he also was  
confident the Stars would be joining them. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the best team I've ever been on,'' Plante said.  
``Obviously, the team in Buffalo is pretty good, too, but they're a 
totally different team. They are younger and kind of building 
things. 
</P>
<P>
	Plante played six of the first 10 playoff games and his lone  
point was a big one: a third-period goal that tied Game 6 of the 
second round, leading to Mike Modano's series-winner in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	Plante sat out in the conference finals, but he's likely to play  
this round, especially if Grant Marshall can't return from a groin 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars also may want to tap Plante's desire to beat his  
former team. It worked last round with Avalanche-ex Mike Keane, who 
scored two goals in the deciding game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never played against them, so I don't know what will  
happen,'' Plante said. ``They know me as well as I know them, I 
guess. So I don't know if it's an advantage or disadvantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully I can provide some offense, just add a spark and  
help the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plante says he enjoys playing his old teammates.  
</P>
<P>
	``You always play against your friends and you want to beat them  
more than anybody else,'' he said. ``You want to have bragging 
rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plante hasn't spoken to his former teammates since the playoffs  
began and he doesn't expect to until after this series. He's 
excited about going back to Buffalo and seeing his non-hockey 
friends, many of whom will be seeking tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Plante said his phone hasn't been ringing too often yet.  
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody has my number down here,'' he said, smiling.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
