<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tennessee Dairy Farms Disappearing / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Dairy farmer Marty Davis has fences in  
disrepair. He has barns that need new roofs. He works his 450 acres 
in Bedford County on a 1971 tractor with 12,000 hours on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's like a driving a car with half a million miles on it,''  
he said Tuesday. ``I don't have the funds to replace it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis is among a dwindling number of Tennessee Grade-A dairy  
farmers clinging to their businesses in the face of stiff 
competition and fluctuating prices. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 400 dairy farms have shut down in the state since  
1997, according to the Tennessee Farm Bureau Federation. Now, just 
998 dairy farms produce Grade-A milk in Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been feast and famine. We have good prices for a while,  
then the prices get low,'' Davis said of his 150-cow operation. 
``We hang on in hard times and try to catch up in the good times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee farmers are more vulnerable to competition because the  
majority have small farms, with 50 cows or fewer. The state imports 
a large amount of its milk from other states where mass producers 
can offer cheaper prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``The large dairies can take advantage of the latest  
technology,'' said John Harrison, a Loudon County dairy farmer with 
about 850 cows. ``As the industry becomes more management and 
capital intensive, it becomes harder and harder for the Southeast 
to compete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Development in rural areas is another factor. Many farmers feel  
they can make more money by selling their land for subdivisions 
than by continuing to operate. Those who choose to continue farming 
have seen property taxes skyrocket as land prices rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Strasser, president of the Dairy Association of Tennessee,  
is Davidson County's only remaining dairy farmer, with an 80-cow 
operation directly across from the Opryland Hotel. He believes 
dairy farms are particularly vulnerable to this land pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	``It goes back to the '40s and '50s, when we didn't have good  
roads and refrigeration, so dairy farms had to be close to towns 
and cities,'' he said. ``When development came, what was the first 
thing in their way? The dairy farms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Farm Bureau has established a task force to find ways to  
bring some financial stability to dairy and other farms in 
Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is considering legislation that would create a Southern  
Dairy Compact that would allow delegates from Tennessee and other 
states to set regional prices above the federal minimum for raw 
milk. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents have argued it would simply raise costs for consumers,  
while farmers say they need the legislation to help ensure they get 
reasonable prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis supports the idea of the compact so he can stay in  
business, even though it's unclear whether it will be enough to 
maintain Tennessee dairy farms into the next generation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I didn't love working outside and working with animals so  
much, I wouldn't continue,'' he said. ``I have a grown son. He 
says, 'Daddy, I'd love to farm, but I just don't feel like I can 
make a living doing it.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
