<HEADLINE> Strawberry Decision Just Days Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Darryl Strawberry's future will be decided soon.  
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for baseball commissioner Bud Selig said Monday the  
decision on how Strawberry's latest drug suspension is resolved 
will be made ``in the next few days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selig's spokesman, Rich Levin, said the decision could come as  
early as today or Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, 37, has been suspended since April 24 following his  
arrest for cocaine possession. Doctors for the players' association 
and the commissioner's office have been working on a joint 
recommendation to Selig on how he should proceed. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees outfielder, who served a 90-day suspension  
in 1995 after testing positive for cocaine, pleaded no contest to 
cocaine possession and solicitation charges last month and was 
sentenced to 18 months' probation and 100 hours' community service. 
He also must undergo more drug treatment, be tested twice and week 
and pay $456 in court fees. 
</P>
