<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing To Examine Launch Failures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Faced with recent space launch  
failures, Boeing Co. has formed an independent panel of experts to 
examine the processes involved in its rocket programs, the company 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel will review Boeing's Delta, Sea Launch and Inertial  
Upper Stage programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expressly selected team members with a broad range of  
senior-level systems experience in aerospace -- from satellites to 
academia to launch vehicles,'' said James F. Albaugh, president of 
Boeing Space and Communications Group. 
</P>
<P>
	The team is expected to report its findings by this fall.  
</P>
<P>
	The panel will be headed by Sheila E. Widnall, former secretary  
of the Air Force and currently a professor at the Massachusetts 
Institute of Technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing's new Delta III rocket failed to put a satellite in the  
proper orbit last month, and the Delta III's debut last August 
ended in an explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, an early analysis of an April 9 failure of a launch of  
Lockheed Martin's big Titan IV rocket implicated the Boeing-built 
upper stage. The new head of Lockheed Martin Astronautics has 
similarly vowed to thoroughly review its programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The team will examine organizational roles and responsibilities  
within Boeing, recent launch failure investigation findings, 
processes used for government, civil and commercial launches as 
well as the acceptance processes for major subsystems and complex 
assemblies from suppliers. 
</P>
<P>
	It will also look at the manufacturing, assembly, transportation  
and storage activities of the Boeing launch programs. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
