<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Swimming Champ Ends Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) -- While insisting that she is innocent of  
drug violations, Olympic champion Michelle Smith de Bruin says she 
will no longer swim competitively. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am saddened that my career has ended in this way, but now  
(husband) Erik and I must look to the future and decide where we go 
from here,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith announced her decision Tuesday, one day after the Irish  
swimmer lost her appeal of a four-year ban for manipulating a urine 
sample. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith won three gold medals at the 1996 Atlanta Games. The  
29-year-old swimmer is ineligible for the 2000 Sydney Olympics and 
the 2001 world championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will forever cherish my moments of victory and hope that  
those who still believe in me will also cherish their memories of 
those times,'' she said. ``I hope that you will not believe that I 
have brought this country into disrepute or that I have let you 
down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She and her husband, whose career ended with his own four-year  
ban for using performance-enhancing drugs, were married weeks 
before Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	FINA, the international swimming federation, banned Smith after  
finding her guilty of contaminating a urine sample with alcohol 
during an out-of-competition test in January 1998. Alcohol could 
mask banned drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Court of Arbitration for Sport in Switzerland  
rejected her appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Irish government, which once hailed Smith for the greatest  
Olympic performance by an Irish athlete, ruefully accepted the 
verdict. Irish swim authorities are now considering stripping her 
of her national records. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I condemn more in sadness than in anger,'' Sports Minister  
James McDaid said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We swam those lanes with her, we stayed up all night, we had  
served our time, and I'm sure a lot of people across the country 
had hoped she would be able to prove her innocence,'' McDaid said. 
``... You wanted to believe her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawyer, Peter Lennon, made no mention of an appeal. Smith  
said in a statement her victories are ``not hollow and were 
achieved without the use of any illegal performance-enhancing 
drugs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``However, I am strong in the knowledge that I have not  
committed the offense with which I was charged, or any other 
offense, and that to date no one has proven on a direct factual 
basis how the whiskey entered the sample,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	McDaid said he would start Ireland's first formal drug-testing  
program for athletes in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Swim Ireland, the country's swimming body, said it might strike  
Smith's nine national records she set in 1995, the year after her 
future husband, a Dutch discus thrower, became her coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith accused FINA of deliberately targeting her and accused the  
three-member arbitration panel of accepting circumstantial evidence 
from others rather than her direct testimony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
