<HEADLINE> Nissan Making Trunk Release Device </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GARDENA, Calif. (AP) -- Nissan North America Inc. followed the  
lead of General Motors Corp. and other automakers to make it 
possible for anyone trapped inside a car trunk to get out. 
</P>
<P>
	During extreme heat last summer, 11 children, including four  
cousins in Gallup, N.M., died after crawling into trunks to play 
and shutting the lids. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan will make trunk release device kits available later this  
year for 4 million models beginning with the 1990 model year, said 
company spokesman Fred Standish. 
</P>
<P>
	New Nissan and Infinity cars sold later this year will have the  
trunk release already installed, said company spokesman Scott 
Vazin. The 2000 models will include pamphlets on how to avoid trunk 
entrapment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Interior trunk release mechanisms will be developed for the  
highest-volume vehicles first,'' said Nissan vice president Jason 
Vines. The cost of the kits has not been determined. 
</P>
<P>
	Since March, GM has been installing manual handles into the  
trunks of cars already on the road as optional equipment at the 
dealership for about $50. GM's yellow handle is illuminated in the 
dark cargo area. It also plans to equip most of its four-door 
family cars with an infrared sensing device that automatically 
unlocks the trunk if anyone is trapped inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Motor Co. and DaimlerChrysler AG are working on a standard  
trunk-release system. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of DaimlerChrysler AG's Chrysler and Dodge cars will have  
an optional kit available within a month. DaimlerChrysler also 
plans to make trunk releases a standard feature for new cars by 
2001. Ford will have a T-shaped handle that glows inside the trunk 
as a standard feature on most of its 2000 models. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 03:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
