<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Seeks Ban on Jail Stun Belts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's court bailiffs and prison guards  
increasingly are strapping inmates into stun belts capable of 
delivering a 50,000-volt shock, Amnesty International USA said 
today, urging an end to the practice. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Bureau of Prisons has 40 of the battery-operated belts  
for use when transporting dangerous prisoners. In New Orleans, the 
Old Parish Prison routinely uses the belts on inmates being taken 
to a hospital for AIDS treatment. In Los Angeles, an inmate who was 
shocked for interrupting a judge during his sentencing hearing is 
suing the county. 
</P>
<P>
	Amnesty International USA said Tuesday the belts are inhumane  
and dangerous. ``A nation that opposes torture in far-off places 
has no credibility when it sanctions torture of its own,'' said the 
human rights group's executive director, William F. Schulz. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Civil Liberties Union also has attacked the belts  
as a violation of prisoners' rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prison officials defend the technology as a nonlethal  
way to deter violent behavior and protect guards, and say the belts 
are used under strict guidelines. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been the bureau's policy to use custody control belts  
to prevent escapes or prevent loss of life or grievous bodily 
harm,'' Bureau of Prisons spokesman Todd Craig said. 
</P>
<P>
	The battery-powered stun belt, triggered by a remote control  
from up to 300 feet away, temporarily incapacitates inmates with a 
painful, eight-second jolt above the left kidney. Stun Tech Inc. of 
Cleveland is the primary manufacturer and sells the belt for about 
$700. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 20 state corrections agencies have authorized the  
belts, Amnesty International USA reported. The group did not 
determine to what extent the devices are actually being used by 
states and federal officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Amnesty International USA, the U.S. affiliate of the  
London-based human rights organization, argued there hasn't been 
sufficient medical study to determine whether the shocks are 
dangerous for inmates, including those with heart problems or AIDS. 
The group said the pain-inflicting devices cause terror and violate 
the constitutional prohibition against ``cruel or unusual 
punishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bureau of Prisons, which cooperated with the Amnesty  
International report, started using the belts in 1994 at its 12 
high-security prisons. The 40 belts are used only in rare 
instances, such as transporting high-security prisoners to medical 
facilities, and none has ever been activated, Craig said. 
</P>
<P>
	A warden must approve use of any stun belt, and only a senior  
lieutenant can hold the remote control that activates it. The 
bureau prohibits use of the belts on prisoners with heart disease, 
epilepsy or other medical conditions, Craig said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Marshals Service, which provides security for federal  
courts and transports suspects, has been using stun belts for 
disruptive prisoners since 1986, spokesman William Dempsey said. 
The belts have been activated ``very few times,'' Dempsey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stun belts have received wide attention since a defendant was  
shocked while serving as his own lawyer in Long Beach, Calif., last 
year. A judge ordered Ronnie Hawkins shocked because of his 
repeated interruptions during a sentencing hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawkins later sued for $50 million. A federal judge issued a  
temporary injunction barring the use of stun belts in Los Angeles 
County courts. 
</P>
<P>
	The ACLU's National Prison Project also has sued in Louisiana,  
arguing inmates of the segregated HIV/AIDS unit of New Orlean's Old 
Parish Prison must wear the belts during transportation between the 
prison and a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for New Orleans Parish Sheriff Charles C. Foti Jr.  
said in court papers that the stun belts are now used for 
transporting all prisoners, including the AIDS patients. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:50:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rate Swings Bedevil Bond Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After years of getting whipsawed by the ups and  
downs of interest rates, investors in bond mutual funds are still 
bedeviled by a bad sense of timing. 
</P>
<P>
	They poured substantial amounts of new money into bond funds  
last year for the first time since 1993. In a replay of the 
aftermath of all the other cash-flow peaks in recent history, now 
they are faced with a spell of weak performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Investment Company Institute, the industry's main trade  
group, reports that bond funds had net new cash flow of $74.6 
billion in 1998, surpassing the previous high for this decade of 
$73.3 billion five years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The wave of new money last year followed outflows totaling more  
than $75 billion in 1994-95, and inflows of just $2.8 billion in 
1996 and $28.4 billion in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The abrupt dropoff in enthusiasm in the mid-1990s occurred when  
the Federal Reserve tightened credit conditions in 1994, and bond 
prices suffered a sharp drop as interest rates rose. In the years 
that followed, investors gradually returned to bond funds again as 
rates fell back to new 30-year lows by early last fall. 
</P>
<P>
	So what has happened now that enthusiasm for bond funds has  
warmed up again? Another jump in interest rates this spring, 
renewed talk of Fed tightening, and a new spell of skimpy or no 
returns from bond funds. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the research firm of Lipper Inc., the average among  
more than 2,000 domestic long-term fixed-income funds posted a 
total return of minus 1.06 percent in May. That left the average 
with a net return, including dividends and changes in net asset 
value, of minus 0.02 percent for the first five months of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	World income funds, as tracked by Lipper, had an even tougher  
time of it, dropping 2.53 percent in May and 1.31 percent overall 
for the January-May period. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a tough year for investors in most high-quality bond  
funds,'' says Norman Fosback, editor-in-chief of the newsletter 
Income Fund Outlook in Deerfield Beach, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on 30-year Treasury bonds climbed 120 basis points, or  
hundredths of a percentage point, from a low of 4.7 percent last 
fall to 5.9 percent recently, Fosback notes. ``The advance was 
accelerated in May when the Federal Open Market Committee announced 
that it would lean in the direction of tight money. 
</P>
<P>
	``The FOMC announcement occurred almost simultaneously with the  
government's surprising report of a 0.7 percent increase in the 
consumer price index for April. ... Although inflation is likely to 
ease from the steep rate in April, the giddy days of only 1 percent 
annual inflation are long gone for this economic expansion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fosback recommends that investors avoid most funds that  
specialize in longer-maturity bonds, given this worrisome picture. 
Presumably, they would be better off waiting until prospects 
improved for a good payoff from bond funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The trouble is, the record suggests that the majority of  
bond-fund investors can't do this kind of maneuvering with any 
degree of success. If they could discern when bonds were a good 
buy, they should have been pouring money into bond funds in 1994 
and 1995, rather than pulling it out. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, by the same standard, they should have turned cautious,  
instead of pumping more money in than at any time since 1986 
(another buying binge, by the way, that was followed by bond market 
woes in the spring of 1987). 
</P>
<P>
	The record shows a pattern of consistent misjudgment. If good  
timing were necessary to achieve worthwhile results, fund investors 
as a group would be better off staying away from this class of 
funds altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet in the long-term, patient investors in bond funds have been  
rewarded quite nicely. Over the past 10 years, according to Lipper, 
domestic bond funds have averaged a 7.84 percent annual return, and 
world bond funds 7.38 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The only way to have realized those results for yourself, of  
course, was to own bond funds as of May 1989 and to hold them all 
through the up-and-down swings of the 1990s -- no attempt to pick 
when bonds looked good or didn't look good, just plain old 
buy-and-hold. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End adv for use anytime    	
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
