<DOCNO> APW19990608.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 08:06:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Down 54.77 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mixed in early trading on Wall  
Street today, with blue-chip stocks giving up ground after their 
strong gains Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 54.77 at 10,854.61. The Dow climbed Monday for the third 
straight session amid enthusiasm over merger activity, adding 
109.54 to close at 10,909.38. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed today, with the Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 composite down 2.23 at 1,332.29 and the Nasdaq composite 
up 7.94 at 2,532.15. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow industrials were led lower by Procter &AMP; Gamble, down 1 7/8  
at 95 11/16; IBM, down 1 5/8 at 118 7/8; and Sears, down 1 1/16 at 48 
11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said there was little news to influence trading.  
Investors are still concerned that the Federal Reserve might raise 
interest rates in a bid to cool the economy at its next policy 
meeting on June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	But some market players believe traders are already betting on a  
rate increase of 0.25 percentage point, and that they're not likely 
to do much more selling. They point to a report last Friday of 
moderate May employment gains, which helped ease fears of a larger 
rate hike. 
</P>
<P>
	And while the major indexes have performed well lately, they  
have done so on very thin volume, a sign, analysts said, that 
traders may begin selling again. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by 1,178 to 989 on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 91.84 million shares, 
above Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 1.30 to 635.64, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 0.41 at 777.74. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.53 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.53 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.20 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 
0.29 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 09:16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NATO Hits Targets Near Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO struck targets near the  
Yugoslav capital for the first time in days today, keeping its 
pledge to intensify attacks until President Slobodan Milosevic 
orders his troops out of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Architects of an international plan calling for the troop  
withdrawal -- the G-8 countries of Russia, the United States and six 
major industrialized nations -- today unanimously agreed on a U.N. 
resolution authorizing a peacekeeping force for Kosovo with NATO at 
the core. 
</P>
<P>
	The G-8's action in Germany was forced by Yugoslav insistence  
that the U.N. Security Council endorse any peace plan for Kosovo -- 
a demand backed by Moscow, Yugoslavia's chief ally. The draft now 
on ``fast track'' goes to New York next for quick approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The foreign ministers also agreed on a NATO bombing pause  
between the time Yugoslav withdrawals begin and the Security 
Council passes the resolution. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO said regardless of the agreement among G-8 nations, the  
bombing campaign that began March 24 will continue until the 40,000 
or so Serb forces in Kosovo actually pull out and all the ethnic 
Albanians expelled over the past couple of months are allowed back 
in. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to maintain our military pressure on Yugoslavia  
until we see the clear indication of a complete, rapid and 
verifiable withdrawal of the Yugoslav forces,'' spokesman Jamie 
Shea told reporters at NATO headquarters in Belgium. 
``Implementation is the bottom light.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright called the negotiations an  
``outstanding example of how force and diplomacy work together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO force came into play today in Serbia, where fire and dense  
smoke could be seen rising above Pancevo, 12 miles northeast of 
Belgrade, and explosions could be heard from the direction of 
nearby Batajnica military airfield. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, one person was killed and five were wounded in NATO  
attacks on Novi Sad, Yugoslavia's second-largest city, Serb media 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	President Boris Yeltsin today condemned the stepped-up bombing,  
saying NATO was trying to establish a ``dictatorship of force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Brussels, a NATO statement this morning said allied jets  
conducted 658 sorties over the past 24 hours -- equal to the levels 
before the alliance scaled back attacks after Milosevic and the 
Serb parliament said it accepted a peace plan Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The airstrikes came despite an attempt by Milosevic to assure  
key Western countries he intends to abide by terms of the peace 
plan even though there was a breakdown of talks on withdrawing Serb 
troops from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Ministry spokesman Nebojsa Vujovic said his government  
was still committed to the plan but he accused NATO of ``trying to 
... have an international security presence enter Kosovo without a 
U.N. mandate, without a Security Council decision and without U.N. 
auspices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vujovic also said Yugoslavia is demanding it be able to keep  
guards and customs officials at the borders to monitor the return 
of hundreds of thousands of refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain said a ``small symbolic force'' of Serbs at the border  
operating under strict NATO supervision would be allowed at the 
border. 
</P>
<P>
	In Cologne, Germany, Albright said ``NATO will be the military  
leader,'' adding: ``We got what we came for'' and that the ``Serbs 
in no way control who goes back into Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also said the ethnic Albanian refugees who fled Kosovo since  
March would be issued identity papers by the United Nations' main 
relief agency to replace those taken away by Serb forces. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians had resisted NATO's leadership of the force, but  
compromised on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any agreement is a compromise,'' Russian Foreign Minister Igor  
Ivanov said. 
</P>
<P>
	British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said the agreement breaks  
through the obstacles that blocked a military agreement between 
NATO and Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The German foreign minister said high-level talks on getting  
that military agreement can now resume. 
</P>
<P>
	Said German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer: ``We have achieved  
a decisive step here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Group of Eight foreign ministers wrapped up 12 hours of  
negotiations today over lingering disputes to a U.N. resolution 
outlining the peace plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Security Council must authorize an international force and  
civilian administration that would be dispatched to Kosovo under 
U.N. auspices to ensure the safe return of the estimated 860,000 
ethnic Albanian refugees who have fled since March. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 50,000 troops, including 7,000 Americans, are expected to  
make up the peacekeeping force in a mission that Washington said 
will be open-ended. 
</P>
<P>
	Finland leader Martti Ahtisaari, a Balkans envoy to the talks,  
was in Beijing today, trying to get China to support the peace 
plan. China, a U.N. Security Council member with veto powers, 
called today for a halt in the NATO bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia also wants a pause in the NATO bombing.  
</P>
<P>
	NATO-Yugoslav talks in Macedonia on pulling out the troops  
collapsed Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, NATO resumed attacks around Yugoslavia's major cities for  
the first time since Milosevic said he accepted a peace plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The official Tanjug news agency said a NATO missile hit a  
residential area in Novi Sad, 50 miles north of Belgrade, 
destroying several houses. The attack apparently was aimed at a 
nearby oil refinery, which was also reported hit. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO also struck Kosovo. The alliance said it hit 20 artillery  
pieces, 10 armored personnel carriers and other military forces in 
the province. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO deployed more troops in Macedonia in the force that will  
first go into Kosovo once Serb troops pull out. Some 1,000 British 
troops joined the force, bringing it to 16,500 soldiers; more 
British and French troops are due today, Shea said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo's prewar population of 2.1 million was 90 percent ethnic  
Albanian, and many favor independence. NATO began airstrikes to 
force Milosevic to accept a peace plan for Kosovo and end a 
13-month crackdown on ethnic Albanians. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0224 </DOCNO>
