<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 21:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians' Cordero Injured From Catch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Wil Cordero broke his left wrist while making a  
sliding catch in the sixth inning of Cleveland's game against the 
Milwaukee Brewers on Tuesday night and could be out for 10 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordero, making his 20th start in left field, bent his wrist  
back awkwardly as he caught a sinking liner hit by Milwaukee's 
Jeromy Burnitz. 
</P>
<P>
	After making the grab, Cordero threw the ball back into the  
infield as he attempted to catch a runner at second base. He then 
fell down in pain as his teammates and an Indians trainer came to 
his aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordero was taken to Lutheran Hospital where X-rays revealed a  
break similar to the one that sidelined Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. 
for 10 weeks in 1995. Cordero will undergo surgery Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't want to see a guy get hurt, I feel bad for Wil,''  
said Indians starter Dave Burba. ``You hate to see a guy who goes 
out and plays hard like that go down like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cordero, signed by the Indians during the offseason, is batting  
.316 with five homers and 26 RBIs. He missed five games early in 
the season with a bruised right wrist and missed eight more with a 
bruised right heel. He has also made 19 starts at DH. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians acquired Cordero at the urging of Roberto and Sandy  
Alomar, who like Cordero, are from Puerto Rico and knew him. 
Cordero was given a $500,000 non-guaranteed contract by Cleveland, 
one of the few teams to show interest in the 27-year-old who had 
prior off-field problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Cordero was one of the surprises of spring training and was  
named the Indians starter in left field when camp broke in April. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally, I feel real bad,'' Roberto Alomar said. ``I am  
sad. Wil was doing a great job for us. He was playing well, all 
business. Hopefully, he will be back soon with us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Raiders Sign Returner Darrien Gordon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Darrien Gordon, a cornerback and kick  
returner whose career 13.2-yard punt return average is an NFL best, 
signed a free agent contract with the Oakland Raiders on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, the Raiders released wide receiver and kick  
returner Desmond Howard, the 1991 Heisman Trophy winner from 
Michigan. Howard was the MVP of the Super Bowl in 1997 with Green 
Bay and signed with the Raiders that offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, a six-year veteran, played the past two years with the  
Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos. He has started in three Super 
Bowls overall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully some of that playoff experience can rub off and we  
can be on track,'' Gordon said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of his agreement weren't released.  
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Gordon led the Broncos with four interceptions  
during the regular season, returning one against Washington for a 
touchdown. He added four more interceptions in the post season, 
included two in the Super Bowl against Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	His 108 return yards in the championship game were a Super Bowl  
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon signed with the Broncos in 1997 after four years with the  
San Diego Chargers. Overall, he has made 60 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon was the 22nd overall pick in the 1993 draft by the  
Chargers out of Stanford. With the Cardinal, he worked under 
current Raiders defensive coordinator Willie Shaw. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
