<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orange County Prosecutor Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- An Orange County prosecutor could spend  
life behind bars if convicted on charges he conspired with a Hells 
Angels leader and others in a drug ring. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy District Attorney Bryan Ray Kazarian, 35, was among a  
dozen people arrested Monday for investigation of drug trafficking 
and money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	His lawyer insisted that Kazarian was duped by the ring's leader  
and did nothing criminal. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12 people, who also include Howard Irvine Coones, 44,  
founder of the Orange County Hells Angels chapter, were charged 
with various counts of conspiracy including money laundering and 
the distribution of cocaine, methamphetamine and prescription 
drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazarian and Coones could face life sentences if convicted,  
Orange County District Attorney Anthony Rackauckas said Monday. 
Kazarian is being held without bail pending trial. 
</P>
<P>
	A deputy district attorney for six years, Kazarian worked in an  
anti-gang unit until January when he was moved to a job inside the 
office so he ``could be more efficiently monitored,'' Rackauckas 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the drug distribution charges involved the shipping of  
chemicals from New Jersey for the manufacturing of methamphetamine 
that was shipped to Hawaii inside Harley-Davidson motorcycles and 
motorcycle shipping crates. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyer Malcolm Guleserian said John David Ward, the  
alleged ringleader, used Kazarian for information and duped him. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had a friendship,'' Guleserian told The Associated Press.  
</P>
<P>
	Court documents claim Kazarian tipped ring members on the status  
of police investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	But Guleserian said Kazarian's only conversation with Ward about  
the case was when Ward asked the prosecutor if he knew a certain 
investigating officer and Kazarian answered no. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.S. Attorney Alejandro Mayorkas said prosecutors have  
wiretaps in which Kazarian is heard relaying information about a 
confidential informant -- actually a fictional character created by 
investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can imagine how we in law enforcement feel when one of the  
individuals with whom we work communicates confidential informant 
information to the targets of our investigative efforts,'' Mayorkas 
said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
