<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Seek Medicare Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *BY ALICE ANN LOVE   	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senior citizens would get Medicare  
prescription drug benefits for the first time but would have to pay 
a monthly premium to help cover the cost under a proposal President 
Clinton is expected to unveil this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The out-of-pocket charge has not yet been calculated, but  
administration officials said it will be less than the average $90 
a month that many retirees now pay to buy private drug coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicare beneficiaries who already have private insurance  
covering prescriptions could choose not to participate and would 
not have to pay the premium. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are working on a benefit that is both meaningful and  
affordable to both the beneficiaries and the program,'' said White 
House domestic policy adviser Chris Jennings. 
</P>
<P>
	John Rother, public policy director for the nation's largest  
organization of older adults, AARP, said that ``for people who 
don't have anything today, clearly they'll be ahead and will 
probably welcome this. But there will be cost sharing involved and 
it's not going to be painless ... it's hardly a freebie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``For people who do have some form of drug coverage today it  
will be a matter of comparing what they have to what's being 
offered,'' Rother added. 
</P>
<P>
	The President plans to unveil details of his proposal later this  
month, as an alternative to a plan proposed in March by an advisory 
commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants to offer new prescription benefits to all 39  
million elderly and disabled Medicare beneficiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, a proposal agreed to by 10 of 17 members of the  
National Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare earlier 
this year would provide government-subsidized drug benefits only 
for those living near the poverty level. Senate Majority Leader 
Trent Lott, R-Miss., has asked the Senate Finance Committee to 
consider that plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennings said Clinton's proposal, first mentioned in his State  
of the Union message in January, has yet to be finalized. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials say they are looking for ways to make  
the new benefit affordable without imposing government price 
controls on drugs, possibly by hiring private companies to help 
negotiate the best prices and manage the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the pharmaceutical industry is watching warily.  
</P>
<P>
	``If it's another giant government program, regardless of  
exactly how it is administered we believe that it will lead to 
government price controls,'' said Alan F. Holmer, president of 
Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America. 
</P>
<P>
	Beneficiaries of Medicare now pay a $45.50 monthly premium for  
coverage that generally doesn't include drugs, except for a few 
that must be administered in hospitals or doctors offices. 
</P>
<P>
	The government estimates about two-thirds of senior citizens  
have some drug coverage -- mostly through retiree health benefits 
offered by former employers, or through supplemental policies known 
as Medigap that they buy on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	But with drug costs rising faster than overall inflation and  
many employers scaling back retirement benefits in the 1990s, 
affording prescriptions is a problem for more and more senior 
citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, as well as many Republicans and Democrats, has voiced  
support for Medicare drug benefits. But the costs are daunting, 
especially since Medicare is expected to run short of cash around 
2015, shortly after the first wave of baby boomers retires. 
</P>
<P>
	One government estimate found that adding even a modest benefit  
-- for example, having Medicare pay 75 percent of retirees' drug 
bills -- would cost at least $20 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has proposed using about $700 billion in income tax  
surpluses expected over the next 15 years to boost Medicare's 
finances and help pay for the drug coverage. Also, he is expected 
to propose steps to save Medicare money, including requiring 
competitive bidding by managed care health plans and some other 
medical providers to serve Medicare beneficiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration also will argue that adding a prescription  
drug benefit could save Medicare money by reducing the need for 
hospital stays and nursing home care. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
