<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 08:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hastert Tells House GOP To Unite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Speaker Dennis Hastert asked fractious House  
Republicans today to unite so they can finally begin passing parts 
of their stalled legislative agenda and retain their slender 
majority in next year's elections. 
</P>
<P>
	In a closed-door meeting, Hastert, R-Ill., delivered a 17-minute  
speech in which participants said he quoted Benjamin Franklin's 
words as he signed the Declaration of Independence: ``We must all 
hang together, or assuredly we shall all hang separately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most immediately, Hastert ordered the House Appropriations  
Committee to make relatively small cuts in the first batch of 
spending bills for the upcoming fiscal year. The reductions are 
designed to finally get those measures moving through the House, 
and to free funds that can be added to later spending bills to 
enhance their chances of passage. 
</P>
<P>
	But with an eye to the 2000 elections, Hastert spoke of the need  
for GOP factions to stop bickering so the House can accomplish 
routine business such as passing annual spending bills, and so the 
party can clarify its message. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're united,'' Hastert told reporters afterwards. ``We're  
standing to balance the budget. We are a party of spending 
restraint. We believe it's important that we preserve Social 
Security. We're not going to dip into the Social Security trust 
fund. And we're going to try to cut taxes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From outside the basement room in the Capitol where the meeting  
was held, applause could be heard. Participants said Hastert read 
his remarks calmly, and conservatives and moderates alike praised 
his call for GOP lawmakers to work together. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a heartfelt expression from the speaker that we have to  
work in a unified fashion, or the whole thing starts to 
deteriorate,'' said Rep. Joe Knollenberg, R-Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are beginning to think seriously about the delights of  
being in the majority'' -- something Republicans don't want to lose, 
said Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a leader of conservatives who had  
blocked a farm spending bill because of unhappiness with earlier 
leadership strategy, said he supported Hastert's plans and would 
end the delays. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's telling some members if you don't have a worthy project,  
forget it,'' Coburn said. 
</P>
<P>
	The speaker's plan involves shifting about $7 billion to  
domestic programs while keeping the 13 annual spending bills for 
fiscal 2000 within limits set by the 1997 budget-balancing law, 
said GOP aides speaking on condition of anonymity. The money would 
come from projected sales of parts of the broadcast spectrum and 
from transfers from defense and other bills. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders were hoping the proposal would allow spending bills  
for fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1, to start moving through the 
House. So far, those measures and others have fared poorly on the 
House floor, as majority Republicans have struggled to control the 
chamber. Defections by just six Republicans can keep the party from 
passing a bill if Democrats hold ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives and other critics have said that under the  
leadership's earlier blueprint, about six of the domestic spending 
bills covering education, veterans and other popular programs would 
not have enough money to even pass the House, let alone get 
President Clinton's signature. That would leave Republicans in a 
weakened bargaining position for end-of-year talks with the White 
House, they argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are eager to avoid another damaging autumn spending  
showdown in which Clinton, as he has in past years, wins billions 
in extra spending from a GOP nervous that a politically costly 
government shutdown would result otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans hope when those negotiations occur this fall -- as  
seems all but certain -- they will be able to limit spending 
increases and win something else in return, such as tax cuts, GOP 
aides said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the 1997 budget pact -- and under a GOP-written budget for  
2000 that Congress approved in April -- lawmakers must hold spending 
to $538 billion next year for all federal agencies. That excludes 
Social Security, interest to federal debt holders and other 
automatically required benefits and payments. The overall federal 
budget is $1.7 trillion. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a blueprint approved last month, House Republicans would  
spend $270 billion for the Pentagon, $19 billion more than this 
year. That leaves $268 billion for the 12 other bills: $25 billion 
less than this year, and more than $30 billion below what Clinton 
has requested. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
