<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Prices Fall on Inflation Fear / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury prices fell Tuesday, briefly boosting  
30-year bond yields above 6 percent for the first time in more than 
a year, amid speculation that the Federal Reserve will boost 
interest rates at its meeting later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 3/8 point,  
or $3.75 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, edged above 6 percent during the session before 
settling at 5.99 percent, up from late Monday's 5.96 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech Tuesday, William Poole, president of the Federal  
Reserve Bank of St. Louis, suggested that he believed inflation has 
returned to the economy, causing bond and stock prices to tumble. 
On the New York Stock Exchange, the Dow Jones industrial average 
fell 143.74 points to 10,765.64. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bond market can't get out of its own way,'' said Charles  
Pradilla, chief investment strategist at SG Cowen Securities, 
noting that at current yeilds, bonds are perceived as a favorable 
alternative to stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed, which already has adopted a bias toward raising  
interest rates to contain inflation, is scheduled to meet on June 
29-30. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.60 percent as the  
discount fell 0.03 percentage points from Monday's auction rate to 
4.48 percent. Six-month yields were 4.96 percent, as the discount 
rose 0.01 percentage point from Monday's auction rate to 4.77 
percent. One-year yields were 5.06 percent as the discount rose by 
0.01 percentage point from late Monday to 4.81 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.69 percent from 4.75 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/8 to 121 1/32. The average yield to 
maturity rose to 5.43 percent, up from 5.42 percent late Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
