<HEADLINE> Bias Charges Filed in N.J. Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) -- Eight people accused of torturing a  
retarded man for kicks have been indicted on bias charges in what 
may be the nation's first such case involving a disabled person. 
</P>
<P>
	In indictments announced Monday, the defendants, ages 19 to 23,  
were charged with kidnapping, harassment and conspiracy stemming 
from a Jan. 30 party in Keansburg. The bias charges would double 
the penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, some of the defendants could get up to 30 years in  
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Physical and mental handicaps were added to New Jersey's bias  
law a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``They tormented this mentally disabled man because of his  
disability,'' said prosecutor John Kaye. ``They did it to him 
because they could, because they could manipulate him and because 
they believed he could not tell on them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bias charges applied in a case of a disabled person are  
probably unique in the United States, said Stuart Van Meveren, a 
Colorado deputy district attorney and co-chairman of the bias crime 
committee of the National Association of District Attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said Eric Krochmaluk was taped to a chair and  
forced to perform embarrassing acts. His eyebrows were shaved, and 
he was burned with cigarettes, choked and beaten, then abandoned in 
a forest. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said he also was attacked during at least two other  
parties after being lured with a promise that he could meet a 
pretty girl. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
