<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyers May Join Other Professions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- People may soon be able to do one-stop  
shopping for legal, financial and other professional help. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest lawyers' group said today it will consider  
whether it's time to end the longtime ban in all 50 states on 
lawyers forming partnerships with other professionals such as 
accountants, psychologists and social workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many clients have a legitimate need for a network of  
professional services,'' Philip S. Anderson, president of the 
American Bar Association, told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, some people might want accounting or financial  
planning advice in addition to legal help. Lawyers who practice 
family law might form partnerships with psychologists or social 
workers to aid people who are being divorced or need to arrange 
care for elderly relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal is spurred in part by changes in Europe and other  
areas of the world where major international accounting firms are 
being allowed to provide legal services. 
</P>
<P>
	``Market forces cannot be stopped, but they can be channeled,''  
Anderson said, adding that the proposal is intended to keep pace 
with a global economy while making sure legal ethics rules apply to 
lawyers no matter where they work. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed ethics rule changes could occur as early as 2001,  
but only if approved next year by the ABA's policy-making House of 
Delegates and then by authorities who regulate lawyers' ethics in 
each state. An initial ABA vote on whether to draft a final 
recommendation is expected in August. 
</P>
<P>
	The decades-old rules barring lawyers from forming partnerships  
with nonlawyers were intended to protect lawyers' independent 
judgment, protect confidential client information and ensure 
lawyers' loyalty to their clients by avoiding conflicts of 
interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson said the proposals are intended to keep those  
protections by making the same legal ethics rules apply to all 
lawyers, whether they work in a traditional law firm or in a 
partnership with other professionals. 
</P>
<P>
	Other professions have ethics rules that may conflict, however,  
such as mental health care workers' obligation to report suspected 
cases of child abuse. Clients would have to be told of such 
differing obligations, Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	And an official with the Securities and Exchange Commission told  
the ABA panel the role of auditors and lawyers are incompatible 
under federal securities law. That issue is being studied further 
by an SEC standards board. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson acknowledged some ABA members oppose the proposed  
changes. But he said they are intended to help both large and small 
firms that want to join forces with other professionals. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a proposal that will permit a variety of novel  
combinations that will provide greater services to the public,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 17:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Cop Guilty in Torture Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A white policeman was convicted today of holding  
down a Haitian immigrant in a stationhouse bathroom while another 
officer brutalized him with a broken broomstick. Three other 
officers were acquitted in the racially explosive case. 
</P>
<P>
	The split verdict came two weeks after Officer Justin Volpe --  
the central figure in the trial -- pleaded guilty to torturing Abner 
Louima with the stick. 
</P>
<P>
	The case against five white officers heightened racial tensions  
between the Police Department and minorities and touched off 
protests. But it also brought about the collapse of the ``blue wall 
of silence'' that keeps police from testifying against each other. 
</P>
<P>
	The anonymous jury of eight whites, three Hispanics and one  
black deliberated 18 hours over three days in federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	Officer Charles Schwarz, 33, sat impassively as the jury  
convicted him of violating Louima's civil rights. Schwarz was 
immediately taken into custody as his supporters wept in the 
courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Volpe could get life in prison.  
</P>
<P>
	Volpe rammed a broomstick up Louima's rectum as he lay  
handcuffed in a bathroom on Aug. 9, 1997. Louima suffered severe 
internal injuries, including a ruptured bladder and colon, and 
spent two months in the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll say something that I've never said before: The jury  
reached the wrong verdict,'' said Stephen Worth, Schwarz's 
attorney. ``I'm sure they were under pressure to convict somebody, 
but they got it wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Louima, 32, was not in the courtroom for the verdict but said  
later that the decision fell short of what he had hoped for. 
Louima, who is suing the city for $155 million, added: ``I am 
confident in the end that complete justice will be done in my case. 
I hope what comes out of my case is change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schwarz was acquitted of beating Louima inside a police car  
before the bathroom attack. Also acquitted in the alleged beating 
were Thomas Wiese, 35, and Thomas Bruder, 33. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did nothing wrong that night,'' Bruder said outside the  
courtroom, where he hugged Wiese. ``I didn't do anything wrong. I 
treated Mr. Louima like a gentleman that night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Louima had testified that Bruder came to his aid after the  
bathroom attack by taking off his handcuffs and helping him dress. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. Michael Bellomo, 37, was acquitted of lying to cover up the  
false arrests of Louima and another Haitian man, who were picked up 
during a melee outside a nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew I didn't do anything wrong, and the jury saw that,''  
Bellomo said outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruder, Wiese and Schwarz still face conspiracy charges for  
allegedly lying to investigators by saying Schwarz was not in the 
bathroom during the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima provided some of the trial's most riveting testimony. He  
testified he was arrested, beaten and finally tortured in a filthy 
bathroom stall -- an account bolstered by the testimony of four 
police officers credited with shattering the blue wall of silence. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial was interrupted on May 25 by Volpe's dramatic guilty  
plea. The stocky, square-jawed patrolman admitted brutalizing 
Louima in the mistaken belief that Louima had sucker-punched him 
outside the nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe's attorney, Marvyn Kornberg, said Tuesday that before the  
plea, Volpe gave prosecutors the name of a second officer he 
claimed was in the bathroom with him -- and that it wasn't Schwarz. 
``They've convicted the wrong man,'' Kornberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Alan Vinegrad would not address Kornberg's claim,  
other to say that Volpe -- as ``the perpetrator of one of the most 
horrific sexual assaults in modern history'' -- was not credible. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Herbert Daughtry, a veteran civil rights activist, said  
he was not disappointed by the split decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've lived with worse than this,'' Daughtry said. ``What it  
says, finally, is that this man told the truth. We keep on 
struggling and maybe next time justice will prevail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir  
praised the officers who stepped foward to testify against their 
colleagues. Giuliani said the police testimony ``made possible the 
convictions.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
