<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Michelle Smith: My Career Is Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- An arbitration panel has rejected  
the claim of Olympic swimming star Michelle Smith de Bruin that 
positive drug samples either were not hers or that a third party 
manipulated the samples. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dublin, Ireland, Smith de Bruin said today the decision meant  
an end to her career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am saddened that my career has ended in this way, but now  
(husband) Erik and I must look to the future and decide where we go 
from here,'' said the triple gold medal winner at the 1996 Atlanta 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement issued by her Dublin lawyer, Peter Lennon, Smith  
insisted her victories ``are not hollow and were achieved without 
the use of any illegal performance-enhancing drugs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The international swimming federation (FINA) banned Smith after  
finding her guilty of contaminating a urine sample with alcohol 
during an out-of-competition test in January 1998. The alcohol 
could mask the presence of banned drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Court of Arbitration for Sport upheld that ban.  
</P>
<P>
	Smith accused FINA of deliberately targeting her and accused the  
three-member CAS arbitration panel of accepting others' 
circumstantial evidence rather than her direct testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will forever cherish my moments of victory and hope that  
those who still believe in me will also cherish their memories of 
those times,'' she said. ``I hope that you will not believe that I 
have brought this country into disrepute or that I have let you 
down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an accompanying statement, her lawyer said Smith would give  
no interviews. He made no mention of any appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Lennon previously raised the possibility of taking the case to  
the European Court for Human Rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith is ineligible for the 2000 Sydney Olympics and the 2001  
world championships. She is 29 years old and will be 33 when the 
ban expires in August 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	FINA said the samples were adulterated with alcohol, possibly  
masking the presence of banned drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-member CAS panel dismissed her contention that the  
burden of proof was on FINA to eliminate all possibilities other 
than manipulation by the swimmer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on the facts of the case and the evidence before them,  
the arbitrators were of the opinion that FINA had convinced them 
that (Smith) was the only person who had the motive and opportunity 
to manipulate the sample,'' the CAS statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling comes 17 months after the disputed test.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's the first time FINA has had a manipulation case,'' Gunnar  
Werner, FINA's honorary secretary, said by telephone from Sweden. 
``Manipulation is a bad crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is more or less two abuses in one -- manipulating samples to  
cover up something else. Hopefully this will warn others not to try 
anything of the same kind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lennon called the 35-page ruling ``fairly comprehensive'' and  
said he will have a statement Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, who emerged from relative obscurity to become one of the  
stars of the 1996 Games, submitted to a surprise, 
out-of-competition drug test at her home in Kilkenny, Ireland, on 
Jan. 10, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	FINA later reported the sample was contaminated with a  
concentration of alcohol so high it would have killed a person had 
it been a legitimate sample. Analysis of the backup sample at an 
IOC laboratory in Barcelona, Spain, confirmed the finding. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith denied any wrongdoing and appealed the ban. She appeared  
at a CAS hearing in Lausanne on May 3-4. Lennon maintained there 
were major flaws in the testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's spectacular results in Atlanta -- winning gold in the  
400-meter medley, 400 freestyle and 200 individual medley, and 
bronze in the 200 butterfly -- led to accusations she used 
performance-enhancing drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	But Smith repeatedly denied doing so. She said she had been  
tested more often than her rivals, and each time the result was 
negative. 
</P>
<P>
	Suspicions were also fueled because of Smith's coach and  
husband. Erik de Bruin, a Dutch discus thrower and shot putter, was 
banned for four years after testing positive for excessive 
testosterone. 
</P>
<P>
	The CAS arbitration panel was led by Yves Fortier of Canada. The  
other arbitrators were lawyers Michael Beloff of Britain and Dennis 
Oswald of Switzerland. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
