<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. May Ease Computer Export Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Clinton administration is making plans to  
ease government restrictions on the sale of high-powered computers 
to more than 100 countries, the Los Angeles Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department has proposed changes in export rules on  
sales to most countries in Asia, Africa, Latin America and Central 
and Eastern Europe, unidentified administration sources told the 
Times. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration, however, will not loosen restrictions on  
China and some 50 other countries, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports of eased controls come just two weeks after a House  
report outlining 20 years of Chinese espionage against the United 
States. A congressional panel, chaired by Rep. Christopher Cox, 
concluded China has been involved in the theft of nuclear secrets 
from U.S. weapons labs -- including culling key military information 
from commercial purchases of high-powered computers and other 
technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials who spoke to the Times on condition of  
anonymity said the White House has not yet determined how much to 
ease controls on computer sales but generally agrees with industry 
assertions that technological advances have surpassed current 
regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials and others have contended the  
increasing availability of high-powered computers from foreign 
countries has prompted U.S. officials to consider a change in 
policy, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government regulates the overseas sale of computers  
based on their speed, measured by how many millions of theoretical 
operations the machines can perform per second. 
</P>
<P>
	To sell to the countries that would be included in the proposed  
export changes, computer makers have to get government licenses for 
any machine that can perform more than 10,000 of the operations per 
second, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the China report's release, Cox said tighter controls on  
technology exports are needed but warned unilateral U.S. action 
would only push China to get the technology elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	The report found that China got some of its high-powered  
computers from third-party nations that resold American products. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
