<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Savior of USS Intrepid Eulogized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- More than 1,000 military officers joined public  
officials, family and friends on the deck of the USS Intrepid to 
remember Zachary Fisher, who saved the battle-scarred World War II 
carrier and turned it into a floating historical museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he never served in the military, Fisher was eulogized  
Monday as a consummate American patriot. Fisher died Friday of 
complications from pneumonia. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	``We honor a true giant among men,'' said Gen. Henry Shelton,  
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. ``As Will Rogers once said, 
`We can't all be heroes. Some of us have to stand on the curb and 
clap as they go by.' Today we stand on the curb, and wave farewell 
as a genuine patriot goes by.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher, a builder and philantrophist who was rejected by the  
Marine Corps in 1942 because of bad knees from years as a 
bricklayer, purchased the Intrepid for $25 million in 1976, saving 
it from demolition. 
</P>
<P>
	He converted it into the world's largest sea-air-space museum.  
The Intrepid, its decks loaded with aircraft and historical 
exhibits, draws hundreds of thousands of visitors a year to its 
Hudson River pier. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher set up scholarships for children of slain military  
personnel, and built 28 Fisher Houses on the grounds of military 
hospitals to house families visiting sick or injured service 
personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Former FBI assistant director James Kallstrom, chairman of the  
Marine Corps Law Enforcement Association, said Fisher, who sat on 
the group's board, was noted for his kindness toward others. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was what Zach was all about,'' Kallstrom said. ``And  
because of the size of his heart and his wealth he could spread 
that goodness in so many locations, and he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York Gov. George Pataki, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Navy  
Secretary Richard Danzig, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill, and Cardinal John 
O'Connor spoke at the three-hour memorial, emceed by former CBS 
newsman Walter Cronkite. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Stern, a longtime friend of Fisher, told how Fisher worked  
to have a black sailor properly credited nearly 50 years later for 
heroism during the 1944 Battle of Leyte Gulf. 
</P>
<P>
	The man had received a lesser medal while several white men  
involved in the same incident were awarded the Navy Cross, the 
second-highest award for valor. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, former President Reagan pinned the Navy Cross on the  
man's chest, and praised Fisher for fighting to see that justice 
was done. 
</P>
<P>
	``I say to you, Zach Fisher, `well done, soldier,''' Reagan  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Colin Powell, the retired chairman of the Joint Chiefs,  
read from Ecclesiastes over Fisher's flag-draped casket, and a 
Marine Corps bugler played ``Taps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A small replica of the Intrepid, carved from a piece of the  
flight deck, was placed in Fisher's casket. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 03:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wilander Finds Tennis Is Fun Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When Mats Wilander reached the top of the tennis  
world, he sounded like the old Peggy Lee song: Is that all there 
is? 
</P>
<P>
	At the age of 17, Wilander became the youngest player to win a  
Grand Slam tournament men's singles title when he captured the 1982 
French Open. Later the same year, he faced John McEnroe for 6 
hours, 39 minutes on carpet in St. Louis -- the longest Davis Cup 
match in history at that time. 
</P>
<P>
	The quiet Swede added two more French Open titles, three  
Australian Opens and a U.S. Open crown. In 1988, he won three of 
the four Grand Slam tournaments and was No. 1 in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``It happened so fast,'' Wilander said from his home in  
Greenwich, Conn. ``It happened easy once. I was motivated to try to 
make it happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fall was even quicker.  
</P>
<P>
	By the end of the following year, he was ranked 12th in the  
world. In December 1990, he was 41st, having skipped the French 
Open and Wimbledon and losing in the first round at the U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	He hung around for a few more years, never a threat in a major  
tournament. Now, he's on the seniors circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Through it all, Wilander says he has had fun.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was never really driven to become No. 1 in the world,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he had a beer with Matt Doyle, a native of Redwood, Calif.,  
who played Davis Cup for Ireland and, with Wilander, was a member 
of the ATP board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Matt said I could become No. 1 if I practiced a little harder  
and trained more,'' Wilander remembered. ``I had never given it a 
thought before. But after that I was more focused. 
</P>
<P>
	``I enjoyed winning. Ivan Lendl liked to beat guys 0-and-1. I  
just liked to beat guys. 
</P>
<P>
	But life at the top wasn't really what Wilander expected -- or  
wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew what it took to become No. 1,'' he said. ``Could I keep  
working this hard and keep focused when I couldn't go up any 
higher. Once you are No. 1, there's only one direction you can 
go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were other things in his life besides tennis. He married a  
fashion model, Sonya, in 1987, just before his big year. If those 
were his highs, he was soon to have a deep loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``My dad got cancer in 1989 and died five months later,''  
Wilander said. 
</P>
<P>
	He missed the French Open and Wimbledon in 1990, skipped  
Wimbledon and the U.S. Open in 1991, sat out the 1992 season before 
playing only the U.S. Open in 1993. It wasn't a career in decline; 
it wasn't even a career at that point. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Wilander showed up again.  
</P>
<P>
	``I played 1993 through '95 and '96,'' he said. ``So I didn't  
expect to do that. I enjoyed that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He retired from the ATP Tour in 1996 -- ``I'm happy I quit,'' he  
said -- and began playing the senior circuit last year. Tennis is 
fun for him once again as he prepares for the Citibank Champions in 
Purchase, N.Y., which begins play tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillermo Vilas, who lost to Wilander in the 1982 French Open,  
takes on Mansour Bahrami in the opening match. Wilander begins 
singles play Wednesday night against John Lloyd. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to all the senior tournaments,'' he said.  
``The level (of play) is getting better and better. McEnroe has 
driven the level up a bit. 
</P>
<P>
	Others in the Citibank Champions field includes fellow Swedes  
Joakim Nystrom and Mikael Pernfors, McEnroe, Jimmy Connors, Johan 
Kriek, Henri Leconte, Eddie Dibbs, Jose Luis Clerc, Tim Wilkison, 
Mel Purcell, Gene Mayer and Andres Gomez. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilander, Connors and McEnroe will be joined by Bjorn Borg on  
June 17-20 for the Quality Challenge in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I started playing on the senior tour, I thought we'd play  
a little golf and then a little tennis. But I got beat 0-and-2 
indoors in Croatia with 6,000 people watching. That's no fun. You 
don't like to lose, period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilander said the competitive juices quickly flow when play  
begins. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first thought is you want to give the people something  
they enjoy,'' he said. ``After the first 15 minutes, I don't care 
what the people think. I want to win. It is more fun to get more 
focused. 
</P>
<P>
	``You do if you really care.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 12:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnston Hired As Ottawa Senators GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OTTAWA (AP) -- Two days after celebrating his 58th birthday,  
Marshall Johnston was hired as general manager of the Ottawa 
Senators on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston was an assistant to Senators GM Rick Dudley last  
season. Dudley was given permission Monday to leave the Senators 
and take over the Tampa Bay Lightning. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston joined the Senators in July 1996 as director of player  
personnel after spending the previous season scouting for the New 
York Islanders. He was director of player personnel for the New 
Jersey Devils from 1983-93. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was a teen-ager, Johnston passed on major junior hockey  
in Canada to attend the University of Denver. After graduating, he 
played for Canada's national team for four years, including the 
1968 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston had a seven-year NHL playing career that did not begin  
until he was 26 in 1968 with the Minnesota North Stars. A 
defenseman, he also played for the California Golden Seals. 
</P>
<P>
	He coached the Golden Seals from 1974-75, then became coach at  
his Denver alma mater for four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	He was made assistant general manager and assistant coach of the  
Colorado Rockies in May 1981 and served as head coach for the final 
56 games in 1981-82. He coached Canada's team at the 1982 World 
Championships, then moved to New Jersey when the Colorado franchise 
shifted that year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 16:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Town Changes Name From Buffalo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, Texas (AP) -- For the third time in five years, this  
town is changing its name for a few days. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993 and 1994, when the Buffalo Bills played the Dallas  
Cowboys in the Super Bowl, city officials ordered all signs with 
``Buffalo'' to be covered up and replaced by the temporary new 
name, ``Blue Star, Texas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, it's the Buffalo Sabres who are playing the Dallas Stars  
for the National Hockey League championship. While the Stanley Cup 
finals are in progress, the town has unofficially been renamed 
``Green Star, Texas,'' and a green star now adorns City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo is on Interstate 45, about 100 miles southeast of  
Dallas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 13:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hormone Benefits May Outweigh Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A study of 37,000 women found that taking  
hormones after menopause does not increase the risk of breast 
cancer, except for some uncommon forms of the disease that are 
slow-growing and highly treatable. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers said the findings are good news because they add to  
evidence that the benefits of hormone supplements outweigh any 
increased risk of breast cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of women take hormones to ease the symptoms of  
menopause, such as hot flashes. The hormones are also known to 
reduce the risk of heart disease, brittle bones and possibly even 
mental decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Previous studies have indicated that women who take hormones --  
specifically estrogen -- after menopause are more likely to develop 
breast cancer. Other studies have found no link. 
</P>
<P>
	This was the first hormone study to categorize cases of breast  
cancer according to whether they were slow-growing or fast-growing. 
</P>
<P>
	``When a woman weighs the risk of breast cancer vs. the benefit  
of possibly reducing cardiovascular disease and reducing risk of 
osteoporosis, this just provides further evidence for the 
benefit,'' said Dr. Susan M. Gapstur, a cancer epidemiologist at 
Northwestern University Medical School in Chicago who led the 
study. 
</P>
<P>
	The study appears in Wednesday's Journal of the American Medical  
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	It may help explain the conflicting data in other studies and  
why hormone takers survive breast cancer more often than 
non-takers. 
</P>
<P>
	``One possible explanation is that they develop more favorable  
tumor types,'' said Dr. Melody A. Cobleigh, director of the 
Comprehensive Breast Center at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical 
Center in Chicago. She was not involved in the study. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers analyzed data on 37,105 subjects enrolled at  
ages 55 to 69 in the Iowa Women's Health Study. Over 11 years 
ending in 1996, a total of 1,520 cases of breast cancer developed 
among the women. 
</P>
<P>
	Women who took hormones and women who didn't had no difference  
in their risk of getting the fast-growing, life-threatening tumors 
that make up 85 percent to 90 percent of all cases of breast 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Women who used hormones for five years or less were 1.8 times  
more likely to have slow-growing, highly curable tumors than women 
who never took hormones. Those who had used hormones for more than 
five years were 2.6 times more likely to have the least-threatening 
tumors. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
