<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Long-Distance Ruling Upheld </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court has upheld a decision  
by federal regulators to block US West and Ameritech from selling 
the long-distance service of Qwest Communications Corp. to local 
phone customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The partnerships were blocked last September by the Federal  
Communications Commission, which said the alliances were illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	US West Communications Inc. and Ameritech Corp., had briefly  
marketed Qwest's long-distance service until they were ordered to 
stop last year. Under pacts between the companies, Qwest paid US 
West and Ameritech an undisclosed recruiting fee for each client in 
the Baby Bells' local phone regions that chooses Qwest for 
long-distance service. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, MCI and other carriers argued that the alliances violated  
a 1996 telecommunications law that forbids Bell companies from 
providing long-distance service to their own customers. The FCC 
agreed, ultimately ruling that the Qwest deals were 
anti-competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	In an opinion released Tuesday by the U.S. Court of Appeals for  
the District of Columbia, a three-judge panel concluded that the 
FCC had acted reasonably. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the (Bell operating companies) could secure this advantage  
without opening their local service markets, the blunting of the 
intended incentive would be considerable -- or so the Commission 
could reasonably find,'' wrote Judge Stephen Williams in the 
group's opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	To provide long-distance service to local customers, a Bell  
company must open its markets to competitors and get FCC approval. 
No Bell has done so. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 00:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> James C. Kopp on Most Wanted List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- James C. Kopp's name and picture will now  
appear all over the world as one of the country's most sought-after 
alleged criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	The subject of a 7-month-old international manhunt, Kopp was  
added Monday to the FBI's Ten Most Wanted List. The anti-abortion 
activist's face will appear in police stations, post offices and on 
the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we are doing is using everything at our disposal,'' U.S.  
Attorney Denise O'Donnell said, ``including now probably the most 
lucrative way of finding a fugitive ... There is little more that 
we can do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kopp has eluded authorities since the sniper slaying of Dr.  
Barnett Slepian, an obstetrician who performed abortions, in the 
doctor's suburban Buffalo home on Oct. 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Kopp, 44, was sought as a witness in the case almost  
immediately, after authorities identified his car in the doctor's 
Amherst neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, investigators identified Kopp as the suspected  
shooter. 
</P>
<P>
	Kopp is charged in state and federal complaints with  
second-degree murder and violating the Freedom of Access to Clinic 
Entrances Act by using deadly force against an abortion doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to the shooting, Kopp traveled the country and world,  
authorities said, spending time in China, Mexico, South America, 
Africa, Poland, England, India, Canada and Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been arrested more than a dozen times during abortion  
protests in New York, Missouri, Georgia, Florida, Pennsylvania, 
West Virginia, Virginia, and Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Since October, authorities have uncovered more than two dozen  
aliases and determined Kopp most recently lived in Vermont, but his 
whereabouts since the shooting are a mystery. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quite honestly, we don't know where he is,'' said Bernard  
Tolbert, special agent-in-charge of the FBI's Buffalo office. 
</P>
<P>
	Kopp is average in height and weight, with red or brown hair and  
blue or gray eyes. He is described as a devout Roman Catholic who 
attends daily Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Amherst Police Chief Frank Olesko said the FBI listing ``puts to  
the forefront how serious a crime we think this is... This person 
is not a hero of any group. He's a criminal. He's a murderer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities noted that of the 454 fugitives placed on the list  
since 1950, 427, or 94 percent, have been captured. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ninety-four percent,'' Erie County District Attorney Frank  
Clark repeated. ``Those are odds I'd bet on any day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The average time spent on the list before capture is 316 days.  
</P>
<P>
	Even with the addition of Kopp, the FBI has room for one more  
fugitive on its list. On Monday night, the leader of the Outlaw 
Motorcycle Club -- also among the Ten Most Wanted -- was captured in 
Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry ``Taco'' Bowman, 49, the Outlaws' international president,  
was arrested in the Detroit area, said FBI special agent Bill Cheek 
in Jacksonville, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	A Tampa-based federal grand jury indicted Bowman in August 1997.  
He was charged with murder, bombing, drug dealing, racketeering and 
conspiracy. Bowman faces several life sentences if convicted. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich: Slow Social Security Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich would slow the growth of  
Social Security benefits by no longer adjusting the tables for 
calculating them to reflect wage increases in society, sources 
familiar with the GOP presidential candidate's plan, said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the  
proposal Kasich is scheduled to unveil Wednesday would change the 
initial calculation of Social Security benefits made when a person 
first retires based on their average lifetime wages. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ohio congressman is alone among the GOP presidential  
hopefuls to call for trimming Social Security benefits to future 
retirees in exchange for letting them divert a portion of their 
Social Security taxes to personal retirement accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Individuals with different earnings histories would continue to  
get different-sized benefit checks, the sources familiar with his 
proposal said Tuesday. And the benefits would continue to rise 
annually based on price inflation as measured by the Consumer Price 
Index. 
</P>
<P>
	But the entire sliding scale of benefits would no longer shift  
upward as wages rise over-all, the sources said. They wouldn't 
offer more details. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kasich's goal is to provide a retirement system for the baby  
boom that Generation X can still afford,'' said one source close to 
the House Budget Committee chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Republican presidential candidates and congressional  
leaders also have endorsed the idea of letting workers invest some 
of their Social Security taxes in private accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kasich is the only one suggesting that baby boomers accept  
smaller benefit checks in exchange for being allowed to divert part 
of their Social Security taxes to potentially more lucrative but 
also riskier stock market accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich's plan would allow workers now under age 55 to  
voluntarily divert some of their Social Security taxes into private 
accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The lowest-wage workers would be allowed to divert up to 3.5  
percent of their wages -- or about half of their employee Social 
Security taxes -- into the private retirement accounts. Workers 
earning more than the maximum income taxed by Social Security -- 
$72,600 in 1999 -- would be allowed to divert only 1 percent of 
their wages. 
</P>
<P>
	The benefit changes in Kasich's proposal would affect the Social  
Security checks of baby boomers and younger Americans, but not 
anyone now over age 55. Annual cost-of-living increases retirees 
get based on price inflation would not be affected. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of his strategy to set himself apart from the crowded  
GOP field, Kasich again called for Republicans to begin targeting 
corporate subsidies in federal spending and the tax code. 
</P>
<P>
	``As I like to say, we reformed welfare for poor people, we  
ought to reform it for the rich,'' he said. ``It's a matter of 
will; it's a matter of attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich appeared with the head of the anti-spending group  
Citizens Against Government Waste, which unveiled the latest 
installment of its annual ``Prime Cuts'' list of recommended fat to 
cut from the federal budget. 
</P>
<P>
	High on this year's list was the Advanced Technology Program,  
Overseas Private Investment Corp. and the Trade and Development 
Agency, which the taxpayer group said could be eliminated at a 
savings of $2 billion over five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The taxpayer group characterized the Advanced Technology Program  
as ``welfare for techies'' that funnels millions of taxpayer 
dollars to Fortune 500 companies every year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nothing but corporate welfare,'' Kasich said. ``I don't  
think there's one single project that has ever gone from the 
Advanced Technology Program to reality.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 09:16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  India Offers To Hold Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- India offered today to hold peace talks with  
Pakistan this weekend, a move that came as its warplanes and troops 
struck against hundreds of fighters India says Pakistan has sent 
into the mountains of Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	A Foreign Ministry statement said Pakistan's foreign minister  
would be welcome on Saturday, countering a proposal by Islamabad 
for Sartaj Aziz to come to New Delhi on Monday, which India called 
``inconvenient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indian Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh is scheduled to leave for  
China on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Islamabad, Pakistani Information Minister Mushahid Hussein  
informed the upper house of parliament of India's offer. He did not 
say if Pakistan would accept the date. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistani Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said his government would  
reply to the Indian offer later today. And he said the one-point 
agenda for the talks set by India was a problem and that there 
should be ``no preconditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee made clear the talks  
would be confined to ending the confrontation on India's northern 
frontier and not other issues dividing the two rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	In a televised speech to the nation Monday, Vajpayee accused  
Pakistan of sending its soldiers across the cease-fire line ``to 
occupy our territory'' in Indian-held Kashmir. Pakistan accused 
India of going ``on the warpath'' by spurning its earlier offer of 
talks. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan have fought three wars, two of them over  
Kashmir, since they won independence from Britain in 1947. India 
now controls two-thirds of the former princely state. 
</P>
<P>
	Islamabad denies its troops are involved in the fighting and  
claims the fighters are secessionist Kashmiri rebels from India. 
</P>
<P>
	Western nations have asked the two new nuclear powers to show  
restraint, fearing the fighting could escalate. 
</P>
<P>
	Artillery shells continued to rain on both sides of the  
Himalayan frontier. India has kept reporters away from the battle 
zone amid preparations for what front-line officers described as an 
all-out assault to push the intruders off the snow-peaked mountains 
they have occupied since early May. 
</P>
<P>
	India's casualty toll stood at 60 dead, 217 wounded and 14  
missing since early May. The military says 221 Pakistani soldiers 
and an unknown number of others have also been killed so far in air 
and ground strikes around Kargil. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighting is taking place 440 miles north of New Delhi, the  
Indian capital. 
</P>
<P>
	In his address, Vajpayee demanded Pakistan remove the guerrilla  
fighters or have Indian troops evict them forcibly. ``It is our 
duty to rid our Motherland of every single intruder,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 19:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Choose Life' License Plates in Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- ``Choose Life,'' two words carrying an  
emotionally charged message about abortion, will be on some Florida 
license plates under a bill signed today by Gov. Jeb Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Money raised by sales of the $20 specialty plate, which bears a  
crayon drawing of children, will go to support organizations that 
serve pregnant women who plan to put their babies up for adoption. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea had been vetoed last year by the late Gov. Lawton  
Chiles, a Democrat, but Bush had promised to sign it into law. 
</P>
<P>
	``This shows the complete difference in leadership we have  
here,'' said Matt Ozolnieks, vice president of Florida Right to 
Life, which lobbied for the plate. ``This is a real good 
opportunity for those concerned for women in crisis pregnancies to 
offer help and hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But opponents argue it bears a divisive political message, one  
some feel so strongly about it could even spark road rage. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't put a political slogan on a license plate,''  
Democratic state Sen. Howard Forman. ``Now the taxpayers are paying 
for a political slogan with the imprimatur of the state of 
Florida.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 09:16:02 </DATE_TIME>
