<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Safety Device Unlocks Car Trunk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking to avoid deaths in car trunks, General  
Motors Corp. will equip most of its four-door family cars with an 
infrared sensing device that automatically unlocks the trunk if 
anyone is trapped inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year during extreme summer heat, 11 children died after  
crawling into trunks to play and shutting the lids. 
</P>
<P>
	GM's automatic trunk-opening feature will be standard on the  
Chevrolet Impala next year and will be phased in on most of GM's 
four-door cars by 2002, GM officials said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The GM system uses infrared technology to detect both motion in  
the trunk and the ``heat signature'' of humans by searching for 
objects that are a different temperature than the trunk. The 
infrared system would pop open the trunk lid only if both the 
motion and heat sensor indicated a person could be in the trunk and 
the car is in park. 
</P>
<P>
	The GM cars also will have a handle inside the trunk for trapped  
passengers to release the trunk lid manually. And engineers plan to 
include a distinctive horn sequence -- perhaps three honks in a row 
from the driver horn followed by a pause -- to signal a passenger is 
trapped in the trunk. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1970, 1,175 people have been victims in 992 trunk  
entrapments -- mostly adults locked in by criminals or children who 
unintentionally locked themselves in, according to a recent study. 
At least 260 people have died. 
</P>
<P>
	The majority of the deaths involved a violent abduction. But it  
was the tragic deaths of children playing in trunks last year that 
prompted a federal safety agency, the National Highway Traffic 
Safety Administration, to start searching for ways to prevent trunk 
entrapment deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	The expert panel appointed by the agency to study the problem  
recommends that all new cars have a release mechanism inside the 
trunk by 2001. The panel's study said temperatures inside a trunk 
could soar over 130 degrees after being parked only 15 minutes in 
the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	GM, Ford Motor Co. and DaimlerChrysler AG are all working on  
some sort of standard trunk-release system. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Motor Co. will have a T-shaped handle that glows inside the  
trunk as a standard feature on most of its 2000 models. 
</P>
<P>
	Since March, GM has been installing manual handles into the  
trunks of cars already on the road as optional equipment at the 
dealership for about $50. GM's yellow handle is illuminated in the 
dark cargo area. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of DaimlerChrysler AG's Chrysler and Dodge cars will have a  
similar optional kit within a month. DaimlerChrysler also plans to 
make trunk releases a standard feature for new cars by 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	However, GM said that in its research to develop a trunk handle  
children could easily identify and use, company officials 
discovered that some children would not try very hard to get out of 
the trunk. 
</P>
<P>
	Children ages 3 to 7 successfully found the handle on their own  
and escaped only about half the time. The youngest children 
experienced the most trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	So GM decided to use the infrared technology to create an  
automatic system to help kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sounds like a good idea, a good approach,'' said William  
Boehly, a member of the panel on trunks and a former top NHTSA 
official. ``We're dealing with a lot of unknows,'' he said, when it 
comes to determining how children will react in trunks. 
</P>
<P>
	Alma Rohan -- the aunt of four young cousins, ages 2 to 6, who  
died in the trunk of a Pontiac Grand Am last July in New Mexico -- 
said an infrared automatic trunk release was a good idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``Children that age don't know to look for a handle,'' she said  
in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Rohan also said most people do not believe their children  
would be trapped in a trunk, so they would be unlikely to teach 
them to look for a release mechanism. ``You teach kids about drugs 
and weapons, not to look for a button in the trunk,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once GM's system detects motion, there is a short time delay,  
roughly 2 minutes, before the trunk pops open. The wait is designed 
in part to allow adults who are forced into trunks at gunpoint a 
chance to escape by delaying the opening of the trunk until after a 
criminal has fled. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're concerned not only about entrapped children but adults  
abducted at gunpoint against their will. We had to balance those 
needs,'' said GM spokesman William J. Kemp Jr. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
