<HEADLINE> Monk Punished for Scratching Coffin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMER, Mass. (AP) -- A monk was ordered to perform 100 hours of  
community service for scratching a cross on a young man's coffin 
before it was lowered into the grave. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement with prosecutors, Dell Scott Goodwin, 42,  
acknowledged today that they had enough evidence to convict him of 
vandalizing a gravesite and destruction of property. The charges 
will be dismissed within a year if he stays out of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	He could have gotten five years in jail if convicted.  
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin is known as Father Lazarus at St. Nectarios Monastery in  
Brimfield, which follows many Eastern Orthodox traditions. 
</P>
<P>
	The monk said he used a rock to carve a cross and Greek  
religious letters into the coffin of 17-year-old Christopher Martel 
after a graveside Roman Catholic service for the young man in 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy's family was appalled by what it considered to be the  
coffin's desecration. 
</P>
<P>
	Martel had been killed by a hit-and-run driver, and Goodwin, who  
knew the young man, had been one of the first on the scene of the 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodwin's lawyer, Gregory Hession, said the monk was overcome  
with grief and should have asked the family's permission. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:30:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Links Day Care To Readiness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The best of day care can help children do well  
later in school, but those in low-quality care tend to have poorer 
language and math skills, says a six-year study by a team of 
college researchers. 
</P>
<P>
	The study, which followed more than 400 children from day care  
through second grade, also found that high-quality day care helped 
children in the long run as well as short term. Saying that good 
day care helped needy children the most, the research team 
recommended that the states and Congress spend more money on day 
care programs, worker training and salaries and tax credits for 
working parents, especially those leaving welfare rolls. 
</P>
<P>
	The full day care centers, which included Head Start, nonprofit  
and for-profit centers, were scored by how much attention a child 
got from workers, how much and how well they played with other 
children, and whether the children had plentiful and safe 
furnishings, toys, books and other learning materials, said Ellen 
Peisner-Feinberg, a University of North Carolina researcher. 
</P>
<P>
	The success in early learning and school readiness report was  
released Tuesday at a news conference, with Education Secretary 
Richard Riley and the researchers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The quality of experiences in the early years matters,'' Riley  
said. But, he added, ``child care facilities that meet high 
standards and offer employees a livable wage remain woefully 
inadequate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers from the University of North Carolina; the  
University of California, Los Angeles; the University of Colorado; 
and Yale University found that children in low-quality care tended 
to score lower on tests measuring their language and math skills. 
</P>
<P>
	The lowest-quality care accounted for about 11 percent of the  
day care studied. Nearly a quarter was judged high quality. 
Concrete factors such as child-teacher ratio or teacher salary can 
predict a good setting, but not guarantee it, said 
Peisner-Feinberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Without offering exact dollar figures, Richard Clifford, another  
UNC researcher, said the best day care tended to cost twice as much 
as the worst. Good programs could be found in the public and 
private sectors, researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers also concluded that good day care:  
</P>
<P>
	--Made children less likely to misbehave in later years,  
particularly if they were in centers where most children got along. 
</P>
<P>
	--Gave children better social and learning skills regardless of  
the quality of their kindergarten and second-grade classes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Made the most difference for children who were poor or whose  
mothers were less-educated than other children's mothers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration wants to increase tax breaks that  
moderate-income parents get for paying child-care expenses for 
children under 13 and create a new tax credit for employers to 
provide daycare for their workers. Republican leaders have similar 
proposals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charity Theft Prompts Cameras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The charity Feed the Children will  
install surveillance cameras to prevent employee theft at its 
Nashville warehouse after staff members were videotaped by a TV 
station taking boxes of donated goods home. 
</P>
<P>
	Feed the Children fired all 14 Nashville employees a week ago,  
and the warehouse has been closed while the charity takes an 
inventory of how much is missing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Up to this point it was like considering putting a camera in a  
church,'' Feed the Children spokeswoman Emilee Truelove said 
Tuesday. ``We've just had a level of trust that's no longer 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Nashville alarm company is donating the nearly $20,000  
security system and installing it for free. 
</P>
<P>
	During a four-month investigation, WTVF secretly videotaped  
administrative staffers carting boxes of clothes, food, toiletries 
and more to their cars and homes. The items had been donated to the 
poor. 
</P>
<P>
	District Attorney Torry Johnson said he is awaiting the results  
of a state investigation before deciding whether to file charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Truelove said that Feed the Children will also increase  
security at its Oklahoma warehouse but that the charity knows of no 
thefts there. 
</P>
<P>
	The closure of the Nashville office has prevented 201 agencies  
in 20 states from getting food from the charity. The states are 
Tennessee, West Virginia, Kentucky, Georgia, Illinois, Virginia, 
Alabama, Arkansas, New York, Texas, Oklahoma, California, Missouri, 
North Carolina, South Carolina, Ohio, Massachusetts, Mississippi, 
South Dakota and Minnesota. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990608.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 17:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Didn't Obtain Lab Visit Licenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Energy Department has failed to issue  
required licenses for extended laboratory visits by foreign 
nationals who may come in contact with sensitive information, a 
report concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's inspector general found that the system isn't  
working because it relies on U.S. sponsors of the foreign visitors 
to apply for the licenses. The sponsors often are confused about 
when a license is needed, said the report, obtained Tuesday by The 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The report was prepared for the Senate Governmental Affairs  
Committee, which has scheduled a hearing for Thursday on department 
export controls. 
</P>
<P>
	A special House committee last month detailed a 20-year campaign  
by China to steal nuclear secrets and criticized lax security at 
the Energy Department laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department, in a response attached to the inspector  
general's findings, said it is updating its export guidelines, 
which ``will, among other things, clarify requirements'' for the 
laboratory visits. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new policy will clarify where export control review  
responsibility lies ... and ensure that consideration of export 
license requirements is part of the visits and assignments 
process,'' the response said. 
</P>
<P>
	A so-called ``deemed export license'' is required for visits by  
foreign nationals who might gain access to information or 
technology that would require a license if shipped to the foreign 
country. Examples are information that could have a dual military 
and civilian use, and technologies that are regulated by the State 
Department through placement on a ``munitions list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report reviewed the license system for visits of at least 30  
days to four laboratories: Los Alamos and Sandia in New Mexico, 
Lawrence Livermore in California and Oak Ridge in Tennessee. The 
report did not consider whether the foreigners should have been at 
the labs in the first place. 
</P>
<P>
	Inspector General Gregory H. Friedman found that neither Energy  
nor Commerce Department guidance ``was clear regarding when a 
deemed export license would be required for an assignment involving 
a foreign national.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sponsors of the visitors, known as ``hosts,'' were relied  
upon to determine whether export concerns were raised by the visits 
-- but ``several hosts were not aware of, or did not understand, the 
requirements,'' the report found. 
</P>
<P>
	``We found ... that 13 of the 17 hosts we interviewed said that  
they were not responsible for making this determination,'' Friedman 
found. ``In addition, when asked who certifies that no license is 
required, four of the 17 hosts said that they did not know or were 
not sure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the uncertainty over the need for licenses, five hosts  
at Oak Ridge said the six foreign nationals they were hosting were 
affiliated with a nuclear facility or ``nuclear end-user in their 
home countries,'' the report said. ``However, none of these hosts 
had considered applying for deemed export licenses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A contractor at the Livermore lab told investigators that  
laboratory employees ``routinely struggle to try to determine if 
and when a deemed export license might be required.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others said their names were officially listed as the hosts of  
record, but the actual sponsors were others. In one case a Chinese 
national was the actual host of another Chinese national, despite a 
requirement that the host be a U.S. citizen. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, an advisory board said in a report Tuesday that the  
Energy Department's foreign visitor program ``is invaluable to this 
country'' and should be continued. 
</P>
<P>
	``International scientific collaborations with foreign  
governments and scientists for research and development ... support 
the department's diverse mission areas of national security, energy 
resources, science and environmental quality,'' said the secretary 
of energy's advisory board. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson in March asked the advisory  
panel to examine the issue of foreign visitor exchanges involving 
the government's research laboratories. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
