<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Farmers Oppose Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Gray with age, a group of farmers who've been  
blocking efforts to build and expand a Tokyo airport for more than 
30 years are vowing to fight on against government plans to 
complete the project. 
</P>
<P>
	The farmers -- some of whose land stands in the path of a planned  
second runway for the overcrowded airport 40 miles from Tokyo in 
Narita -- said it was unlikely they'd ever sell the plots where they 
grow organic crops like cucumbers, onions and peanuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they should give up on Narita,'' said landowner Shoji  
Shimamura, 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Shimamura, an egg farmer, and the others have resisted the  
airport ever since the government announced in 1966 that it wanted 
to build an international travel hub in what was then a sleepy 
village. 
</P>
<P>
	Clashes erupted back then between police and hundreds of farmers  
who opposed the project, backed by hundreds of leftist students. 
</P>
<P>
	The airport finally opened in 1978 -- seven years behind schedule  
and with only one of three planned runways. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have been trying ever since to buy or force out the  
farmers to make way for a badly needed second runway. 
</P>
<P>
	Many farmer's have given in and left. Only nine still refuse to  
budge, maintaining their farms in the shadows of the hulking 
terminals and roaring jets. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the airport's use has surged. More than 340 flights  
arrive and depart every day, carrying 70,000 passengers and 4,000 
tons of freight. 
</P>
<P>
	After promising to finish the runway in time for the 2002 World  
Cup soccer tournament, the government said last month that it had 
enough land to go ahead with a shortened version. 
</P>
<P>
	The farmers point out that at 7,200 feet, the runway won't be  
long enough for the bigger jets used on international flights. 
</P>
<P>
	``To us, the proposed runway is an act of intimidation, a crude  
attempt by the government to coerce farmers opposing the airport 
into leaving their community,'' said farmer Noriko Ishii, who 
declined to give her age. 
</P>
<P>
	The farmers said they'll carry on despite the inconvenience it  
means for the area's 30 million other residents because they want 
to teach the government a lesson for using heavy-handed tactics to 
force them off their land. 
</P>
<P>
	``The single biggest cause is the fact that the government never  
once consulted residents before going ahead with the airport,'' 
said Kiyonori Hirano, 53, who works at a pickle plant that the 
government hopes to tear down to make way for the second runway. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see ourselves as fighting for democracy in Japan.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
