<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM-Microsoft Relations Outlined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Stung by courtroom claims that it sought  
illegally to pressure IBM Corp., Microsoft will point to IBM's 
efforts to disparage its Windows software at the same time IBM was 
scrambling to secure a contract to sell Windows on its computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft Corp. argues that IBM's apparently contradictory  
behavior illustrates the complex relationship between the two 
companies, which worked closely as partners in some areas but 
remained bitter rivals in others. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft was expected today to begin questioning Garry Norris,  
an IBM manager and the government's next-to-last witness in its 
antitrust case. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris accused the software company Monday of offering IBM  
discounts worth tens of millions of dollars to sacrifice its rival 
OS/2 computer operating system. He said Microsoft also urged IBM to 
stop distributing software from key competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, in turn, argued outside court that it never sought to  
have IBM to embrace Windows exclusively, and that IBM continues to 
this day to distribute rival software on its popular line of 
desktops and portable Thinkpad machines. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris testified that Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates was so angry  
about IBM's defiance that he overheard Gates screaming during a 
private phone call in July 1995 to another IBM executive in the 
room. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was pretty loud,'' Norris said, eliciting laughter from a  
crowded federal courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris, who negotiated key agreements in 1995 and 1996,  
testified that IBM saw the total fees it pays to Microsoft rise 
from $40 million in 1996 to $440 million last year because it 
rejected Microsoft's alleged overtures not to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who will decide the  
verdict later this year, appeared to follow Norris' testimony 
closely. He frequently took notes, asked minor questions for 
clarification and studied e-mails and other documents on a large 
projection screen in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Norris is a crucial witness because none of the nation's major  
computer makers previously had been willing to testify in court in 
support of government allegations that Microsoft uses the prices 
for its dominant Windows operating system to punish enemies and 
reward allies. 
</P>
<P>
	But as Microsoft opens its cross-examination of Norris, it wants  
the judge to consider its overall relationship with IBM, not just 
its dealings with IBM's personal computer division. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft says that even as IBM was negotiating a lower price  
for Windows, it launched a national advertising campaign to 
disparage the operating system by comparing it to the latest 
versions of its own OS/2 software, which it considered more robust. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, during the same period, IBM purchased Lotus Development  
Corp. -- one of Microsoft's biggest software rivals -- and promised 
to distribute the Lotus SmartSuite software, not Microsoft's 
lucrative Office software, on IBM computers. 
</P>
<P>
	The government showed IBM e-mail describing Microsoft's Joachim  
Kempin as ``definitely worried about SmartSuite being given away 
and eating into their 'Office heartland.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Other IBM initiatives have included Lotus Notes, which competes  
with Microsoft's Exchange mail software; Java, the programming 
language that Microsoft believed threatened to undermine Windows; 
and Network Computers, which deliberately don't require Microsoft's 
operating system to run. 
</P>
<P>
	``It becomes very clear that Microsoft and IBM are direct  
competitors in at least 85 percent of Microsoft's total business,'' 
Kempin wrote to his counterpart at IBM in January 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The government accuses Microsoft of illegally wielding its  
influence over Windows to arm-twist lucrative concessions from 
IBM's PC Co. and other computer makers. But Microsoft, in turn, 
describes the IBM computer division as caught between loyalty to 
other IBM initiatives and its own efforts to negotiate low prices 
for Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's top executives ``were sensitive to the challenges  
that the (IBM) PC Company were experiencing,'' said Mark Baber, the 
former Microsoft employee in charge of negotiations with IBM. 
``They had a very complex set of issues to deal with on their 
side.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
